<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 00:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Assembly Democrats to back two-month waiver of state gas tax  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- People endeavoring to get to the beautiful,
though far-flung, vacation destinations in New York deserve a break
this summer from high gasoline prices, Democrats in the state
Assembly say.
</P>
<P>
   The Assembly will propose this week eliminating the state's 4
percent sales tax on gasoline for about two months at the height of
tourism season this summer. That would cost the state some $60
million, but Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver said it might also
keep tourists coming to eastern Long Island, the Adirondack and
Catskill mountains, the Finger Lakes, the Thousand Islands, the
Great Lakes, Lake Champlain, Niagara Falls and other summer
showcases in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The vast majority of people vacationing in those areas must
drive there instead of taking commercial transportation.
</P>
<P>
   ''We think it's important to our upstate tourism industry and to
working men and women who are using cars to get to and from work,''
Silver, a Manhattan Democrat, said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Assembly Democratic proposal will call for the state portion
of the gas tax to be waived starting with the Fourth of July
weekend and to go back into force at the conclusion of the Labor
Day holiday. The proposal will give counties and municipalities
which also impose a local gas tax -- their add-ons are generally
between 3 percent and 4 percent -- the option of also waiving their
levies.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal is similar to the state's elimination of its
portion of sales taxes on clothing purchases worth $110 or less.
That went into effect on March 1. A handful of localities -- most
significantly New York City -- also decided to give up their portion
of sales taxes on those purchases.
</P>
<P>
   The Assembly gas tax proposal will be included in the budget
resolution for the 2000-01 state fiscal year which the
Democrat-dominated Assembly plans to pass Wednesday, aides to
Silver said. Republicans who control the state Senate plan to pass
their own resolution this week, creating the possibility of
conference committees being convened to work out the remaining
details on a spending plan for the fiscal year which begins April
1.
</P>
<P>
   The Assembly proposal would keep state taxes on diesel fuel,
used by trucks, other commercial vehicles and a small percentage of
passenger cars, in place.
</P>
<P>
   New Yorkers have been hit hard with a double whammy of sorts on
energy prices. OPEC's decision to curtail oil production caused
crude oil prices to climb, and a harsh stretch of weather in
January and early February caused the price of home heating oil to
soar in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Gasoline prices have followed suit, with unleaded regular now
routinely costing $1.50 or more a gallon. Some predict that prices
will continue to escalate into the summer tourist months, Silver
said.
</P>
<P>
   Silver also said he would release today a letter asking state
Attorney General Eliot Spitzer to investigate possible gasoline
price-gouging in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ''The prices of crude oil went up significantly, but the prices
at the pump have gone up more significantly,'' Silver said.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Spitzer, Darren Dopp, said Sunday the attorney
general has found recent instances where home heating oil suppliers
had failed to honor the contracted price of oil with their
customers.
</P>
<P>
   However, Dopp said that where global market forces are at work
such as OPEC production quotas and a national cold snap, ''it may
be that factors driving prices up are not technically illegal.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We will review it (Silver's request) carefully,'' Dopp said.
''We do have an ongoing review of the dramatic rise in energy
prices and whenever we find instances of companies breaking the law
we are acting aggressively. But we have to counsel that the
(price-gouging) law itself ... is not clear in the state in regards
to gasoline. It is clear in regards to milk.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-13-00 0011 </TRAILER>
