<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 01:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Salvador Rebels Claim Election Win  </HEADLINE>
By MARCOS ALEMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) -- The country's leftist former
rebels won renewed control of the capital in elections Sunday and
held a razor-thin lead over the rightist governing party in the
congressional vote.
</P>
<P>
   Incumbent Hector Silva of the Farabundo Marti National
Liberation Front proclaimed victory in San Salvador -- the most
important of 262 mayoral races in the nationwide elections.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am here to confirm the victory,'' Silva, a 53-year-old
Boston-born gynecologist, said during a news conference. His
victory three years ago was the biggest electoral boost the Front
has yet achieved in the country.
</P>
<P>
   With 67 percent of the vote counted in the capital, Silva had 56
percent of the vote to 39 percent for Luis Cardenal of the
Nationalist Republican Alliance, or ARENA, that governs the
country.
</P>
<P>
   The Front, known as the FMLN, also was barely leading the
Alliance in voting for 84 congressional seats. With 22.7 percent of
the vote counted, it had 39 percent to 38 percent for the Alliance.
</P>
<P>
   A center-left party, the Democratic Center Union, was running
third with 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently worried by pre-election poll results, President
Francisco Flores earlier Sunday urged Salvadorans to vote against
''those who opposed the establishment of our democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Flores' comments outraged the FMLN, which became a political
party following the January 1992 peace accord that ended a 12-year
civil war in which 76,000 people died.
</P>
<P>
   ''What President Flores is doing is prohibited; he is not acting
as president. He is nothing more than a (party) campaign
activist,'' said Schafick Handal, a former guerrilla commander who
is seeking re-election to congress.
</P>
<P>
   But as the polls closed at 5 p.m., he expressed confidence that
the FMLN and its center-left allies would make significant gains.
</P>
<P>
   ''There will be a new balance of power in El Salvador,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Silva's victory three years ago in the capital was the biggest
electoral boost the Front had yet achieved in the country.
</P>
<P>
   While the leftist party calls for halting the government's
privatization program, it has also called for cutting taxes and
tightening anti-corruption laws.
</P>
<P>
   Electoral officials said fewer than 50 percent of the 3 million
eligible voters turned out to cast ballots for congressmen, mayors
and 20 representatives to the Central American Parliament. Eight
parties were participating.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-13-00 0104 </TRAILER>
