<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 01:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taiwan Just Wants To Be Left Alone  </HEADLINE>
By MARCOS CALO MEDINA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) -- Li Pao-luan hoists her two toddlers into a
rusty truck and grabs her microphone. Her husband twirls the
mallets he uses to beat a huge drum as the couple prepares to do
something that was once illegal.
</P>
<P>
   Festooned with banners that read ''Taiwan Independence,'' the
vehicle with a cracked windshield begins cruising Taipei's narrow
streets. Through a scratchy speaker, Li yells, ''From this time on
we must be independent!''
</P>
<P>
   The couple is among a growing number of Taiwanese who think this
tobacco leaf-shaped island 80 miles off China's east coast should
be an independent nation and not reunify with the mainland. It is a
sentiment that causes China's communist regime in Beijing to warn
of war.
</P>
<P>
   But while many Taiwanese agree with the idea, people haven't
rushed to join the Lis' tiny Association for Taiwan Independence,
nor has there been a clamor to make independence a central issue in
Sunday's presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   None of the three major candidates is promising independence,
and months ago the fringe Independence Party dropped out of the
race because it couldn't collect enough petition signatures to get
its candidate on the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Although many people don't want to reunify with China, they are
reluctant to support a politician who aggressively campaigns for
independence. The reason is simple: China's repeated threats to
attack Taiwan if it tries to break away permanently.
</P>
<P>
   By declaring independence, Taiwan would risk losing the de facto
sovereignty it has enjoyed since the island broke away from the
mainland during the civil war 50 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''People will not dare say the word 'independence,' but I still
have hope in the future,'' says Su Beng, an 84-year-old activist
who once fled to Japan when the independence movement was outlawed
during Taiwan's martial law era.
</P>
<P>
   ''Taiwan and China were never really one country. Historically,
both societies developed separately,'' Su says.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past 100 years, a government in China has ruled Taiwan
for only four years. The island was a Japanese colony for about 50
years until the end of World War II. Since 1945, it has been
governed by the Nationalist Party, which fled the mainland after
the communists won the civil war.
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan's official policy is that it will seek gradual
reunification with China once the mainland is democratic and more
economically advanced.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Beijing issued a new warning that it would use force
if Taiwan indefinitely dragged its feet on reunification talks.
</P>
<P>
   It's these marry-me-or-die threats that are driving more
Taiwanese to favor independence, says Taiwan's Mainland Affairs
Council, which handles China policy.
</P>
<P>
   A survey commissioned by the council said an all-time high of 45
percent of the island's people consider themselves Taiwanese, not
Chinese. Only 14 percent of those polled said they were Chinese,
and 40 percent said they were both Chinese and Taiwanese.
</P>
<P>
   The Taipei-based Burke Marketing Research firm interviewed 1,067
people Feb. 23-26 -- after China issued its new threat. The poll had
a margin of error of 3 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about ties with China, the biggest segment -- 35 percent --
favored maintaining the status quo and considering unification at
an unspecified later date. About 19 percent wanted to keep the
status quo forever, and another 19 favored eventual unification.
</P>
<P>
   About 12 percent favored gradual independence and about 6
percent wanted immediate independence. Only 2 percent favored
immediate reunification.
</P>
<P>
   Koo Kuang-ming, brother of Taipei's chief negotiator with China,
is skeptical that talks with China would lead to reunification.
</P>
<P>
   ''Basically, there's no way to negotiate,'' says the 74-year-old
tycoon who can trace his ancestry back hundreds of years to a
village in central Taiwan. ''Twenty-three million people here have
made it clear that they will not accept China's proposals.''
</P>
<P>
   The longer the two sides stay apart, the harder it might be to
reunify. It's becoming fashionable for young Taiwanese to explore
and develop their own culture, one with fewer ties to the mainland.
</P>
<P>
   Bookstore owner Wu Cheng-san is trying to feed the growing
appetite for things Taiwanese. His store near the elite National
Taiwan University sells previously banned pro-independence
literature, sculptures from Taiwan's indigenous minorities and
tapes to learn Taiwan's local dialect.
</P>
<P>
   ''In our hearts, we know we are an independent country,'' Wu
says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
