<DOCNO> APW20000313.0008 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 01:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pope Seeks Pardon for Catholics  </HEADLINE>
By JULIA LIEBLICH, AP Religion Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   VATICAN CITY (AP) -- It was what Pope John Paul II didn't say
during a solemn Day of Pardon Mass that has elicited the most
impassioned responses. While many welcome the pope's appeal for
God's forgiveness, some had hoped for more explicit apologies.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's chief rabbi, Meir Lau, said he was ''deeply
frustrated'' by the pope's failure to mention the Holocaust in the
eagerly awaited ''mea culpa'' Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   A Catholic mission that ministers to the Roma, or Gypsies, in
Rome, asked: ''Why is the Holocaust of the Gypsies not mentioned?''
</P>
<P>
   At Sunday's special Mass, the pope asked God's forgiveness for
the sins of Catholics through the ages, including wrongs inflicted
on Jews, women, and minorities. But he spoke mostly in general
terms, not mentioning the Holocaust, the Inquisition or Crusades by
name and listing few specific groups.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. John Pawlikowski, professor of social ethics at
Catholic Theological Union in Chicago, said the pope ''pushed the
envelope far as he could, given the opposition to the apology''
among Catholics who feared tarnishing the church's reputation.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Pawlikowski, who participated in a 1998 closed-door
Vatican meeting to advise the pope on the pardon and Judaism, said
he would have preferred more direct language.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would have liked the pope to express regret for the
centuries of anti-Judaic teaching that has been conveyed through
preaching, catechesis and religious art,'' Pawlikowski said. And he
would have liked the pope to state that some people who committed
sins against Jews ''were leaders of the highest level.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the criticism, the apology was a personal landmark for
the frail, 79-year-old pope, who vowed to cleanse and reinvigorate
Catholicism for its third millennium.
</P>
<P>
   John Paul and the five cardinals and two bishops who also
delivered the confession of sins with him were dressed in heavy
purple robes, the color of penitence. The pope leaned on his silver
staff, his voice clear but his hands trembling, a symptom of
Parkinson's.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the confessions, he embraced a large crucifix on
the altar for the special Mass, imploring God's forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinal Edward Cassidy recalled the ''sufferings of the people
of Israel'' and asked divine pardon for ''the sins committed by not
a few (Catholics) against the people of the Covenant.''
</P>
<P>
   After a moment of silent prayer, the pope responded: ''We are
deeply saddened by the behavior of those who in the course of
history have caused these children of yours to suffer, and asking
your forgiveness we wish to commit ourselves to genuine
brotherhood.''
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to women's issues, Sister Donna Quinn, director of
Chicago Catholic Women, said she is less concerned about the
language used to discuss discrimination than the actions that
follow.
</P>
<P>
   If the pope ''is sincerely asking for forgiveness, he would have
to change the policies of the Catholic Church that discriminate
against women, such as ordination,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Garcia, director of Equality Illinois, a gay civil rights
group, said he ''was deeply touched'' that Cardinal Roger M. Mahony
of Los Angeles discussed gays and lesbians in his public apology
last week, but was not surprised that the pope did not.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think that Rome is willing to make amends for the
horrible way it treats gay and lesbian Catholics,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Yosef ''Tommy'' Lapid, a Holocaust survivor and head of Israel's
secular Shinui party, was among those who wanted the pope to
apologize directly to the victims.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is high time for the pope to ask for forgiveness from the
Jewish people,'' he said, ''not only for the silence of (Pope) Pius
XII during Auschwitz and the Holocaust, but for all the sins that
the church committed toward the Jews in 2,000 years of a very sad
history.''
</P>
<P>
   Vatican spokesman Joaquin Navarro-Valls had warned that the
pope's intention was never to ask for forgiveness from people. The
pope, he said, asks for forgiveness from God.
</P>
<P>
   Lau and other Israelis expressed hope that the pope will talk
about the Holocaust when he visits Yad Vashem, the Holocaust
memorial in Israel, during his March 20-26 pilgrimage to the Holy
Land.
</P>
<P>
   But Pawlikowski noted that the pope could ''cause more problems
if he offers a spirited defense of Pius XII.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Jewish leaders have said that Pius failed to speak out
against the Nazis during the Holocaust, while the Vatican has
consistently defended him. The issue remains a source of tension on
the eve of the papal visit.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Vatican's official Web site: http://www.vatican.va
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-13-00 0126 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000313.0009 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 01:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chagall, Soutine and, yes, Modigliani at Jewish Museum  </HEADLINE>
By BETH J. HARPAZ, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- They came from Eastern Europe, some from
traditional Jewish villages and Orthodox families, others from
well-to-do circumstances in big cities like Warsaw.
</P>
<P>
   But regardless of their backgrounds, the artists featured in a
new exhibit at The Jewish Museum all ended up in cosmopolitan Paris
between 1907 and 1939, an era when Post-Impressionism, Fauvism and
Cubism served up a heady brew of influences. Drawn like other
bohemians to the art word's capital, these Jewish artists achieved
success and renown for their work before Nazism scattered them
again.
</P>
<P>
   ''Paris in New York'' features 38 works by 12 artists including
Marc Chagall, Max Weber, Chaim Soutine and Amedeo Modigliani. Yes,
Modigliani was Jewish! But with assimilation and his Italian name
and upbringing (he's the only one of the 12 who wasn't born in
Eastern Europe), it's not well-known. And unlike Chagall, who grew
up in a Russian shtetl and incorporates Jewish symbols and images
into his work, Modigliani's instantly recognizable portrait style
with its oval faces, swan necks and irisless eyes offers no clues
to his religious identity.
</P>
<P>
   All but two of the 38 paintings and sculptures featured here are
borrowed from private collectors in New York; hence the exhibit's
title ''Paris in New York.'' The goal of the show was to highlight
rarely seen works. While that deprives viewers of the chance to
revisit better-known masterpieces, it also brings to light unknown
treasures. An audio-tour even features quotes from the private
collectors, and hearing their intimate reactions to the art is like
comparing notes with a friend on how you personally relate to a
certain piece.
</P>
<P>
   Kurt Olden, the collector who loaned Jules Pascin's ''The
Turkish Family,'' says that the painting of nine cheerful
individuals, from a little girl to a jaunty man in a top hat,
gathered beneath a blissful cherub, reminded him of how his own
clan arrived in New York from Hitler's Germany: ''We were like
Pascin's Turkish family, like the refugees who escaped from Turkey
in the late 19th century.''
</P>
<P>
   Two bronze nudes, each about 2 feet tall, by Elie Nadelman, were
loaned by Bernard Goldberg, who is quoted as seeing the two in a
sexual courtship: ''The woman -- very coy, very, very guarded. And
the male, although he is kind of androgynous, is saying, you know,
'Come on, let's get on with it.' ... When the museum asked if they
could borrow one, I said: 'You can't borrow one without the other
because I think they relate to each other.'''
</P>
<P>
   There are two Chagalls in the exhibit: ''Rabbi,'' a moody
painting in blacks and grays of a man standing with his eyes shut,
lost in thought and stroking a long beard, a crowd of tumble-down
houses in the background; and ''Carpenters and Fishes,'' a brightly
colored picture of two men working a handsaw, with a whimsical blue
fish floating in the corner of a yellow sky.
</P>
<P>
   The Modiglianis include several portraits, among them the 1916
masterpiece ''Portrait of Anna (Hanka) Zborowska,'' an almost
classical depiction of a serene, elegant woman with the artist's
trademark hollowed-out eyes, like a statue's gaze gone
one-dimensional.
</P>
<P>
   Chaim Soutine's work is the most unsettling with its grim
depiction of even the most benign subjects. ''Little Girl with a
Doll'' shows a waif with haunting black pools for eyes, her lips
turned down, clutching a lump of a doll with eyes but no face. Both
girl and doll bring to mind Edvard Munch's famous Expressionist
work ''The Scream.''
</P>
<P>
   Soutine's ''The Communicant,'' which interestingly portrays a
Catholic subject, shows a girl dressed in a wedding-like gown, but
her expression conveys sorrow and dread. The bloody ''Hanging
Turkey'' bears a gruesome resemblance to a human corpse. And in
''House at Oiseme,'' even his landscape is infused with foreboding
-- black trees, a ghostly mansion, wispy clouds hanging like
question marks.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit also features two enchanting sculptures by Jacques
Lipchitz: ''Acrobat on Horseback,'' a joyful study of motion,
curves and lines; and ''Detachable Figure: Seated Musician,'' a
cello player that is both a realistic wooden statue and a Cubist
construct of geometric shapes.
</P>
<P>
   Moise Kisling's ''Large Reclining Nude, Kiki,'' is a sexy 1925
portrait of a well-known artist-model and cabaret singer whose
curvy white body nearly floats above the floral chaise she reclines
on. Mane-Katz's Post-Impressionist ''Landscape'' uses short,
heavily layered streaks of paint to portray a jumble of simple
peak-roofed homes.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit runs through June 25 at the Jewish Museum, located
on Fifth Avenue at 93rd Street. You may want to go a few blocks
down the avenue to the Metropolitan Museum of Art, which is hosting
''Painters in Paris: 1895-1950.'' The Met show includes Chagall and
Modigliani among 100 other artists and makes a good companion to
the more modest show at the Jewish Museum.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-13-00 0128 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000313.0010 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 01:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spain's Premier Wins Election  </HEADLINE>
By KERNAN TURNER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADRID, Spain (AP) -- Spanish voters handed their prime minister
-- one of the European Union's few conservative leaders -- a major
victory in general elections, allowing him to continue the
free-market policies he credits for Spain's vibrant economy.
</P>
<P>
   Surpassing the expectations of pre-election polls, Jose Maria
Aznar on Sunday secured 183 seats in the 350-member Parliament for
his conservative Popular Party. That is up from 156 in the last
legislature and more than the 170 polls had predicted.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've won the elections!'' Aznar shouted from a balcony at
party headquarters in Madrid as enthusiastic party supporters
cheered and chanted and waved red and yellow Spanish flags in the
street below.
</P>
<P>
   With his wife, Ana Botella, at his side, Aznar promised a
government ''open to dialogue'' with other political parties and
''all of Spanish society.''
</P>
<P>
   With 100 percent of the votes counted, Aznar's party won 44.54
percent of the vote, the Interior Ministry reported. Socialists won
34 percent and dropped to 125 seats from 141. Their allies in the
communist-dominated United Left coalition slumped to eight seats
from 21.
</P>
<P>
   The moderate Basque Nationalist Party got 1.7 percent of the
votes and seven seats, up from five. The rest were shared among
small regional parties. Of Spain's 34 million eligible voters, 70
percent cast ballots, down from 77 percent in the last election in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   Aznar, a 47-year-old former tax inspector, sought re-election to
another four-year term based on the strength of an economy that
grew 3.7 percent last year. He has reduced the jobless rate from 23
percent to 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Aznar unseated Socialist Prime Minister Felipe
Gonzalez, who had governed for nearly 14 years -- but whose
administration was tarnished by corruption scandals.
</P>
<P>
   Party officials said the solid victory meant Aznar will have a
clear mandate to continue his free-market policies. A parliamentary
majority gives Aznar a freer hand in passing legislation.
</P>
<P>
   His main opponent, Socialist Party leader Joaquin Almunia, a
former cabinet minister, had campaigned mainly on promises to
better distribute Spain's wealth, claiming Spain's economic bonanza
has benefited mainly the wealthy -- particularly businesspeople
close to Aznar.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to galvanize leftist forces, Almunia's party struck an
alliance with United Left, which for years had accused the
Socialists of being centrist sellouts.
</P>
<P>
   In accepting defeat at party headquarters, Almunia announced his
resignation as party head, a post he had held for three years.
</P>
<P>
   Lacking a majority in Parliament during his first four years in
office, Aznar relied on support from Jordi Pujol, Catalan
nationalist leader of the Convergence and Union Party. Aznar's
victory ended Pujol's role as kingmaker, a position he had enjoyed
for the last three Spanish governments.
</P>
<P>
   But Pujol's party became the third-largest party in the
legislature Sunday. By winning 15 seats, a loss of one, it overtook
United Left, which won only eight seats, dropping from 21 in the
last legislature.
</P>
<P>
   At Sunday's victory rally, Aznar soberly urged Spaniards to
remember the victims of terrorism who ''are not able to be with us
tonight'' because they had given their lives ''for liberty and
democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   The prime minister has taken a tough stand against the Basque
separatist group ETA, which staged three car bombings that took
three lives in the weeks leading up to the election.
</P>
<P>
   ETA ended a 14-month truce in December after Aznar's government
refused to discuss sovereignty for the northern Basque region. The
group has killed nearly 800 people since it began its independence
crusade in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   Both major parties reject ETA's separatists goals and the Basque
conflict was not a major campaign issue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-13-00 0141 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000313.0011 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 01:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Montana Dems See Hope for Revival  </HEADLINE>
By BOB ANEZ, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HELENA, Mont. (AP) -- Montana Democrats, who have watched their
standing in Big Sky politics dwindle dramatically over the past
dozen years, see hope for revival in the 2000 elections.
</P>
<P>
   ''The stars are lining up right,'' said Bob Ream, Montana
Democratic Party chairman.
</P>
<P>
   The party has fallen on hard times. In 1988, it lost the
governor's seat to the Republican camp, where it remains. That same
year, Republican Conrad Burns snatched away a U.S. Senate seat. In
1994, the GOP took full control of the Legislature. Two years
later, Democrats lost the state's lone U.S. House seat.
</P>
<P>
   But as 2000 unfolds, Democrats seem well-positioned to reclaim
some of that lost ground. Term limits will deny many GOP
officeholders the chance to run again, and the Republican
congressman is quitting. Analysts give Democrats a good chance to
take both the U.S. House seat and the governor's mansion.
</P>
<P>
   But winning back Burns' Senate seat is iffy, and wresting
control of either house of the Legislature from the GOP will be
difficult at best.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a potential for the Democrats to do better, but it's
not a dead-cinch, certain thing,'' said Craig Wilson, head of the
political science department at Montana State University-Billings.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, whose control of the Legislature and governor's
office for the last six years is the longest GOP reign over both
branches since 1948, consider Democrats overly optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't see it,'' said Matt Denny, state GOP chairman. ''We
have had a stable state government without special sessions,
without budget problems or tax increases. It ain't broke.''
</P>
<P>
   While the GOP has an advantage in a conservative state like
Montana, Democrats have legitimate reasons for feeling upbeat.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Gov. Marc Racicot, a moderate, hugely popular with
Montanans throughout his two terms, will be on the sidelines this
time because of term limits. He has largely ignored Montana
politics this year to focus on helping his friend George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ''With Racicot not running again at the head of the ticket, it
leaves a huge hole for Republicans,'' Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats also got a break in the U.S. House race when two-term
Republican Rick Hill bowed out, citing lingering complications from
eye surgery. A strong Democratic candidate already in the race,
state school Superintendent Nancy Keenan, suddenly found herself
running for an open seat rather than challenging an incumbent.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Rehberg, a former lieutenant governor and U.S. Senate
candidate, took Hill's spot on the ballot. He and Keenan, both
former legislators with statewide campaign and fund-raising
experience, are well-matched as opponents, and their political
views are about as far apart as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Calvert, chairman of the political science department at
MSU-Bozeman, expects the race to attract a lot of out-of-state
attention. With Democrats needing only six seats to take over the
House and the bargain-basement price of campaigns in the Montana,
the national parties will pour in buckets of money, he predicted.
</P>
<P>
   ''Montana is in the bull's eye,'' Calvert said.
</P>
<P>
   A strong slate of well-known Democrats running for governor is
another reason for party optimism. Secretary of State Mike Cooney,
Attorney General Joe Mazurek and Auditor Mark O'Keefe -- all
term-limited -- are seeking the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP favorite is Lt. Gov. Judy Martz, who was a political
unknown when tapped by Racicot as his running mate four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the three Democratic candidates has legislative
experience, a track record of running successful statewide
campaigns and names familiar to voters. Martz is a neophyte with a
low-profile job and relatively little statewide identity.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think she has a reputation of being an effective
manager, because the lieutenant governor is never in the news,''
said Jim Lopach, political science professor at the University of
Montana.
</P>
<P>
   Her challenger is Rob Natelson, a combative conservative
tax-fighter with strong appeal to the GOP right-wing. ''If he
wins,'' Calvert argues, ''the Democrats could nominate Lassie, and
Lassie would win.''
</P>
<P>
   While Democrats have good shots at the U.S. House and governor's
seats, their prospects in the U.S. Senate race are more dicey.
</P>
<P>
   Whitefish farmer Brian Schweitzer is the most likely of two
Democrats to win the party nomination and take on two-term
incumbent Burns. Schweitzer, a newcomer to statewide politics, has
established himself as an aggressive campaigner with a knack for
successful publicity stunts.
</P>
<P>
   But Burns has a down-home style that has appealed to voters in
the past. He also has the money for what he expects will be a
state-record $5 million campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Political experts expect he will survive his reneging on a
promise to run only twice and the criticism he has received for
supporting asbestos-compensation bills pending in Congress.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-13-00 0149 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000313.0012 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 01:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Matisse Works Displayed in Denver  </HEADLINE>
By ROBERT WELLER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER (AP) -- For once, a construction job is bringing people to
downtown Denver instead of keeping them away.
</P>
<P>
   A renovation project at the Baltimore Museum of Art has brought
a major collection of Henri Matisse works to the Denver Art Museum.
The exhibit opened Sunday and runs through June 25.
</P>
<P>
   ''They thought storing them during the work would be a waste so
they made them available for a traveling exhibition,'' said Blake
Milteer, curatorial assistant.
</P>
<P>
   It is the third major traveling exhibition at the Denver museum
in the past year. The previous two exhibitions highlighted the work
of Impressionists and Neo-Impressionist Henri Toulouse-Lautrec.
</P>
<P>
   The latest includes 36 paintings, 16 sculptures and 15 drawings.
The colors are as bright as the Mediterranean sun that dazzled
Matisse after he gave up a promising law career.
</P>
<P>
   Later he followed in the footsteps of Paul Gaugain to Tahiti.
</P>
<P>
   A reviewer tagged Matisse's works with the title of ''fauve,''
or ''wild beast,'' a blazing departure from the softer colors of
the Impressionists.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the Matisse paintings and sculptures are of female
nudes, his main subject during a 60-year career that lasted until
the day he died in 1954.
</P>
<P>
   His choice of subject contrasts dramatically with that of his
longtime friend and rival, Pablo Picasso. Matisse (1869-1954)
became known as a painter of ''love and life'' while Picasso was
called the painter of ''love and death.''
</P>
<P>
   The artist's works are in stark contrast to his own staid
appearance. His wife insisted that he always be photographed in a
suit, said Milteer.
</P>
<P>
   ''He found it very important to appear as a gentleman. A lot of
his paintings were pretty far out for the time,'' Milteer said,
adding that some reproductions of his ''Blue Nude'' were burned in
protest in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ''I just want America to know I am a family man,'' he told
interviewers.
</P>
<P>
   The two most famous works in the collection are ''The Large
Reclining Nude,'' formerly known as ''The Pink Nude,'' and ''The
Blue Nude.''
</P>
<P>
   The works were collected by the Cone sisters of Baltimore, heirs
to a textile fortune. Claribel and Etta Cone often traveled to
Europe and became friends with the artist as well as other
celebrities.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: http://www.denverartmuseum.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-13-00 0151 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000313.0013 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 01:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Popular Party Wins in Spain Vote  </HEADLINE>
By KERNAN TURNER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADRID, Spain (AP) -- Spanish voters handed their prime minister
-- one of the European Union's few conservative leaders -- a major
victory in general elections, allowing him to continue the
free-market policies he credits for Spain's vibrant economy.
</P>
<P>
   Surpassing the expectations of pre-election polls, Jose Maria
