<HEADLINE> Plane Lands on its Belly in Calif.  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BURBANK, Calif. (AP) -- A small plane with a landing gear
malfunction made a successful emergency landing at Burbank Airport
on Sunday, a week after another jet skidded off a runway here.
</P>
<P>
   None of the four people aboard the Piper Comanche were injured,
said Louis Diaz, Federal Aviation Administration operations officer
in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   There was no fire or fuel leak reported.
</P>
<P>
   The single-engine plane made the unscheduled landing on its
belly at 5:18 p.m. after having problems with both its landing gear
and its communications system.
</P>
<P>
   It was not immediately clear where the plane departed from or
where it was heading when it was diverted to
Burbank-Glendale-Pasadena Airport.
</P>
<P>
   The landing comes a week after a Southwest Airlines jet skidded
off a runway at Burbank Airport into a nearby street. The plane
narrowly missed disaster -- skidding 40 feet away from a Chevron
station's gas pumps. Fifteen people reported injuries in that
accident.
</P>
<P>
   In December, another Piper Comanche made a successful belly
landing at Burbank Airport after it reported problems with its
landing gear. There were no injuries.
</P>
</TEXT>
