<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spain Leader Has Fought for Respect  </HEADLINE>
By DANIEL WOOLLS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADRID, Spain (AP) -- Jose Maria Aznar rose from a tax inspector
to unseat one of Europe's longest-standing leaders and to preside
over one of its most vibrant economies.
</P>
<P>
   Still, critics say he has image problems.
</P>
<P>
   Aznar on Sunday won the right to keep his post as prime
minister, but only after enduring four years of constant
suggestions that he lacked the political and intellectual depth to
run a country.
</P>
<P>
   Now 47, the conservative leader took office in 1996 after
defeating Prime Minister Felipe Gonzalez, a Socialist who had ruled
Spain for nearly 14 years and boasted powerful friends all over
Europe -- including then-German Chancellor Helmut Kohl. Outside
Spain, virtually no one had heard of Aznar.
</P>
<P>
   And while Gonzalez was a silver-tongued orator clearly at ease
working a crowd, Aznar came across as distant, his delivery stiff
and wooden. To this day, he's the first to admit he is anything but
folksy and glib.
</P>
<P>
   Newspaper cartoonists regularly feast on Aznar, depicting him as
being of abbreviated stature -- literally and figuratively -- in his
dealings with other leaders and in domestic politics.
</P>
<P>
   One particularly telling vignette ran Oct. 21, 1998, in the
newspaper El Mundo, which is generally supportive of Aznar. Weeks
earlier, the Basque separatist group ETA had declared a cease-fire.
Then, on Oct. 16, former Chilean dictator Augusto Pinochet was
arrested in London on a warrant from a Spanish judge seeking the
general's extradition on human rights violations.
</P>
<P>
   In the cartoon, Aznar appears as a small figure next to a
towering Fidel Castro. ''Go figure,'' Castro says. ''Someone as
insignificant as you may go down in history as the man who ended
ETA terrorism and sent Pinochet to jail.''
</P>
<P>
   However, ETA ended a 14-month truce in December after Aznar's
government refused to discuss sovereignty for the northern Basque
region. The group has killed nearly 800 people since it began its
independence crusade in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Pinochet returned to Chile earlier this month after
16 months detention in London. He was released after a panel of
judges said he was too ill to stand trial for abuses during his
1973-90 rule.
</P>
<P>
   Spanish newspapers have also recounted how in April of last
year, during a visit to Washington that was to include dinner with
President Clinton, Aznar insisted on eating at the White House --
with its potential for photo opportunities -- rather than at a
restaurant as suggested by Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   And when Aznar traveled to Moscow last May for talks with
President Boris Yeltsin, only to see them canceled at the last
minute by the Russians, Spain's opposition Socialist Party seized
on the cancelation as proof that no one abroad takes Aznar
seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ''Can you imagine a worse job on Earth than being Aznar's public
relations adviser?'' said political scientist Ramon Cotarelo.
</P>
<P>
   Aznar shrugs off this kind of criticism, saying that what
matters is his record, not his sound bites. ''I am a quiet man who
grows through adversity,'' he said during the campaign.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-13-00 0207 </TRAILER>
