<HEADLINE> Musical Re-enacts Lincoln's Death  </HEADLINE>
By CARL HARTMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- It's a historic national tragedy wrapped in a
new musical -- re-enacted on the site where it actually happened.
</P>
<P>
   The musical ''Reunion'' portrays a small theatrical group
performing a Civil War drama 25 years to the day after John Wilkes
Booth shot President Lincoln. The show, which played a series of
previews last week, opens Tuesday at Ford's Theatre, where the
assassination occurred.
</P>
<P>
   The theater was gutted soon after Lincoln's death and rebuilt in
1968, reproduced with the help of images by Matthew Brady, the
Civil War photographer. The outside of the box where Lincoln sat in
a rocking chair is permanently decorated as it was on the night of
April 14, 1865, with flags, bunting and a small picture of George
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the final scenes of the new production, a spotlight
falls on a small stage built on the larger stage.
</P>
<P>
   Actor James Judy takes the part of Harry Hawk, who was on stage
at Ford's in the farce ''Our American Cousin'' when the fatal shot
was fired. Hawk was portraying Asa Trenchard -- an American who has
come to England to claim an inheritance, and then has given it
away. A snooty, fortune-hunting Mrs. Mountchessington tells him
off.
</P>
<P>
   ''Well, I guess I know enough to turn you inside out, old gal,''
Trenchard tells her as she struts off in her hoop skirt. ''You
sockdologizing old mantrap!''
</P>
<P>
   In 1865, the laughter and clapping drowned out the single shot
that Booth fired from his short-barreled derringer into the back of
the president's neck. The assassin vaulted nearly 12 feet to the
stage, catching his spur in a flag. He broke a foot in his fall and
hobbled to the rear of the theater, where a horse was waiting.
</P>
<P>
   In 2000, actor Ric Ryder doesn't jump, but struggles to his feet
and hobbles off in the semi-darkness. Lincoln is not seen -- the box
is empty.
</P>
<P>
   ''Reunion'' is billed as ''a musical epic in miniature.'' Jack
Kyrieleison, 49, an actor from suburban Kensington, Md., wrote the
script. Most of it consists of actual words from Lincoln, Gen.
George B. McClellan -- his opponent in the 1864 election -- poet Walt
Whitman and others of the period.
</P>
<P>
   Michael O'Flaherty, music director of the Goodspeed Opera House
in East Haddam, Conn., arranged a series of songs from the Civil
War era.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   ''Reunion, A Musical Epic in Miniature,'' is scheduled to run
through June 18, including a performance on April 14, the 135th
anniversary of the assassination.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The theater Web site is: www.fordstheatre.org
</P>
<P>
   A complete account of the assassination from the Library of
Congress can be viewed at:
http://memory.loc.gov/ammem/alhtml/malhome.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-13-00 0223 </TRAILER>
