<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 02:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Subway Continues To Operate  </HEADLINE>
By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- They were a sensation in 1909, a pair of
leather-seated, open-air cars affectionately dubbed ''Peg'' and
''Tommy'' that sped senators to the Capitol through a 760-foot
tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   ''They are operated by five horsepower storage batteries and can
make about 12 miles an hour, unless the senators object to this
speed,'' a newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
   ''Nobody who has seen them has ever seen their like before,''
another paper enthused. ''They are a cross between an automobile
and a dogcart,'' the Washington Evening Star said.
</P>
<P>
   The new cars, light tan in color and made by the Studebaker Co.
at a cost of $2,400 each, were the stars of what was probably the
world's shortest subway system, running to the Capitol from the
Senate's first office building.
</P>
<P>
   Museum pieces today, they have long since been replaced by more
modern equipment. But their purpose remains, transporting lawmakers
from their offices to votes on the Senate floor in the shortest
possible time.
</P>
<P>
   Some people think of it as the ultimate senatorial perquisite,
some as just a ''horizontal elevator'' that helps senators do their
jobs and also transport tourists by the thousands across the
congressional campus.
</P>
<P>
   Built long and low with seating for five people on each side,
Peg and Tommy ferried senators, lobbyists and tourists through the
tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   Since there was no room to turn around, the cars reversed
direction on return trips through the 22-foot-wide tunnel. That was
broad enough to allow a seven-foot pedestrian walkway with the
remaining lane reserved for Peg and Tommy. They ran on a slightly
concave concrete track. It was wide enough for the two cars to pass
''without much danger of collision.''
</P>
<P>
   With the automobile itself just beginning to come into its own,
some people found the whole thing a bit startling.
</P>
<P>
   ''Never does one hear (anything) to herald their approach,
except a peculiar buzzing and a faint tinkling that starts far away
and comes nearer and nearer around the corner of the serpentine
tunnel,'' the Evening Star said. ''When that sound is heard for the
first time the suspense is terrible until the freakish thing buzzes
and tinkles into view out of the bowels of the earth.''
</P>
<P>
   The service began in March, just days after the Capitol
inaugural of President Taft.
</P>
<P>
   Climbing on board for one of the first rides were Sens. William
Borah of Idaho, Elihu Root of New York, Henry Cabot Lodge of
Massachusetts, Robert LaFollette of Wisconsin and Taft's vice
president, James S. Sherman.
</P>
<P>
   Sherman observed while the ride was adequate the scenery was
boring.
</P>
<P>
   ''... Nowhere in that seemingly endless tunnel is there anything
to break the monotony of the dead white walls and ceiling and the
floor of light gray, except where the slim black iron railing
separates the footpath from the railroad right of way,'' the vice
president said.
</P>
<P>
   The tunnel remains in use. The monotony that distressed Vice
President Sherman is broken by a bright display of state and
territorial flags hanging along its length.
</P>
<P>
   The use of the Senate tunnel for a subway system to get senators
to the votes on time was an afterthought. It was designed to
channel electric power, steam and hot water from a new power plant
and to provide a more efficient way to deal with deliveries.
</P>
<P>
   Updated periodically, the congressional subways have operated
continuously for 91 years. The House side of the Capitol is linked
to the Rayburn House Office Building by open-air subway cars. They
provide a breezy ride on cars similar to those that serve the
Russell Senate Office Building through the tunnel first used in
1909.
</P>
<P>
   The newest improvement in the senators' subway is a high-tech
leap from the age of Peg and Tommy. Built at a cost of $18 million
and opened about five years ago, it is a fully driverless and
automated system with enclosed cars, sliding doors and recorded
voices to announce arrivals and departures.
</P>
<P>
   The cars travel between the Capitol and the newer Dirksen and
Hart Senate office buildings. The system was installed by the
company that developed the transport system at Disney World in
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   After a new rail system was installed in 1912, Peg and Tommy
were sent to storage. According to the U.S. Senate Library, which
has researched their history, the two cars were reclaimed by the
Studebaker Co. for $35 each at a 1939 auction. Peg went to the
Studebaker National Museum at South Bend, Ind. Tommy was sent to
the Swigart Museum of Antique Cars in Huntingdon, Pa., after a stop
at the 1940 New York World's Fair.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE -- Lawrence L. Knutson has covered the White House,
Congress and Washington history for more than 30 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-13-00 0227 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000313.0027 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 02:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Census Forms To Be Mailed This Week  </HEADLINE>
By GENARO C. ARMAS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The government is mailing out 98 million
census forms to city and suburban addresses beginning today as it
promotes cooperation with the national headcount in the nation's
classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Census Bureau director Kenneth Prewitt said ''Teach Census
Week'' is aimed at rectifying a problem evident in 1990: Some
Americans forgot to count their children in the census.
</P>
<P>
   ''The hope is that this program ... will ensure that in 2000,
every child is counted,'' Prewitt said in a statement. ''This
program is an ideal way to teach people -- through children's school
lessons -- about the importance of including everyone living in
their household on the census forms.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 1.5 million teacher kits have been shipped to
participating schools. Children also are receiving take-home
exercises to complete with adults in their households.
</P>
<P>
   Prewitt said the mailings begun today should have questionnaires
in most of the country's 115 million households by the end of the
week. About 83 million homes will get short forms, which contain
seven questions, and a randomly sampled list of 15 million homes
will get long forms, which have 52 questions.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the forms were delivered by hand, mostly to rural
addresses.
</P>
<P>
   Census figures are used, among other purposes, to reapportion
congressional districts and allocate federal aid to states and
localities.
</P>
<P>
   Prewitt warned the public to beware of deceptive mailings. The
official census form comes in an envelope with a Commerce
Department return address and the Census 2000 logo.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've designed a distinctive-looking package,'' he said, ''so
everyone will know that this, and only this, is the official census
form with a bar code for their household.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, people have the option of using the number
on the bar code to log on to the Census Bureau's Web site,
www.census.gov, and answer their questionnaire over the Internet.
They also can fill out the paper form and mail it back.
</P>
<P>
   Also today, census takers will start to survey households in
isolated rural areas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-13-00 0230 </TRAILER>
