<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 02:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Buchanan Won't Stray From Positions  </HEADLINE>
By LAURIE KELLMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Reform Party presidential candidate Pat
Buchanan isn't backing down from divisive positions that are at
odds with most of the party's members, including his opposition to
abortion rights and his call for a cultural war.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan doesn't volunteer those positions at Reform meetings as
he pursues its presidential nomination, and the party platform is
silent on such matters.
</P>
<P>
   ''The majority would be best described as secular,'' said former
party chairman Russell Verney, who is a top aide to founder Ross
Perot. ''They don't want the government to take a position on those
issues.''
</P>
<P>
   But asked Sunday to comment, Buchanan said he will use the
exposure to campaign against the procedure.
</P>
<P>
   ''I will commit myself to use the bully pulpit to fight the
culture of death,'' he said on NBC's ''Meet the Press.'' ''If I'm
nominated by the Reform Party, which I intend to be, the Reform
Party candidate will be the most pro-life candidate in the
presidential race.''
</P>
<P>
   The conservative commentator's stance on domestic issues have
been branded extremist even by some former colleagues in the
Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   But Verney said Buchanan's positions wouldn't disqualify him
from winning the Reform Party's presidential nomination, as long as
he agrees with the platform's opposition to free-trade agreements.
</P>
<P>
   ''Every candidate has positions outside the party's platform,''
Verney said.
</P>
<P>
   By his own admission, Buchanan needs the nomination to keep from
being overshadowed by Texas Gov. George W. Bush and Vice President
Al Gore, the presumptive Republican and Democratic nominees.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan started the race as one of a dozen Republican hopefuls
and has survived by leaving the GOP for the Reform Party and
forging an alliance with political opposites in the party.
</P>
<P>
   At campaign events, Buchanan does not volunteer his
anti-abortion views or the fact that an individual's position on
the issue would be a prime factor in choosing a running mate.
</P>
<P>
   Asked Sunday about potential nominees to the Supreme Court, he
said: ''I would only appoint justices who I knew or deeply believed
would overturn Roe vs. Wade,'' the high court's 1973 decision that
legalized abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is a cultural war going on for the soul of America,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   On whom, if anyone, he would refuse to meet with, Buchanan said
quietly, ''I would not meet with the (Ku Klux) Klan.''
</P>
<P>
   For Buchanan, the Reform Party nomination would bring a huge
reward.
</P>
<P>
   It would give him a pulpit from which to focus on the common
ground between him and the party: opposition to free trade
agreements and normal trade status for China, which the Clinton
administration supports, while minimizing his more divisive
positions.
</P>
<P>
   Winning the nomination also brings $12.6 million in federal
subsidies for his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange, the Reform Party tops its ticket with a candidate
who will draw media coverage and who powerfully articulates its
central underpinning, trade policy.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan predicted Sunday that his candidacy would attract the
support of 15 percent of voters and qualify him to participate in
the fall presidential debates. Such poll numbers would defy surveys
that show that domestic issues, not foreign affairs, drive the
nation's elections.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan plans to fly around the country this week to
fund-raisers and to give a speech Thursday at Harvard University.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-13-00 0231 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
