<DOCNO> APW20000313.0030 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 02:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore, Bush Pursuing Independents  </HEADLINE>
By KATHY BARKS HOFFMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LANSING, Mich. (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore, settling in for a
two-hour chat with 200 people in a university gym, scanned the room
for independents and said, ''I'm anxious to talk to you.''
</P>
<P>
   He still is. That's where the action is in Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're at a fork in the road, and I'm here to try to convince
you to vote for me,'' Gore, the presumptive Democratic presidential
nominee, told the group at Wayne State University in Detroit -- John
McCain territory not too long ago.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush lost the state's Republican
presidential primary in part because he couldn't get the support of
independents, who went instead for McCain, his now-vanquished
rival. Bush also is changing his message in hopes of pulling
independents his way in November.
</P>
<P>
   ''As a group, independents and ticket splitters are the ones who
will decide the outcome'' this fall, said David Rohde, a
presidential election expert at Michigan State University. The
candidates ''are going to focus on those people right from the
beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   Michigan has been a barometer of national presidential strength
in the last four elections, picking the winner each time. The final
outcome was within one percentage point of reflecting the national
popular vote in three of the four, and only three points in
President Clinton's favor in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   More than one-fifth of Michigan's 6.7 million registered voters
are independents or swing voters who vote for the candidate rather
than the party, said Craig Ruff of Public Sector Consultants, a
Lansing think tank.
</P>
<P>
   They tend to support abortion rights, cite health care, taxes
and education as their top concerns and value saving Social
Security over reducing taxes, according to polls done by EPIC/MRA
of Lansing.
</P>
<P>
   Six out of 10 are women, and -- regardless of gender -- likely to
be either over age 64 or between 41 and 49. Nearly 90 percent are
white.
</P>
<P>
   They overwhelmingly supported McCain in the state's Feb. 22 GOP
primary, accounting for four of every 10 votes for the Arizona
senator. About 13 percent backed third-party candidate Ross Perot
in both 1992 and 1996, and more than half would like to see McCain
run as the nominee of Perot's Reform Party.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Fred Upton supports Bush but criticized him after McCain's
Michigan victory. He said the Texas governor ''allowed the
hard-right element to speak for him in lots of ways, and it was an
absolute turnoff measured in votes among independents, who we have
to rely on to win, whether it be for governor or for president.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that McCain, and former Democratic contender Bill Bradley,
have quit the race, some independent voters may stay home, said Ed
Sarpolus of EPIC/MRA.
</P>
<P>
   For those who do vote in the general election, he said, ''It's
going to come down to the character and trust issue. That's why
McCain got all his votes.'' He expects independents to base their
votes on who they think can keep prosperity going rather than on
specific issues or party.
</P>
<P>
   Incoming state Republican Chairman Rusty Hills said Bush still
has plenty of time to convince independent and swing voters that
he's the best candidate to guard their interests.
</P>
<P>
   ''Bush has done it'' as governor in Texas, Hills said. ''We just
have to do it nationally.''
</P>
<P>
   While it's too early to tell how independents will vote in
Michigan's presidential race, Ruff said their role remains crucial.
</P>
<P>
   ''I see neither Gore nor Bush whipping anyone into a frenzy, and
we'll return to a somewhat normal turnout among partisan voters,''
he predicted. ''That puts independents back into the role of
broker.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-13-00 0231 </TRAILER>
