<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 03:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oregon St. Fires Hoops Coach Payne  </HEADLINE>
By LANDON HALL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- Oregon State basketball coach Eddie Payne
and his staff were fired Sunday, a day after the Beavers completed
their fifth straight non-winning season.
</P>
<P>
   Oregon State lost 83-65 to Oregon on Saturday night to finish
13-16 overall, including 5-13 in the Pacific-10. The Beavers were
52-88 overall and 20-70 in the Pac-10 in five seasons under Payne.
</P>
<P>
   ''Making changes in your program is never an easy thing to do,
especially when it involves good people,'' athletic director Mitch
Barnhart said in a statement. ''Sometimes the chemistry of teams
and events don't always produce the success level you are hoping to
achieve.''
</P>
<P>
   Oregon State once was among the nation's most powerful programs.
The Beavers won four Pac-10 titles during the 1980s, went to the
NCAA tournament seven times and were ranked No. 1 for five weeks
during the 1980-81 season. But the team hasn't had a winning record
since 1989-90, Gary Payton's last season.
</P>
<P>
   The Beavers improved steadily during Payne's first four seasons,
going 6-21, 7-20, 13-17 and 13-4 last season, when Oregon State
defeated three Top 10 teams at home. With all five starters
returning, prospects were good for a winning campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The team's offense never became a threat, and center Jason Heide
was plagued by injuries. The Beavers upgraded with freshmen Brian
Jackson and Jimmie Haywood, but the better teams in the Pac-10
improved faster by bringing in more talented players.
</P>
<P>
   Attendance also began to falter, and Barnhart, who watched the
football program get competitive almost overnight under new coach
Dennis Erickson, lost patience. During the buzzer-beating upset of
Arizona last week, only 5,538 fans turned out, just over half the
capacity of Gill Coliseum. Overall, attendance was down more than
12 percent from last season.
</P>
<P>
   Oregon State's outlook is bleak for next year, too. The team's
best player, junior point guard Deaundra Tanner, said he might
leave school and return to Los Angeles to be closer to his
3-year-old son. And to replace five departing seniors, Payne signed
just one player -- a 6-foot-11 Canadian -- and has four scholarships
left to fill.
</P>
<P>
   Payne, 48, has one year remaining on his contract, for which the
school owes him a base salary of $135,000. Assistant coaches Leroy
Washington, Rich Wold and Chad Forcier have contracts that expire
in June.
</P>
<P>
   Payne was coach at East Carolina from 1991-1995, compiling a
record of 56-58. But his final two teams posted winning records,
and the Pirates reached the 1993 NCAA tournament.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-13-00 0309 </TRAILER>
