<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 03:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hall of Fame Trainer Lukas Wins One  </HEADLINE>
By RICHARD ROSENBLATT, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   A first, two seconds and two fourths in five Kentucky Derby prep
races isn't the worst thing that could have happened to Hall of
Fame trainer D. Wayne Lukas.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt, Lukas would have preferred five victories over the
weekend, but if his 3-year-olds keep running well, the four-time
Derby winner might just pull off a fifth Derby win on May 6.
</P>
<P>
   Surfside saved Lukas from a lost weekend when the sensational
filly won the $300,000 Santa Anita Oaks on Sunday, holding off
Kumari Continent by three-quarters of a length.
</P>
<P>
   The victory, although not as impressive as expected, moved
Surfside into a race against boys in the Santa Anita Derby on April
8.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've got grandiose ideas, we're looking down the road,''
Lukas said. ''They don't give us anything extra for winning by six
or seven lengths.''
</P>
<P>
   Lukas saddled the last filly to win the Derby, Winning Colors,
in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   A look at Lukas' weekend ledger:
</P>
<P>
   -- Even-money favorite High Yield was beaten a head by Hal's Hope
in Saturday's $750,000 Florida Derby.
</P>
<P>
   -- True Confidence was 1{ lengths behind long shot Remember
Sheikh in Saturday's $200,000 El Camino Derby at Bay Meadows.
</P>
<P>
   -- Second-choice Exchange Rate was fourth in Sunday's $750,000
Louisiana Derby, won by Mighty.
</P>
<P>
   -- Sun Cat was fourth in the $100,000 Swale Stakes on the Florida
Derby undercard. Trippi was the winner.
</P>
<P>
   -- Another Lukas filly, Shawnee Country, won the $350,000 Fair
Grounds Oaks on Saturday, but she appears headed to the Kentucky
Oaks on May 5.
</P>
<P>
   Lukas said High Yield will head to the Blue Grass Stakes on
April 15 for a rematch with Hal's Hope, who won a stretch-long duel
with Lukas' colt to give 88-year-old owner-trainer Harold Rose and
jockey Roger Velez the biggest wins of their careers.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've never been to the Derby before,'' Velez said, ''but it
looks like we're going this time.''
</P>
<P>
   Rose, who has bred, owned and trained claimers for much of his
nearly 40 years in the racing business, is set for his second trip
to Churchill Downs. In 1984, his Rexson's Hope finished 10th in a
20-horse field.
</P>
<P>
   ''This time,'' he said, ''I'm going with a contender.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the top Derby contenders who did not race over the weekend
were Anees, The Deputy and War Chant.
</P>
<P>
   Anees, winner of the Breeders' Cup Juvenile, and The Deputy are
expected to meet in the San Felipe at Santa Anita on March 19; and
War Chant, the San Rafael winner, goes next in the Santa Anita
Derby, where Surfside will be waiting.
</P>
<P>
   In the Santa Anita Oaks, jockey Pat Day was aboard Surfside a
day after his second-place finish on Hal's Hope.
</P>
<P>
   The win was the fourth straight and seventh in nine lifetime
starts for Surfside, and the winner's share of $180,000 raised the
career earnings of the Kentucky-bred daughter of 1977 Triple Crown
winner Seattle Slew to $1,040,230.
</P>
<P>
   In the Louisiana Derby, Mighty rallied from last place entering
the final turn as jockey Shane Sellers guided his colt into the
lead for a two-length victory over More Than Ready.
</P>
<P>
   ''This was by far his biggest race,'' Mighty's trainer Frank
Brothers said.
</P>
<P>
   Captain Steve, the 2-1 favorite trained by Bob Baffert, was
third, but the trainer said he was leaning toward running his colt
in the Blue Grass.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Pletcher, who trains More Than Ready, was encouraged by his
colt's first race around two turns.
</P>
<P>
   ''I hope this quiets some of the critics who say he can't go two
turns,'' Pletcher said. ''He's absolutely ready to step up to the
next level.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Florida Derby undercard, Trippi improved his Derby
chances with a 1}-length victory over Ultimate Warrior in the
$100,000 Swale Stakes. Lukas' Sun Cat was fourth.
</P>
<P>
   In the El Camino Real Derby, Remember Sheikh's upset of True
Confidence in a field of 14 has his owner, Jeff Peppard,
considering a shot at the Triple Crown races.
</P>
<P>
   ''We'll take it slow with him,'' Peppard said. ''We don't want
to put him over his head.''
</P>
<P>
   Lukas can take consolation knowing that last year, Charismatic
finished second in this race before winning the Derby, Preakness
and Horse of the Year honors in 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-13-00 0314 </TRAILER>
