<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 03:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tribune, Times Mirror May Merge  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Tribune Co. and Times Mirror Co. were on the
brink of approving a merger late Sunday that would create the
nation's third-largest newspaper company, the Chicago Tribune
reported.
</P>
<P>
   Tribune Co. would control operations of the combined companies,
including the Times Mirror flagship Los Angeles Times. The new
company would be based in Chicago, the newspaper said in its
Internet edition on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The combined daily newspaper circulation of the merged companies
would be 3.6 million, by the Tribune's count, ranking it third
behind Gannett Co. Inc. and Knight Ridder.
</P>
<P>
   ''Advanced discussions are under way between Tribune Company and
Times Mirror to merge the two companies,'' Martha Goldstein, vice
president of Times Mirror corporate communications, told The
Morning Call of Allentown, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   The new firm would include 11 daily newspapers, 22 television
stations and a combined market value of $11.7 billion, The New York
Times reported in Monday's editions.
</P>
<P>
   The Times Mirror board of directors was meeting late Sunday and
was prepared to endorse the deal, the Tribune reported. At the Los
Angeles Times, employees were told the company would issue a
statement Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   The merger may need permission from the Federal Communications
Commission since FCC rules do not allow a company to own both a TV
station and a newspaper in the same market without a waiver.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the Los Angeles Times, Times Mirror publishes
Newsday of Long Island, N.Y.; The Baltimore Sun; The Hartford
Courant; The Morning Call of Pennsylvania; and The (Stamford)
Advocate and Greenwich Time of Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   More than 60 million people read Times Mirror magazines,
including Field &AMP; Stream, Popular Science, GOLF Magazine, Outdoor
Life, SKI Magazine and SKATEboarding.
</P>
<P>
   The Tribune company reported 1999 revenues of $3.2 billion and
has about 13,400 employees. Tribune Broadcasting owns and operates
22 major market television stations and reaches more than 75
percent of U.S. television households.
</P>
<P>
   The company also owns and operates four radio stations,
including three stations in Denver and WGN-AM in Chicago. Tribune
Entertainment, a subsidiary, develops and distributes TV
programming.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the company owns the Chicago Cubs baseball team.
Tribune Publishing publishes four market-leading newspapers: the
Chicago Tribune, the South Florida-based Sun-Sentinel, The Orlando
Sentinel and the Hampton Roads (Va.)-based Daily Press.
</P>
<P>
   The Tribune newspaper said talks began last year and were
encouraged by the Chandler family, which has had an interest in the
Los Angeles Times since 1882, a year after it began publication.
The Chandler family controls much of the newspaper's voting stock.
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: http://www.timesmirror.com
</P>
<P>
   http://www.tribjobs.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
