<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 10:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Counsel To File Report on FBI Files  </HEADLINE>
By PETE YOST, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Independent Counsel Robert Ray will file a
final report this week on the Clinton White House's improper
gathering of hundreds of FBI background files of Republican
appointees, the prosecutor's office announced today.
</P>
<P>
   The report is expected to be the first of three on the various
aspects of the six-year criminal investigation of the president and
the first lady.
</P>
<P>
   Subsequent reports, all to be sent under seal to a panel of
three federal appeals judges who appointed Ray and predecessor
Kenneth Starr, will deal with the role of first lady Hillary Rodham
Clinton in the purge of the White House travel office and the
Clintons Whitewater dealings.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, presidential spokesman Joe Lockhart said
''we have been through six years and $60 million'' worth of
investigations. ''It's certainly our hope that they report out in a
way that's done quickly ... that's consistent with the statute and
done without regard to politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers outside Ray's office described the plan for reporting on
the probe of the Clintons. ''The FBI files investigation has been
concluded'' and ''we intend to issue a report to the special
division under seal later this week,'' Ray said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Ray's predecessor investigated the FBI files controversy, which
stemmed from an Army detailee at the White House, Anthony Marceca,
gathering FBI files on hundreds of Republican appointees from prior
administrations. The detailee's boss, White House security director
Craig Livingstone, resigned under fire. Marceca and Livingstone
were long-time political operatives for Democratic candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Marceca said that in some instances he passed on ''derogatory''
information from the files to Livingstone. Livingstone said he was
aware that Marceca was gathering FBI files, but knew no details.
</P>
<P>
   The president apologized for the file-gathering, calling it ''an
honest bureaucratic mess-up'' and saying ''I would never condone or
tolerate any kind of enemies list.''
</P>
<P>
   Presidential aides said the FBI files were stored in a secure
vault and never used, blaming the Secret Service for providing
outdated lists of White House passholders -- which Livingstone's
office then relied on to order the background files from the FBI.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
