<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 11:10 a.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
Monday, March 13, 2000
<TEXT>
<P>
   Aetna To Split Into Two Companies
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Aetna Inc., the nation's largest health insurer,
has rejected a $10 billion takeover offer and instead plans to
split its health care and financial services businesses into two
publicly traded companies. Its stock skidded 13 percent in early
trading, dropping $7.12{ to $48.87{ a share today on the New York
Stock Exchange. Aetna, troubled by rising medical costs, several
class action lawsuits and cold relations with doctors and
hospitals, said it plans to make the split into two companies by
the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Tribune To Take Over Times Mirror
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Tribune Co. will acquire Times Mirror Co. in
a $6.46 billion deal that would create a multimedia empire
encompassing the Los Angeles Times, the Chicago Tribune and 22
television stations, ending a family dynasty that dates to 1882.
The transaction creates the nation's third-largest newspaper
company and marks the end of Times Mirror. The Chandler family,
which has controlled the Times for 118 years and owns a majority of
Times Mirror voting shares, initiated the negotiations and supports
the deal, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks Lower in Early Trading
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks fell in early trading today on the heels
of a steep decline abroad, as technology shares came under intense
selling pressure following the dramatic rise in the sector in
recent weeks. The Nasdaq composite index was down 92.85 at 4,955.77
in early trading after being down more than 200 this morning,
falling from the record high reached on Friday. Analysts attributed
the wave of selling to investors eager to lock in profits from the
Nasdaq's sharp rise this year. The index, dominated by technology
stocks, was up 24 percent year-to-date as of Friday's close.
</P>
