<P>
   Fiat, GM May Form Partnership
</P>
<P>
   ROME (AP) -- Italian automaker Fiat reportedly is on the verge of
striking a partnership with General Motors. The Financial Times of
London reported today that GM was expected to announce this week
that it will acquire a 20 percent stake in Fiat worth about $2.4
billion. In return, Fiat was to take a 5 percent interest in GM,
also worth about $2.4 billion, making it one of the U.S.
automaker's largest shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   EU Backs German Pick for IMF Job
</P>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- European Union finance ministers agreed today to
back Germany's Horst Koehler for the top job at the International
Monetary Fund, Portuguese Prime Minister Antonio Guterres said
after meeting with Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder. Schroeder said he
expects Portugal to lobby for Koehler in Washington, which had
rejected the first EU candidate, also a German, as unqualified.
Portugal had lobbied over the weekend for all 15 EU nations to line
up behind Koehler at today's meeting of finance ministers in
Brussels, Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   i2 Technologies Buys Aspect
</P>
<P>
   DALLAS (AP) --Software developer i2 Technologies Inc. is buying
Aspect Development Inc. for about $9.3 billion in stock in a deal
that would be one of the largest in the software industry. Mountain
View, Calif.-based Aspect Development would become a subsidiary of
Dallas-based i2 under the deal announced today. They each
specialize in making software that helps companies conduct business
with other companies.
</P>
<P>
   Disneyland Said OK Environmentally
</P>
<P>
   HONG KONG (AP) -- A planned Disneyland park is environmentally
sound, although it may scare some endangered sea eagles away from
their nearby nest and force them to find to a new home, officials
said today. The pair of breeding white-bellied sea eagles weren't
even discovered until the officials began their assessment of the
environment. An environmentalist said the birds may be far enough
away from the Disneyland park that the construction, crowds and
noise won't bother them.
</P>
<P>
   Continental Fare Increase Remains
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON (AP) -- A fare increase of up to $40 per roundtrip
initiated by Continental Airlines may stick, as competitors have
either matched it or continue to study the move. It was the third
time in as many months that Continental has led bids to raise
fares, blaming soaring jet fuel prices. In January, Continental led
the industry with a $20 hike. American Airlines and Delta Air Lines
said yesterday they have matched Continental's latest increase.
Northwest Airlines matched in certain markets.
</P>
<P>
   Gas Prices Jump Record 12 Cents
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A crude oil crunch sent gasoline prices
soaring a record 12 cents per gallon in the past two weeks and they
may not dip until summer, an analyst predicted. The average retail
price of gasoline nationwide, including all grades and taxes, was
about $1.59 per gallon on Friday, up 11.99 cents from Feb. 25,
according to the Lundberg Survey of 10,000 stations.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's Economy Back Into Recession
</P>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Flagging domestic consumption drove Japan's economy
back into recession late last year, puncturing hopes for a quick
recovery from the deepest slump since World War II. Gross domestic
product, the total value of goods and services, fell 1.4 percent in
the October-December quarter, while private consumption dropped a
steep 1.6 percent, the Economic Planning Agency said today. It was
the second consecutive quarter of GDP decline, meaning the economy
was officially back in recession after anemic growth fueled by a
massive government spending binge last year.
</P>
<P>
   Asian Stock Markets Slump
</P>
<P>
   HONG KONG (AP) -- Asian stock markets slumped across the board
today, with the key index in Taipei posting the biggest one-day
point fall as nervous investors dumped stocks just days ahead of
the presidential election. The Taiwan market's Weighted Stock Price
Index dropped 617 points, or 6.55 percent, to 8,811.95. In Tokyo,
the Nikkei Stock Average lost 560.47 points, or 2.8 percent, to
close at 19,189.93. The Hang Seng Index, the Hong Kong market's key
indicator of blue chips, fell 735.18 points, or 4.1 percent,
closing at 17,096.68.
</P>
<P>
   Chip Maker Infineon Doubles Worth
</P>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- Shares of semiconductor maker Infineon
AG opened on the Frankfurt stock exchange at 70.20 euros, or
$67.39, in today's initial public offering, more than doubling its
initial price. The company, a spinoff of electronics giant Siemens
AG, said the issue was oversubscribed 33 times, with investors
placing orders for 5.7 billion shares to the tune of $192 billion.
</P>
