<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Mixed, Gold Rises in Europe  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- The U.S. dollar was mixed against most other major
currencies in European trading today. Gold rose.
</P>
<P>
   The euro was quoted at 96.56 cents in late European trading, up
from 96.53 cents Friday. Later, in midday trading in New York, the
euro traded at 96.45 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Other dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Friday,
included 105.36 Japanese yen, down from 106.27; 1.6664 Swiss
francs, up from 1.6662; 1.4594 Canadian dollars, up from 1.4567.
</P>
<P>
   The British pound was quoted at $1.5795, up from $1.5786.
</P>
<P>
   In midday trading in New York the dollar bought 105.33 yen, and
the pound was worth $1.5778.
</P>
<P>
   Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no
longer traded separately, though they remain in use. Based on euro
rates, the dollar is worth 2.0247 German marks, down from 2.0257;
2.2808 Dutch guilders, down from 2.2825; 2004.01 Italian lire, down
from 2005.46.
</P>
<P>
   Gold closed in London at $290.40 bid per troy ounce, up from
$289.80 on Friday. In Zurich the bid price was $290.15, up from
$289.25. Gold closed at $290.05 in Hong Kong, up from $289.35.
</P>
<P>
   Silver closed in London at $5.10 bid per troy ounce, up from
$5.09.
</P>
</TEXT>
