<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 12:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stumbles on Selloff  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks edged back from a steep early decline
today, but remained mostly lower in the wake of a widespread
decline abroad. Technology shares came under intense selling
pressure following the dramatic rise in the sector in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index was down 98.27 at 4,950.35 at late
morning, falling from the record high of 5,048.62 reached on
Friday. Shortly after the opening bell, the index fell as much as
209.36 points, a loss of 4.1 percent, before regaining much of the
lost ground.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts attributed the wave of selling to investors eager to
lock in profits from the Nasdaq's sharp rise this year. The index,
dominated by technology stocks, was up 24 percent as of Friday's
close. Just last week, the Nasdaq rose 133.83 points, a gain of 2.7
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Other market indicators were also lower, although their declines
were more modest. The Dow Jones industrial average was down 8.14 to
9,920.68 at midday, having recovered from a loss of as much as
190.49 points, or 1.9 percent, within minutes of the opening of
trading.
</P>
<P>
   The broader Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 was off 9.28 at 1,385.79. The
Russell 2000 index of smaller companies was down 9.37 at 594.44.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're seeing the reflection of investors' nervousness, but
overall, the outlook remains strong,'' said John Shaughnessy, chief
investment strategist at Advest Inc. of Hartford, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   The selloff began abroad, with financial markets in Asia and
European falling sharply.
</P>
<P>
   Leading the decline was Japan's Nikkei stock average, which fell
2.8 percent after the Japanese government announced the economy
shrank more than expected in the last quarter of 1999. It was the
second consecutive quarterly decline of the gross domestic product,
meaning the economy was technically back in recession.
</P>
<P>
   Investors had hoped that an economic recovery in Japan would
compensate for any slowdown in the United States in the coming
years.
</P>
<P>
   The downturn in Asian markets set off selling in Europe too.
Britain's FT-SE 100 was down 1.6 percent, Germany's Xetra DAX index
fell 3.5 percent and France's CAC-40 fell 2.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   European analysts also cited profit-taking, noting that
high-flying media, telecommunications and technology shares were
most severely affected.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mondays always seem to have a dampening effect, particularly
after a good week,'' said Ken Joseph, director of European sales
trading at Credit Lyonnais in London.
</P>
<P>
   On Wall Street, technology shares that have performed the best
this year were falling. Qualcomm fell 4 5/16 to 131 13/16, Oracle
fell 3 3/16 to 78 7/16 and CMGI fell 3{ to 132 15/16.
</P>
<P>
   ''There was a lot of chatter of the weekend on the Wall Street
(television) shows about the impending doom of the Nasdaq,'' said
Brian G. Belski, chief investment strategist at George K. Baum &AMP;
Co., in Kansas City, Mo. ''The market by virtue of its recent
ascent, especially the Nasdaq, has set itself up for a bit of a
correction.''
</P>
<P>
   A few high-profile technology stocks were higher today. Intel
rose 3| to 123 13/16, helping the Dow contain its losses.
</P>
<P>
   Times Mirror, publisher of the Los Angeles Times, soared 35 5/16
to 83\ on the New York Stock Exchange after Tribune Co., publisher
of the Chicago Tribune, agreed to acquire it for $6.46 billion. The
combined company would have 11 daily newspapers, 22 television
stations, magazines such as Popular Science, and four radio
stations.
</P>
<P>
   Tribune shares fell 7~ to 29 5/16.
</P>
<P>
   NYSE volume was moderate, with 471.29 million shares changing
hands at midday, compared with 555.39 at the same time on Friday.
Decliners outnumbered advancers by a 9-to-5 margin on the NYSE and
by a 7-to-3 margin on the Nasdaq.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
