<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Customs Cracking Down on Ecstasy  </HEADLINE>
By JEANNINE AVERSA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Customs Service is taking steps to crack
down on trafficking in Ecstasy as record amounts of the
hallucinogenic drug popular with teen-agers pour into the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   ''Ecstasy has rapidly become a major concern for Customs,''
Customs Commissioner Raymond Kelly said today in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   The agency has created a task force to coordinate all cases
dealing with the drug and is training 13 drug-detection dogs to
specifically sniff out the drug.
</P>
<P>
   And, Kelly posted a message on Custom's Web site seeking to
educate parents and young people about the drug and its dangers.
</P>
<P>
   ''The new measures we're taking are designed to keep the Ecstasy
problem from becoming a full-fledged epidemic,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Since Oct. 1, Customs has seized nearly 4 million doses of the
drug -- an all-time high, officials said. For fiscal year 1999,
which ended Sept. 30, Customs inspectors confiscated 3 million
doses of the drug and in the 1998 fiscal year, they seized 750,000
doses.
</P>
<P>
   In Europe -- where many of the tablets come from -- the drug costs
just a few pennies a piece to make, Kelly said. But once the
tablets are sold in the United States, they can fetch $20 to $40
each, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Because of this profit margin, international crime groups have
become heavily involved in the Ecstasy trade,'' Kelly said. ''These
syndicates are capable of smuggling huge quantities of Ecstasy.''
</P>
<P>
   Customs said the drug is popular among teen-agers, especially
those who frequent nightclubs and all-night techno-dance parties
known as ''raves.''
</P>
<P>
   Urban areas remain the primary venues for raves, Customs said.
But raves are also creeping up in suburban and rural communities--
and with those parties comes the illegal use of Ecstasy, the agency
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ecstasy's users usually experience feelings of euphoria and an
increased desire to interact socially, Customs said. Blood
pressure, heart rate and body temperature increase dramatically.
Other physical symptoms include involuntary teeth-grinding and
dehydration.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Customs site and Kelly's message:
http://www.customs.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-13-00 1241 </TRAILER>
