<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 14:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> BUSINESS SPOTLIGHT: Comcast digital cable battles satellite TV  </HEADLINE>
By BILL BERGSTROM, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- As cable and satellite companies scramble
for viewers, the nation's third-largest cable provider hopes a
fast-growing digital service will make sure customers want dishes
only on the dinner table.
</P>
<P>
   Comcast Cable, a key player in mergers that reshaped the
telecommunications industry in the past year, is battling to stay
among the leaders by marketing 185-channel digital cable TV to
compete with the hundreds of channels satellite TV can offer.
</P>
<P>
   More than 550,000 customers have signed up for the digital
service, which nearly doubles the channels regular cable offers,
and lets them flip through new choices including 10 HBO channels
and 40 CD-quality, commercial-free music channels.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is a product which is competitive with satellite,'' Stephen
B. Burke, president of Comcast Cable, said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Burke said upgrading cable lines for digital service also helps
in the competition over whether other communications services reach
homes through cable TV lines, digital subscriber phone lines or
satellite dishes.
</P>
<P>
   Comcast is already marketing Comcast@Home Internet access on
systems it has upgraded with fiber-optic lines, offering download
speeds up to 100 times faster than on dial-up connections.
Comcast@Home subscribers more than doubled last year to about
150,000.
</P>
<P>
   In a year or two, customers also will be able to make phone
calls over Comcast cable lines, predicted Burke, who worked at The
Walt Disney Co. as president of ABC Broadcasting before joining
Comcast in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   And consumers will expect all those capabilities as
telecommunications companies move toward ''bundled'' services and
billing packages, said Jeffrey Kagan, an industry analyst based
outside Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ''Consumer service providers can't afford to be boxed into the
corner selling just one service. That's why they are all expanding
their core businesses. If they don't, they can't compete for a
growing universe of customers who are interested in buying multiple
services from one provider,'' Kagan said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year brought big expansion for Comcast, though it was
outbid for the No. 4 cable company, MediaOne, by AT&AMP;T. AT&AMP;T became
the leading cable company, controlling connections to 25 million
homes, followed by Time Warner with about 13 million.
</P>
<P>
   A strong No. 3, Comcast, which started 1999 with 4.5 million
customers, projects that it will finish this year with more than
8.2 million. Comcast has 1.16 million customers in New Jersey, and
operates in every county except Passaic and Sussex.
</P>
<P>
   The company has also been successful in the scramble for
telecommunications content, which is just as intense as the race
for customers.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the merger by AOL, the largest Internet company,
with Time Warner was as important for bringing big-name content
sources such as Time magazine, Warner Bros. studios, CNN and HBO
into the AOL fold as for adding cable TV lines to deliver
high-speed Internet service to homes.
</P>
<P>
   Comcast has a two-thirds share in Comcast-Spectacor, owner of
the Philadelphia Flyers hockey team and Philadelphia 76ers
basketball team, and a 40 percent share of E! Entertainment
Television.
</P>
<P>
   Helping its bottom line, along with cable-division revenues that
rose 9 percent to more than $3 billion last year, were revenues
from its QVC shopping-channel subsidiary that jumped 19 percent to
$2.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The growth makes the Philadelphia-based company ''a key player
in the consolidating and rapidly converging telecommunications
landscape,'' according to an analysis by Jessica Reif Cohen, an
analyst for Merrill Lynch. ''We believe Comcast will continue to be
a consolidator.''
</P>
<P>
   Comcast is actively pursuing more merger and expansion
opportunities, Burke confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are big enough now so that we can compete effectively. This
is a business we believe in and we would like to get bigger,'' he
said, though he wouldn't name any potential merger partners.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Burke said about one in 10 customers now opts
for the digital cable TV service, which adds $9.95 a month to a
regular cable bill.
</P>
<P>
   More than 550,000 customers have signed up since the service was
introduced in a few areas in July 1998, and Comcast officials
predict the number will top 1 million this year.
</P>
<P>
   ''You can get this without having to buy a dish, without having
to have somebody come to your house and get up on your roof and
install the dish, and it's $10 a month,'' said Burke.
</P>
<P>
   He wielded a big digital-cable remote control, a couch-potato's
dream with buttons to do everything but run to the kitchen for
chips. It will be able to order pizza, as interactive TV and online
capabilities grow.
</P>
<P>
   Viewers can scroll up and down through the channel guide instead
of just watching it roll by, and Burke counted 56 movies available
on a recent afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   In a year or two, digital cable boxes will come with a hard
drive that increases the system's flexibility, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's 56 movies, but not all available when I want to
watch,'' said Burke. ''In the future you will be able to watch
'Sour Grapes' on demand.''
</P>
<P>
   ''What people want is more choice,'' he said. ''They want the
ability to have a movie when they want it, they want the ability to
stop the movie. In the future, you will be able to get a movie
exactly when you want it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-13-00 1459 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
