<HEADLINE> European Stocks Close Lower  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Heavy losses in telecommunications, technology and
media stocks forced European stocks lower Monday.
</P>
<P>
   European investors were skittish after stocks fell in Asia.
Japan's Nikkei Stock Average dropped 2.8 percent Monday, helped in
part by a negative economic report, and Hong Kong's Hang Seng Index
dropped 4.1 percent as investors cashed in on recent gains in
technology stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones Stoxx Index of European companies fell 9.40 points
to 392.86, while the Dow Jones Euro Stoxx Index -- which tracks
companies in countries joining the single currency -- fell 12.48
points to 449.49. The Dow Jones Euro Stoxx 50 Index finished down
162.40 points to 5,254.41, while the DJ Stoxx 50 Index lost 131.04
points to 4,998.94 .
</P>
<P>
   The DJ Stoxx media sector ticker lost 4.3 percent, telecoms fell
3.2 percent and technology dropped 3.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Among European telecommunication stocks, Deutsche Telekom fell
5.6 percent, British Telecom fell 3.9 percent and France Telecom
dropped 4.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Vivendi fell 4.0 percent and Canal Plus lost 10 percent on
reports that British Telecom could mount a legal challenge against
the recent Vivendi-Vodafone Internet and telecom alliance.
</P>
<P>
   In domestic markets, the FTSE 100 finished down 1.5 percent, to
close at 6,466.9.
</P>
<P>
   Frankfurt's Xetra DAX index closed down 3.5 percent to 7,693.85,
the Paris CAC 40 index fell 2.7 percent to 6,336.93, Amsterdam's
AEX lost 2.7 percent to 658.06 and Milan's MIBTEL ended 2.2 percent
lower to 33,899.
</P>
</TEXT>
