<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawyer: Lebanese Leader Assaulted  </HEADLINE>
By MARK LAVIE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- A Lebanese guerrilla leader sued Israel for
$1.5 million in damages Monday, saying Israeli soldiers raped and
tortured him in an effort to extract information about a missing
airman.
</P>
<P>
   The army spokesman's office said in a statement that the army
was not familiar with the allegations and that it would examine the
lawsuit when it receives it.
</P>
<P>
   Israel abducted Mustafa Dirani -- head of a small pro-Iranian
militia, the Believers' Resistance -- from south Lebanon in May 1994
in an attempt to win the release of Ron Arad, an air force
navigator captured in Lebanon in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Dirani charged in his suit, filed in the Tel Aviv District
Court, that Israeli soldiers tortured him in the month after his
kidnapping. Dirani was beaten, violently shaken, deprived of sleep
and photographed naked, said his Israeli attorney, Zvi Rish.
</P>
<P>
   The detainee was raped by a soldier brought in especially for
the purpose in the presence of other soldiers, the suit said.
Later, according to the suit, the head of the interrogation team
sodomized Dirani with a broomstick, leaving him with severe
hemorrhaging.
</P>
<P>
   Rish said Dirani first hinted at the rape in a conversation
several weeks ago, and needed to be persuaded to file the
complaint.
</P>
<P>
   The Shin Bet security service is usually responsible for
interrogating security prisoners. However, lawmaker Gideon Ezra,
who was a senior Shin Bet official at the time of the alleged rape,
said it was soldiers who interrogated Dirani in the first month
after his capture.
</P>
<P>
   Tomer Feffer, spokesman for the Israeli human rights group
Betselem, said that his organization knew of a few cases in the
last 10 years in which Shin Bet and army interrogators sexually
assaulted prisoners, but never a case of rape.
</P>
<P>
   Dirani was security chief of the Shiite Muslim Amal militia when
the militia captured Arad. Dirani later formed his own group, the
Believers' Resistance.
</P>
<P>
   Altogether, 21 Lebanese citizens have been held in Israel for
long periods as bargaining chips to trade for Arad. Five of the
Lebanese were freed in December. The Tel Aviv District Court has
twice ordered the release of the others, but the state appealed to
the Supreme Court, which has yet to rule.
</P>
<P>
   Arad was captured alive, but has not been heard from in more
than a decade.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
