<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 3:10 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
Monday, March 13, 2000
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tribune To Take Over Times Mirror
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Tribune Co. will acquire Times Mirror Co. in
a $6.46 billion deal that would create a multimedia empire
encompassing the Los Angeles Times, the Chicago Tribune and 22
television stations, ending a family dynasty that dates to 1882.
The transaction creates the nation's third-largest newspaper
company and marks the end of Times Mirror. The Chandler family,
which has controlled the Times for 118 years and owns a majority of
Times Mirror voting shares, initiated the negotiations and supports
the deal, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna To Split Into Two Companies
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Aetna Inc., the nation's largest health insurer,
has rejected a $10 billion takeover offer and instead plans to
split its health care and financial services businesses into two
publicly traded companies. Its stock skidded 9 percent in late
afternoon trading, dropping 5\ to 50} on the New York Stock
Exchange. Aetna, troubled by rising medical costs, several class
action lawsuits and cold relations with doctors and hospitals, said
it plans to make the split into two companies by the end of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   FCC Seeks Airwaves Trading System
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The federal government is developing plans to
treat airwaves as commodities to be bought and sold on the open
market. Federal Communications Commission officials say they are
working on rules that would create a trading system in which
telecommunications companies could bid on frequencies that are
owned by other companies but are underused. For example, license
holders that aren't using all of their frequencies could post that
availability on a Web site for other interested companies.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks Edge Back After Steep Drop
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks edged back from a steep early decline
today, but remained mostly lower in the wake of a widespread
selloff abroad. Technology shares came under intense selling
pressure following the dramatic rise in the sector in recent weeks.
The Nasdaq composite index was down 71.04 at 4,977.58 in late
afternoon trading, falling from the record high of 5,048.62 reached
on Friday. Analysts attributed the wave of selling to investors
eager to lock in profits from the Nasdaq's sharp rise this year.
</P>
<P>
   Financial Figures
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Financial figures just before 3 p.m. EST:
