</P>
<P>
   Chip Maker Infineon Doubles Worth
</P>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- Semiconductor maker Infineon
Technologies AG nearly doubled its share price today in Germany's
biggest initial public offering since Deutsche Telekom went on the
block in 1996. The spinoff of electronics giant Siemens AG closed
at 69.80 euros ($67) as investors rushed to get in on the deal,
oversubscribing the issue 33 times. The closing price was nearly
double the issue price of 35 euros ($33.60) a share. Infineon's
U.S. shares opened at $66 on the New York Stock Exchange, and
traded at $72.31\ early in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Fiat, GM Form $2.4 Billion Deal
</P>
<P>
   TURIN, Italy (AP) -- General Motors Corp., the world's largest
automaker, is taking a 20 percent stake in Italy's Fiat Auto SpA in
exchange for $2.4 billion in stock -- equivalent to 5.1 percent of
GM. The companies said the partnership would focus on Europe and
Latin America. They expect annual savings to reach $2 billion
within the next five years. The deal covers Fiat's Alfa Romeo and
Lancia brands. The deal will include joint ventures in purchasing,
engine development and auto financing.
</P>
<P>
   China Resolved To Enter WTO
</P>
<P>
   BEIJING (AP) -- Congress' denial of permanent low-tariff trading
rights wouldn't deter China's resolve to join the World Trade
Organization and could cause the United States to gamble away
business opportunities for a generation, China's foreign trade
minister said today. If Congress rejects normal trade relations,
Beijing could invoke a WTO rule allowing it to deny U.S. companies
access to the Chinese market.
</P>
<P>
   China Eases Foreign Software Limits
</P>
<P>
   SHANGHAI, China (AP) -- China relaxed new rules on using foreign
software to transmit sensitive data after an outcry by high-tech
firms and warnings that the rules could have crippled mobile phone
companies and other promising services. Foreign companies were told
last week that rules issued in October won't apply to telephones,
Internet browsers or computer operating systems, the U.S.-China
Business Council announced today. However, the rules still cover
software and equipment meant primarily to encode data.
</P>
<P>
   EU Backs Koehler for IMF Job
</P>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- Germany secured unanimous European
Union backing today for its second choice to head the International
Monetary Fund, and prepared to seek U.S. support for Horst Koehler.
Washington blocked Germany's first-choice candidate, Caio
Koch-Weser, claiming the deputy finance minister lacked the
international standing needed to run the 182-nation IMF. German
Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder was expected to call President Clinton
to seek his endorsement of Koehler, EU officials said.
</P>
<P>
   NASD Polls Members on Market Spinoff
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The brokers' group that operates the Nasdaq
Stock Market has started polling its members on the proposed
spinoff of the electronic Nasdaq into a for-profit organization.
The votes, one for each of the National Association of Securities
Dealers' 5,500 or so member brokerage firms, will be counted at a
special meeting on April 14. If a majority approves the
restructuring, the first phase of a massive private sale of shares
in Nasdaq will be completed in late April or May.
</P>
<P>
   Japan Mired in New Recession
</P>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese officials remained optimistic about the
future of Japan's economy today, despite economic results from last
year showing the country mired in a new recession. The government
revealed today that gross domestic product, the total value of
goods and services, fell 1.4 percent in the October-December
quarter due in part to a 1.6 percent drop in private consumption.
It was the second consecutive quarter of GDP decline, meaning the
economy was officially back in recession.
</P>
<P>
   i2 Technologies Buys Aspect
</P>
<P>
   DALLAS (AP) --Software developer i2 Technologies Inc. is buying
Aspect Development Inc. for about $9.3 billion in stock in a deal
that would be one of the largest in the software industry. Mountain
View, Calif.-based Aspect Development would become a subsidiary of
Dallas-based i2 under the deal announced today. They each
specialize in making software that helps companies conduct business
with other companies.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, Andersen Form $1B Deal
</P>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. (AP) -- Microsoft Corp. and Andersen Consulting
are forming a joint venture to offer electronic commerce, Internet
and other computing services to large corporations. The venture, to
be called Avanade, will have a work force of 3,000 technical
experts and be headquartered in the Seattle area. It also plans to
open branch offices in San Francisco, Dallas, New York, Paris,
London, Sydney, Sao Paulo and Singapore in the next 18 months.
</P>
