<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 15:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> DNA Match May Crack Old Murder Case  </HEADLINE>
By JIM FITZGERALD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) -- Prosecutors on Monday said they
cracked a 21-year-old murder case, connecting a robber to the
stabbing through New York state's newly expanded DNA database.
</P>
<P>
   A DNA match linked Walter Gill to the death of Diane Gregory
''like the finger of God pointing down and saying, 'You can't get
away with it no matter how long it's been,''' said District
Attorney Jeanine Pirro.
</P>
<P>
   The second-degree murder charge against Gill, 49, was the first
to be brought as a result of the 1999 state law that expanded the
state's database on criminals, adding robbery to the offenses
requiring a convict to submit a DNA sample, Pirro said.
</P>
<P>
   Gill, 49, is serving a 10-to-20 year robbery sentence and would
have been eligible for parole in May 2001. If convicted of murder,
he could be sentenced to 25 years to life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   The Gregory case was reopened after the victim's family
questioned if DNA technology could be applied to blood found near
the 22-year-old's apartment that police suspected came from the
attacker.
</P>
<P>
   Gill had been a suspect in the August 1979 murder, but police
never had enough evidence to get a court order for a blood sample.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new law, he submitted a sample in January, and some of
the blood from the murder scene matched Gill's profile, Pirro said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It appeared that he knew when the blood was taken that sooner
or later he'd be caught,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Gregory's daughter, Lakisha Gregory, who was 2 when her mother
was killed, said through tears: ''I'm very happy. I'm just very
upset that I didn't have a mother to grow up with.''
</P>
<P>
   The break in the case lends support to a proposal to require DNA
samples from almost anyone convicted of a state crime, Gov. George
Pataki said. That pending bill, backed by the governor, would add
an estimated 120,000 samples to the databank each year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
