<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 15:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sharif Trial Adjourned in Pakistan  </HEADLINE>
By ZAHID HUSSAIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   KARACHI, Pakistan (AP) -- A Pakistani judge adjourned the trial
of former prime minister Nawaz Sharif on Monday to consider the
defense lawyers' demand for a change of venue following the killing
of one of their colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to call off the day's proceedings came after
Sharif's attorneys failed to show up in court Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers say they fear for their safety and want the trial
moved out of the southern city of Karachi, where a lead attorney in
the case, Iqbal Raad, was gunned down Friday by three men who
stormed his second-story law office.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Rehmetullah Hussein Jaffri said he wanted to give Sharif
time to consult his attorneys about their demand to move the trial
either to Lahore, the capital of eastern Punjab province, or to the
federal capital of Islamabad.
</P>
<P>
   The former prime minister has not said whether he supports such
a move, and told the court Monday he had only read of the boycott
by his attorneys ''in the newspapers.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I haven't had any contact with them, and their decision has
not been taken with my knowledge,'' Sharif said in a statement to
the court.
</P>
<P>
   Sharif also expressed concern over Raad's murder, saying it had
''sent shock waves not only through this country but also
internationally.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It exposes the government's failure to provide security not
only to the lawyers defending us but to the common people,'' he
said. ''His brutal killing was meant to quiet a brave voice.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharif, his younger brother, Shahbaz, and five other close aides
have been jailed since a military coup Oct. 12 toppled Pakistan's
elected government. The former prime minister has denied the
charges of hijacking, treason, kidnapping and attempted murder.
</P>
<P>
   Sharif is accused of refusing to allow a passenger plane
carrying army chief Gen. Pervez Musharraf to land in Karachi. The
plane eventually landed, but the pilot has testified that it had
only seven minutes of fuel remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the aircraft landed, Musharraf -- with the backing
of Pakistan's powerful military -- seized power from Sharif in a
bloodless coup.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecution lawyer Raja Quereshi told the court today that the
Karachi-based Sindh provincial government has offered Sharif's
lawyers additional security.
</P>
<P>
   The trial was scheduled to resume on Tuesday when the
prosecution is expected to ask the judge to allow the case to go
ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, lawyers throughout Pakistan went on strike to protest
Raad's killing, which police said was still under investigation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-13-00 1539 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
