<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ex Secretaries of State Back Clinton  </HEADLINE>
By BARRY SCHWEID, AP Diplomatic Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Six former secretaries of state signed on to
President Clinton's campaign for low-tariff trading rights for
China.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Clinton, they said giving China both permanent
access to U.S. markets without high tariff barriers and membership
in the World Trade Organization are ''critically important tools''
for moving China toward a more open society.
</P>
<P>
   The six are Henry A. Kissinger, Alexander M. Haig, George P.
Shultz, James A. Baker III, Lawrence Eagleburger and Warren
Christopher.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is in our long-term interest -- and that of others in the
international community -- to develop a relationship with China that
is stable and predictable,'' they said.
</P>
<P>
   If the Clinton initiative is accepted by Congress, China no
longer would depend on annual congressional approval to ship its
products to the United States at normal tariffs. China's huge
market also would be opened wider to American exports.
</P>
<P>
   Some opponents, including human rights advocates, argue that
abandoning an annual review would eliminate a potent weapon in
trying to influence China's policies.
</P>
<P>
   Senate supporters of the measure count a thin majority for
approval. The outcome in the House is more uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright announced the backing of
six predecessors Monday. She added that China's entry into the
World Trade Organization ''would encourage the rule of law and spur
the development of a more open society.''
</P>
<P>
   In Beijing, the Chinese foreign trade minister, Shi Guangsheng,
said if Congress refused to grant his government permanent
low-tariff trading rights China would deny American companies
access to Chinese markets. That, he said, would cause the United
States ''regret, for 20 years, for a generation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
