<HEADLINE> Weather Boosts Grains, Soybeans  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean prices shot higher Monday on
the Chicago Board of Trade amid drought concerns in the central
United States and soybean harvest delays in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   Soybean futures surged nearly 3 percent to a three-week high
after the National Weather Service said U.S. farmers face a serious
threat this year from a ''worsening drought'' in the wake of the
warmest winter on record.
</P>
<P>
   Also supporting prices were weekend rains that didn't meet
expectations in midwestern U.S. crop areas, as well as continuing
rains in central Brazil that are holding back harvest progress.
</P>
<P>
   Corn rose nearly as sharply as soybeans as investors and farmers
fretted about the dryness that has been prevalent in the Midwest
since last summer -- its impact growing as spring planting season
nears. Prices hit a two-week high.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat was buoyed by the same weather worries and by the rallies
in soybeans and corn. But the buying wave was not as large as for
those commodities, with the big commodity funds not as bullish on
wheat.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat for May delivery rose 3{ cents to $2.63{ a bushel; May
corn rose 4 cents to $2.30} a bushel; May oats rose 1} cent to
$1.18\ a bushel; May soybeans rose 13\ cents to $5.23 a bushel.
</P>
<P>
   Beef and pork futures declined on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   April live cattle fell .15 cent to 72.45 cents a pound; April
feeder cattle fell .43 cent to 83.92 cents a pound; April lean hogs
fell .15 cent to 61.90 cents a pound; May pork bellies fell .02
cent to 93.35 cents a pound.
</P>
</TEXT>
