<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Resolved To Enter WTO  </HEADLINE>
By ELAINE KURTENBACH, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING (AP) -- Congress' denial of permanent low-tariff trading
rights wouldn't deter China's resolve to join the World Trade
Organization and could cause the United States to gamble away
business opportunities for a generation, China's foreign trade
minister said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   If Congress rejects normal trade relations, Beijing could invoke
a WTO rule allowing it to deny U.S. companies access to the Chinese
market, causing the United States ''regret for 20 years, for a
generation,'' Shi Guangsheng suggested.
</P>
<P>
   Shi's comments were the clearest indication so far that China
intends to seek entry into WTO, regardless of what the U.S.
Congress does and despite the risks market opening will bring to
its own struggling economy.
</P>
<P>
   ''If the United States misses this opportunity, it will actually
lose the tremendous market of China and will be giving away the
opportunity for participating in this market to its competitors,''
Shi said at a news conference on the sidelines of the annual
session of the National People's Congress, China's legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Beijing can gain membership after it has reached accords with
all 135 member countries and after two-thirds of WTO members
approve. Agreements with just 10 countries still need to be
reached, and in most cases all that was required was the signing,
Shi said.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, President Clinton sent the proposal to make normal
trade benefits permanent to Congress, where labor and environmental
groups are lobbying against it. The administration, business and
most congressional Republicans support the China trade deal, and
there appears to be enough support to pass the U.S. Senate, but
support in the House remains in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton promised the proposal as part of a market-access deal
Shi and U.S. Trade Representative Charlene Barshefsky signed in
November to allow Beijing to join WTO, the Geneva-based
organization that oversees world trade rules. Clinton called the
trade deal a ''once in a generation'' opportunity, sentiments
echoed by Shi in his comments.
</P>
<P>
   Six former secretaries of state threw their support behind
Clinton on Monday, saying in a letter that the measure was
''critically important'' to helping move China toward a more open
society.
</P>
<P>
   The letter was signed by Henry A. Kissinger, Alexander M. Haig
Jr., George P. Shultz, James A. Baker III, Lawrence Eagleburger and
Warren Christopher.
</P>
<P>
   China is the only major U.S. trading partner whose normal
trading status -- previously called most-favored nation status --
must be renewed annually. A positive vote by Congress would assure
China of the same access to U.S. markets and lowest-possible
tariffs that other nations now have.
</P>
<P>
   Shi said China was close to reaching a bilateral agreement with
the European Union, the largest of the trading partners with which
it has yet to reach agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ''Except for a few demands China is unable to commit to for any
trading partner, there are not many remaining issues,'' Shi said.
</P>
<P>
   The other countries that have not signed WTO deals with China
are Malaysia, Kyrgyzstan, Poland, Latvia, Switzerland, Mexico,
Costa Rica, Guatemala and Ecuador.
</P>
<P>
   The recovery of neighboring countries from the Asian financial
crisis and government policies to stimulate the economy and
encourage exports have helped China's trade performance, as has
progress in revamping inefficient and uncompetitive state-owned
enterprises, Shi said.
</P>
<P>
   China's exports surged 41.2 percent to $31.57 billion in the
first two months of this year compared to the same period the year
before, he reported, saying this trend showed the country's trade
competitiveness was improving.
</P>
<P>
   Shi said exports rose 6.1 percent in 1999 to $194.9 billion,
while imports climbed 18.2 percent to $165.8 billion, leaving a
trade surplus of $29.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But China remains vulnerable to setbacks. The Asian economic
recovery remained fragile, and many industries are not competitive,
Shi said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are sober-minded about the challenges and pressures that
WTO membership will bring, especially for technically backward,
small enterprises with poor operation and poor management. The
pressure on those enterprises will be intense,'' Shi said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Shi insisted that the benefits of WTO membership far
outweighed the risks.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is no economy that has collapsed as a result of joining
WTO. On the contrary, WTO membership has promoted economic
development for all of them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
