<HEADLINE> Argentina Flood Toll Rises To 10  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) -- Steady rains continued to fall
Monday across northwestern Argentina, extending a week of heavy
rainfall and flooding that has left 10 people dead and forced some
15,000 people to evacuate their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities reported two deaths Monday in the central city of
Cordoba, 475 miles northwest of Buenos Aires. Cordoba was hit by
torrential rains, hail and blustery winds Sunday that left much of
the city without drinking water or electricity.
</P>
<P>
   Waters from the overflowing Suquia River uprooted trees and
flooded homes in Cordoba, Argentina's second-largest city.
Authorities worked Monday to restore services and transport food,
clothes and medical supplies to the rain-soaked provinces in the
northwest.
</P>
<P>
   Heavy rains and floods killed eight other people last week.
Meteorologists predicted more rain Tuesday in Cordoba and other
parts of the region.
</P>
</TEXT>
