<DOCNO> APW20000313.0109 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 16:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Atlantic City, neighboring towns to get $52 million beachreplenishment  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN CURRAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) -- It's part of the routine, up and down
the Jersey shore: As the sun sets, the lifeguards move their wooden
stands and surfboats away from the water.
</P>
<P>
   Lifeguards at some beaches here can't do that anymore. Erosion
has clawed away at the beach near Martin Luther King Jr. Drive. At
high tide, ocean water rushes up under the Boardwalk.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't even have enough room in summer to store our
equipment. We have to move the boats and stands every night,'' said
Bob Levy, chief of the Atlantic City Beach Patrol.
</P>
<P>
   Relief is on the way -- for Atlantic City and its fellow Absecon
Island communities of Ventnor, Margate and Longport.
</P>
<P>
   A $52 million beach replenishment project is to begin after
Labor Day, dredging more than 3 million cubic yards of sand from
the ocean floor near Absecon Inlet and piping it onto thinning
beaches.
</P>
<P>
   ''The whole island really needs a good beach fill,'' said
Bernard Moore, director of coastal engineering for the state
Department of Environmental Protection. ''Atlantic City hasn't had
one since the early 1970s.''
</P>
<P>
   To complete the whole project in 2000 and 2001, however, more
federal money is needed, he said. The state's representatives will
ask for $23 million in fiscal year 2001, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the replenishment, project plans call for the
building of dunes parallel to the boardwalks and sea walls of the
island. That aspect of the project is getting a cool reception in
Ventnor because of concerns about beach access.
</P>
<P>
   Some people are worried that the dunes will grow over time,
obscuring ocean views from million-dollar homes and the Boardwalk
itself.
</P>
<P>
   ''Here, we've dodged the bullet when it comes to storms. We
haven't been seriously hurt at all,'' said city Business
Administrator William Thomas. ''So people are blase about why we
need this. They're more worried about the engineered beach and the
disruption it'll bring to their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas said city officials have concerns about dune growth, too.
If they expand up under the Boardwalk, restricting air flow,
Boardwalk wood could get wet and rot away, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have a chance to take part in a program that will cost us a
little money but has the potential to protect property and our
Boardwalk, which a lot of people think is our biggest asset. If we
don't do it, and we get the storm everyone knows we'll eventually
get and it destroys our Boardwalk, what will FEMA say? My concern
is they'll come in and say 'You had a chance to mitigate it and you
didn't,''' Thomas said. FEMA is the Federal Emergency Management
Agency.
</P>
<P>
   Others have concerns about beach replenishment, too. Critics
have long blasted it as taxpayer-funded insurance for wealthy
oceanfront property owners. Supporters, on the other hand, say
beach replenishment protects the businesses that draw visitors --
and money -- to beach communities.
</P>
<P>
   A recent report by the American Littoral Society, the New Jersey
Audubon Society, Taxpayers for Common Sense and the National
Wildlife Federation targeting government spending called New
Jersey's beach-building projects Uncle Sam's ninth-biggest waste of
money.
</P>
<P>
   ''The shore doesn't need to be protected, houses do,'' said
Elizabeth Hanratty, a spokeswoman for the American Littoral
Society. ''It's a vicious cycle. The national flood insurance
program is subsidized by the government and so is beach protection.
Our tax dollars are paying for them to stay there, and if they get
damaged, we're paying again to keep them there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-13-00 1645 </TRAILER>
