<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Police Detain Kurdish Leader  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BATMAN, Turkey (AP) -- Police detained a deputy head of Turkey's
only legal Kurdish party on Monday for a speech he made during a
meeting with a group of village leaders, his party said.
</P>
<P>
   Police did not say on what charges they detained Eyup Karagecili
of the People's Democracy Party. Details of his speech were not
released.
</P>
<P>
   His arrest appeared to be part of a wider crackdown on the
party.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the party's leader, Ahmet Turan Demir, was sentenced
to three years in prison for holding a hunger strike in 1998 in
support of Kurdish rebel leader Abdullah Ocalan.
</P>
<P>
   Three mayors of mainly Kurdish southeastern cities were arrested
following meetings with European officials to discuss cultural
rights for Kurds. The mayors, all members of the People's Democracy
Party, were released pending trial on charges of aiding Kurdish
rebels. If found guilty, they face seven years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Karagecili was detained after he walked into a police station to
seek permission to hold a Kurdish spring festival on March 21. He
had met with Kurdish village leaders last week to prepare for the
festival.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our friend's arrest is just a continuation of the hindrances
that officials are putting in the way of our party's activities,''
said Hamit Geylani, a senior party official.
</P>
<P>
   The People's Democracy Party is facing closure on charges of
being a front for Ocalan's Kurdistan Workers Party, or PKK, which
has fought a 15-year war with Turkish forces for Kurdish autonomy.
Some 37,000 people, mostly Kurds, have been killed in the fighting.
</P>
<P>
   The PKK announced a cease-fire last year, and said it wanted to
negotiate peace. Turkey refuses to talk with the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Turkey's approximately 12 million Kurds are not recognized as a
minority. Turkey bans education and broadcasting in Kurdish.
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Human Rights Watch:
http://www.hrw.org/campaigns/turkey/index.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
