<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 16:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Jets Hit Palestinian Base  </HEADLINE>
By ZEINA KARAM, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) -- Israeli-allied militiamen unleashed a
barrage of shells Monday on a coastal village in south Lebanon,
killing two people and wounding one, a Lebanese security official
said.
</P>
<P>
   The attack on the village of Mansouri hit a Lebanese army
checkpoint, said the official, speaking on condition of anonymity.
A soldier and a passer-by were killed, and another soldier was
wounded. They were taken to a hospital in the southern port city of
Tyre.
</P>
<P>
   Later Monday, the Lebanese army opened fire with tanks on an
Israeli-backed South Lebanon Army position, an army spokesman said.
The Lebanese army rarely gets involved in the southern Lebanon
fighting.
</P>
<P>
   Mansouri, a predominantly Shiite Muslim village six miles south
of Tyre, sits below SLA outposts on the edge of the
Israeli-occupied zone.
</P>
<P>
   Lebanese security sources said the SLA attack was apparently
launched in retaliation for an attack by Hezbollah guerrillas on
the village of Hardon, a hilly position controlled by the SLA
militia inside the security zone.
</P>
<P>
   An official in the northern command confirmed the SLA in Hardon
had come under fire from Mansouri, but said he did not know if the
SLA returned fire.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli army radio quoted foreign news agencies as saying one
Lebanese civilian was killed and another wounded in the SLA fire on
Mansouri.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Monday, Israeli jets blasted suspected Hezbollah
positions in southern Lebanon with more than a dozen missiles and
pounded radical Palestinian guerrilla bases near the Syrian border,
Lebanese security officials said.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear what prompted the air raid on Syrian-backed Fatah
Uprising, which came two days after an Arab ministers' meeting in
Beirut condemned Israeli attacks on Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first major onslaught since 1998 on Palestinian
guerrillas opposed to Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat's peace
deals with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Lebanese officials said the attack destroyed three multiple
rocket launchers, a 130mm artillery gun and a transport truck.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Fatah Uprising reported no casualties and
pledged to continue to fight and oppose the ''shameful and
humiliating'' peace deals between Arafat and Israel.
</P>
<P>
   But local reporters said they saw an armed guerrilla at the
scene with blood dripping from his hand.
</P>
<P>
   Near the front line in southern Lebanon, Israeli jets staged two
air raids on suspected Hezbollah positions, firing a total of eight
missiles following earlier Hezbollah attacks against the Israeli
mountaintop outpost of Beaufort.
</P>
<P>
   There was no independent word on casualties from Monday's raids.
</P>
<P>
   The fighting underscored the potential for violence at a time
when Israel has promised to withdraw from an occupied zone in
southern Lebanon by July.
</P>
<P>
   Israel said it would prefer to pull out with an agreement with
Syria, the main power-broker in Lebanon, but would proceed without
one. Israel has threatened heavy retaliation for post-pullout
attacks on Israel's northern borders.
</P>
<P>
   Lebanon said it could not guarantee calm along the border if
Israel pulled out without reaching peace with Lebanon, Syria and
the Palestinians first.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Prime Minister Salim Hoss again warned that
unilateral withdrawal could lead to an escalation in violence, and
urged Israel ''to avoid the dangers and risks of a withdrawal that
is not part of a settlement.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of thousands of Palestinian refugees live in Lebanon,
and officials warn that militants among them might attack northern
Israel following a troop pullout.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
