<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 17:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Aetna's Plan Makes Its Stock Sink  </HEADLINE>
By PHIL GALEWITZ, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Investors dumped shares of beleaguered Aetna
Inc. on Monday, a day after the nation's largest health insurer
rejected a $10 billion takeover bid and unveiled plans to split its
health care and financial services businesses into two publicly
traded companies.
</P>
<P>
   ''A lot of people had a lot of hopes for this takeover,'' said
David Shove, an analyst for Prudential Securities. ''A lot people
are disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   Aetna, hurt by rising medical costs, several class-action
lawsuits and cold relations with doctors and hospitals, said it
plans to divide the company by the end of the year. It was unclear
which business would keep the name of the company founded in 1853.
</P>
<P>
   ''The decision to separate health and wealth businesses should
create more value for shareholders,'' William H. Donaldson, who was
named chairman and CEO in a management shakeup last month, said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But the move was panned by some securities analysts because it
does nothing to fix the company's struggling health insurance
business. The Hartford, Conn.-based Aetna's stock slipped 9
percent, dropping $5.25 to $50.75 on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna on Sunday rejected a $70-a-share takeover bid offered last
month from WellPoint Health Networks Inc., a California
managed-care company, and ING Group, a Dutch investment bank and
insurer. WellPoint wanted Aetna U.S. HealthCare, while ING was
interested in Aetna's financial services and international arms.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna officials said the bid was too low and they had doubts the
smaller WellPoint would be able to integrate Aetna's larger health
business.
</P>
<P>
   The entire managed care industry has been in a funk for the past
two years due to rising medical costs and threats of federal
legislation that would expand patients right to sue their HMO.
</P>
<P>
   But Aetna, by virtue of its size, has been a lightening rod for
public criticism of managed care. It also has struggled to digest
recent acquisitions of Prudential HealthCare and NYLCare.
</P>
<P>
   Further, the company faces several lawsuits filed by the same
attorneys who successfully went after Big Tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna's former CEO and chairman Richard Huber resigned last
month under the weight of Aetna's falling stock price. Aetna's
stock, which traded as high as $99.87{ last May, has been under
renewed pressure as the company's first quarter results found it
unable to control medical costs as good as the competition.
</P>
<P>
   A bit more than two weeks into his new job, Donaldson has moved
quickly to undo many of Huber's plans.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to eliminating Huber's reorganization plan,
Donaldson said Aetna plans to sell up to half of the firm's
international business. Huber had rejected such a strategy and was
trying to build Aetna's brand around the globe.
</P>
<P>
   Donaldson also said Aetna is considering dropping its
much-criticized ''all or nothing'' clause with doctors, that
requires them to either treat Aetna's low-paying HMO patients or
not treat any of Aetna's patients. Some doctors have filed suit
against Aetna to drop the clause because they believe it gave Aetna
too much power over them.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna plans to cut about $150 million in costs by reducing
technology and advertising spending and reducing staff through
attrition, Donaldson said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   He also suggested the company may shift it core health insurance
offerings from highly restrictive health maintenance organizations
to preferred provider organizations (PPO) plans that don't limit
which hospitals and doctors patients can use.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts have said Aetna's financial services business, which
sells annuities and a line of mutual funds, had little in common
with its health insurance business.
</P>
<P>
   ''Long term this is a very logical move,'' Jim Lane, an analyst
with Salomon Smith Barney, said of Aetna's plan to divide. ''But it
doesn't do a whole lot for shareholders in the short term.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Aetna is unlikely to get any more bidders for its health
business, analysts said many companies might still be interested in
its financial services business.
</P>
<P>
   WellPoint said it was disappointed with Aetna's decision, while
ING said it was keeping its options open.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Aetna: http://www.aetna.com
</P>
<P>
   WellPoint Health Networks: http://www.wellpoint.com
</P>
<P>
   ING Group: http://www.inggroup.com
</P>
</TEXT>
