<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sears building, railroads, mills among endangered sites  </HEADLINE>
By AMY WESTFELDT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- A 19th century mill, a road lined by
75-year-old elm trees and a 1927 Sears building in Camden are among
10 historic sites in the state fighting for their lives, a
preservation group says.
</P>
<P>
   Preservation New Jersey released its sixth annual list of the
state's ''most endangered historic sites'' on Monday. It has
released names of 10 new sites each year.
</P>
<P>
   One is Pierson's Mill, a 2{-acre complex in Maplewood that
includes an 1830 grist mill and 1840 home owned for six generations
by the same family. The mill stopped working in 1916, but the
family adapted it into a garden supply center over the years.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a major, major structure in our town,'' said Ginny
Kurshan, a member of Preservation Maplewood. ''It's just been there
forever. It's a link to our agrarian past.''
</P>
<P>
   The mill complex is now on the market for $1.65 million, and
Kurshan and others want the buyer to promise to keep the mill
complex from being torn down.
</P>
<P>
   Another site with an uncertain future is the Westside All Wars
Memorial in Atlantic City, a 1924 building constructed to honor
black veterans of all American wars. The building, with an
auditorium, gymnasium, tennis courts and playgrounds, has served as
a recreation center for Atlantic City's black community.
</P>
<P>
   But a leaky roof has caused damage and supporters fear the city,
which owns the building, will soon demolish it to build a parking
lot for hotel and casino employees.
</P>
<P>
   The list also includes a 1927 Sears Roebuck &AMP; Co. building,
built along Admiral Wilson Boulevard in Camden. The long-vacant,
Greek Revival-style building, one of the most modern department
stores in the world when it was opened, is slated for demolition as
part of a state project to clean up the boulevard before the
Republican National Convention in Philadelphia this summer.
</P>
<P>
   A New Jersey Department of Transportation proposal to realign
part of state Route 571 and remove three traffic lights on Route 1
would destroy 15 of the 76 elm trees that line Washington Road in
West Windsor Township, the preservation group said.
</P>
<P>
   Washington Road Elm Allee, which leads into the Princeton
University campus, is nearly three-quarters of a mile long. The
60-foot-high Princeton elms were planted in 1925, and the road is
on the state and National Registers of Historic Places.
</P>
<P>
   Other sites listed by Preservation New Jersey include:
</P>
<P>
   --Lustron Homes, steel-paneled residences built by the government
to alleviate a post-World War II housing shortage. Only 16 are
believed to exist in New Jersey, and two in Bergen County -- one in
Closter, the other in Alpine -- are in danger of demolition because
of development pressures, the society says.
</P>
<P>
   --Ferracute Machine Company, founded in Bridgeton in the late
1800s by inventor Oberlin Smith, who later became famous for
inventing magnetic recording. The company shut down in 1968 and the
building is vacant and its owner faces bankruptcy problems.
</P>
<P>
   --Hudson and Manhattan Railroad Powerhouse, built between 1906
and 1908 in Jersey City to house the generators that powered the
train stations and tunnels linking New York City and New Jersey.
The city and the Port Authority of New York and New Jersey, which
co-own the vacant, brick structure with ornamental steel-framed
windows, are considering tearing it down to make room for
development along the Jersey City waterfront.
</P>
<P>
   --Morris-Saltar-Hartshorne-Tredwell House, a Rumson home which
passed through four owners, one who operated it as an inn. Part of
the home dates to 1711, making it one of the oldest in the state.
Some residents want to tear it down to build four new homes.
</P>
<P>
   --Hackett-Strang House, an 1864-era farmhouse in Mannington
Township that sits in at least 2,000 contiguous acres of farmland.
Salem County is prepared to buy the farm with farmland preservation
funds that require the owner to protect the farmland, but not the
house, the society says.
</P>
<P>
   --Betsy Frazee House, a Scotch Plains home built between 1720 and
1740 where Lord Cornwallis was said to have stopped with his troops
when he smelled Frazee's baking bread during the Battle of Short
Hills. The building has been neglected for decades.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
