<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clear Channel To Sell 12 Stations  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- Radio One Inc., one of the largest
broadcasting companies targeting black listeners, has agreed to buy
12 stations in seven cities from Clear Channel Communications Inc.
for $1.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio-based Clear Channel is selling about $4 billion
worth of stations to meet regulators' demands for approving its
pending merger with Dallas-based AMFM Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Radio One, based in Lanham, Md., would buy KBFB-FM in Dallas,
KBXX-FM and KMJQ-FM in Houston, KKBT-FM in Los Angeles, WJMO-AM and
WZAK-FM in Cleveland, WVCG-AM in Miami, WJMZ-FM in Greenville,
S.C., and WFXC-FM, WFXK-FM, WNNL-FM and WQOK-FM in Raleigh, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Clear Channel operates 874 radio and 19 television stations in
the United States and has equity interests in more than 240 radio
stations internationally.
</P>
<P>
   Radio One, which also said Monday it will buy six stations in
Charlotte, N.C., and Savannah, Ga., from Davis Broadcasting Inc.,
and three stations in Indianapolis from Shirk Inc., would own 48
stations if the deals are closed.
</P>
<P>
   Radio One chief executive Alfred C. Liggins III said the deal
would transform his company into the second-largest U.S. operator
of urban radio stations.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Clear Channel were down 12{ cents, to $62, in trading
Monday on the New York Stock Exchange. Radio One shares fell $2.31\
to $63.43}.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
