<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Falls Against Yen, Euro  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A slump on Wall Street pushed the dollar to a
six-week low against the Japanese yen on Monday, but the U.S.
currency recovered some of its losses as the stock market recovered
a bit from its early lows.
</P>
<P>
   In late New York trading, the euro was quoted at 96.49 cents, up
from 96.16 cents late Friday. The dollar also was quoted at 105.55
Japanese yen, down from 106.22. The dollar fell to 104.83 yen early
Monday, its lowest level since Jan. 28.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks tumbled on Wall Street in early trading Monday.
Technology shares were especially battered as investors cashed in
on the recent dramatic gains in the sector.
</P>
<P>
   As overseas investors sold their stocks, they then sold their
dollars.
</P>
<P>
   But stocks did manage to bounce back from the early lows,
helping lift the dollar late in the day.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average rose 18.31 to 9,947.13, having
recovered from a loss of as much as 190.49 points within minutes of
the opening of trading.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index, down as much as 209.36 in the early
going, regained some lost ground but still had its fourth-worst
point drop ever. It fell 141.30 to close at 4,907.32.
</P>
<P>
   The slump in U.S. stocks added to an already difficult day for
the dollar against the yen.
</P>
<P>
   Investors shrugged off a new government report showing that
Japanese gross domestic product -- the total value of goods and
services -- fell 1.4 percent in the October-December quarter. It was
the second consecutive quarter of GDP decline, meaning the economy
was technically back in recession.
</P>
<P>
   The disappointing numbers, however, were not considered a sign
that Japan's economy was headed further downhill, and government
officials were quick to point out hopeful indicators, such as a
rise in capital expenditure.
</P>
<P>
   The 4.6 percent increase in corporate capital investment -- the
first rise in nine months -- encouraged many investors to begin
buying yen.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. currency was also lower Monday against the euro on
speculation that the European Central Bank may tighten monetary
policy as early as this week.
</P>
<P>
   A newspaper report said that Wim Duisenberg, president of the
ECB, may boost interest rates at this week's ECB council meeting.
</P>
<P>
   In other trading, the dollar was quoted at 1.6698 Swiss francs,
down from 1.6730, and 1.4617 Canadian dollars, up from 1.4580. The
British pound rose to $1.5785 from $1.5768.
</P>
<P>
   Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate.
</P>
<P>
   Based on Thursday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 2.0269
German marks, down from 2.0333; 6.7978 French francs, down from
6.8194; and 2,006.60 Italian lire, down from 2,012.96.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
