<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Garry Kasparov: touting chess as an aggressive sport, on theInternet  </HEADLINE>
By VERENA DOBNIK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- World chess champion Garry Kasparov travels the
world -- but never with a chessboard.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he trains on a laptop that sat in his Manhattan hotel
suite Monday. Inside were his secret strategies for a worldwide
Internet tournament against 30 young opponents -- all at once, and
live from Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   But Kasparov kept his personal computer far away from any
Internet link.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't want anything to happen to that database, for it to
get out,'' said the Russian, his eyes flashing across the American
room with an amused, sly smile.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, starting at 4 p.m., a giant screen is to broadcast
the Internet games in Times Square while Kasparov's moves are
beamed from a studio behind it. Among his opponents, all teen-agers
or younger, 10 were to play him from chessboards there and 20
others make electronic moves in countries from India to Uruguay,
Indonesia and China, and across the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The ''United Nations of Chess'' is to unroll live at
www.KasparovChess.com. The site, to be officially launched Tuesday,
offers live coverage of international chess events, as well as
lessons aimed at beginners, pick-up games against both humans and
the computer, and chess products.
</P>
<P>
   ''One of my missions in launching this site is to engage more of
the world's children in chess,'' says Kasparov, who has helped
schools all over the globe start chess programs. In New York, a
study showed that disadvantaged kids learning chess have improved
their academic test scores.
</P>
<P>
   ''It teaches them how to assume responsibility for their own
action,'' says Kasparov. ''Because in the game of chess, no one is
going to help you, and at the end of the game, you pay for your
mistakes. If you lose, there's no one to blame.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the top players in Tuesday's games were more than a half
dozen youths from the greater New York area.
</P>
<P>
   Kasparov's site also is hosting the World Chess Championship --
games involving 600 schools that began competing March 1. The
series ends in June, with the winner invited to play Kasparov
face-to-face.
</P>
<P>
   To this champion, his cerebral game is definitely a sport -- the
second most popular after soccer.
</P>
<P>
   But at 36, he's a senior among the best players; most champions
are in their 20s. Kasparov says physical training boosts his
concentration and helps keep him on top of ever-younger rivals. He
swims and rows, and does 100 pushups at a time.
</P>
<P>
   And he trains his mind ''by quarrying information,'' says
Kasparov, gesticulating with the quick, agile movements of an
athlete.
</P>
<P>
   ''For me it's very important to feed my brain with
information,'' he says. ''Unfortunately, there's quite a lot of
garbage around. But still, I believe I could reprocess the
information and find the real flavor.''
</P>
<P>
   The result is his playing style, which he calls ''dynamic chess,
with a lot of aggression.''
</P>
<P>
   From his Moscow home, he roams the world about seven months of
the year.
</P>
<P>
   This week in New York, he spread a huge map on his hotel room
floor. Then he and his 6-year-old daughter Polina crawled around
pegging flags on the countries he has visited, 45 in all. He plans
to take the girl, who lives in New Jersey with his ex-wife, to her
dream spot, the jungles of Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   While he carries a Russian passport, Kasparov is a native of the
former Soviet republic of Azerbaijan, born to a Jewish father.
</P>
<P>
   From his Moscow home, he keeps tabs on Russia's unstable
political scene, occasionally writing newspaper editorials. But
several years ago, when he realized his opinions couldn't change
Russia's course, he decided to focus on the field where ''I can
make a difference,'' he says -- chess and education.
</P>
<P>
   And now, high-tech chess.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet is an ideal medium for the game, which has all but
failed on television against more visually active sports. ''On
television, basketball looks better, tennis looks much better,''
says Kasparov. ''On the Internet, it's the other way around. We can
establish the link between chess and the crowd.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with his new activity, the remarried father of a
3-year-old son has ''put some more order in my life,'' he says.
''If your mind is disturbed, if you are jumping from one subject to
another, it's difficult to generate enough energy for winning, and
resisting tension.''
</P>
<P>
   And everybody, he adds, ''expects me to win.''
</P>
<P>
   He has delivered -- with the knockout confidence that once
belonged to Muhammad Ali.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think that my performance in the past years is unprecedented
in the sport,'' he says matter-of-factly. ''There's no one in the
history of any game where one person was crowned No. 1 14
consecutive years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
