<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Talking To N. Korea on Terrorism  </HEADLINE>
By BARRY SCHWEID, AP Diplomatic Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- In a move to smooth relations, the Clinton
administration is advising North Korea how it can clear its record
on terrorism and take a big step toward economic ties with the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   A declaration renouncing terrorism is a likely precondition.
Another is expulsion of terrorism suspects.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea is one of seven countries branded by the State
Department as a sponsor of terrorism. Under law, this bars all but
humanitarian aid to the Pyongyang government and rules out
international bank loans.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright announced the opening of
discussions on terrorism at a joint news conference here with South
Korean Foreign Minister Lee Joung-Binn.
</P>
<P>
   She said Michael Sheehan, director of the U.S. office to counter
terrorism, had taken up the subject in talks with North Korea in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   The secrecy-shrouded talks have recessed for the two delegations
to consult with their capitals, Albright said.
</P>
<P>
   Lee said South Korea had not been a target of North Korean
terrorism for years. His statement in response to a question could
improve North Korea's chances.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the two Koreas remain locked in an armed standoff,
the Communist North appears eager to break out of its isolation and
the South seems eager to help.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Lee said, ''U.S.-South Korea relations are as strong
as ever.''
</P>
<P>
   The talks in New York are aimed mostly on arranging a visit by a
top North Korean official to Washington. A possible candidate to
head the delegation is Kang Sok Ju, North Korea's first deputy
foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
   Pyongyang was put on the terrorism list because of involvement
in the midair bombing of a South Korean airliner near Burma, now
Myanmar, in 1987. All 115 people on board the Korean Air plane
died.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea lost a strong ally with the collapse of the Soviet
Union a decade ago. It is pursuing normal relations with Japan, and
stepping up its overtures to already-friendly China while also
approaching the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan welcomed ''the
increasingly positive signs'' on the divided Korean peninsula and
strongly endorsed the quick resumption of a dialogue between North
Korea and South Korea, a U.N. spokesman said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ''While the issues in question remain most challenging, he
believes that they can be successfully addressed through dialogue
and determination,'' spokesman Fred Eckhard said.
</P>
<P>
   On request, Annan is ready ''to contribute to the efforts aimed
at reducing tensions and promoting mutual confidence in the
region'' and looks forward to a North Korean visit to Washington,
Eckhard said.
</P>
<P>
   In a ceremony here, Albright and Lee signed an agreement to end
the practice of having Americans and South Koreans who work in each
other's countries paying social security taxes to both governments.
</P>
<P>
   Unless Congress objects, the double-taxation will end probably
next April. Several thousand American and South Korean workers will
be affected.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
