<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush, Gore Stances on Health Care  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   A look at health care proposals of Republican George
W. Bush and
Democrat Al Gore:
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bush:
</P>
<P>
   Coverage-Tax Breaks: Expand tax-protected medical savings
accounts so anyone who wants to set one up to help cover health
costs may do so. Allow tax deductibility of long-term care
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare: Keep as a federal commitment but offer ''more choice
and more private sector alternatives for the elderly.'' Supports
unspecified drug benefit, and subsidies to help poorest of the
elderly afford supplementary or alternative coverage.
</P>
<P>
   HMOs: Favors requirement that patients be covered for hospital
emergency care, that women be able to go directly to gynecologist,
and patients with ongoing illnesses not be forced to change
doctors, among other protections. Also favors independent review
process and ultimate avenue for legal action by patients, but says
any federal move on this front should not supersede protections in
place in states.
</P>
<P>
   Gore:
</P>
<P>
   Coverage: Expand Children's Health Insurance Program, which
subsidizes premiums for working poor. Plan would offer subsides to
more children, plus their parents, in families that earn too much
now to qualify but not enough to afford private insurance on their
own. Also would allow children of wealthier families into the
program, with families paying the full cost.
</P>
<P>
   Tax breaks: 25 percent tax credit for people who buy private
health insurance because they don't get it at work. People who do
get insurance at work would also get a 25 percent tax credit on
premiums -- if the company has fewer than 50 employees and joins a
''purchasing coalition'' to negotiate affordable rates.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare: Add prescription drug benefit and let uninsured
Americans aged 55 to 65 buy into Medicare coverage. Drug plan would
offer free coverage for low-income recipients, catastrophic
coverage for all, and optional cost-sharing benefit for others with
premiums of $44 a month when phased in.
</P>
<P>
   HMOs: Supports right of patients to ''independent appeal'' when
denied treatment, guaranteed coverage of emergency room treatment,
and ''redress'' for actions of the HMO, among other protections.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-13-00 1741 </TRAILER>
