<HEADLINE> Report Coming on FBI Files Probe  </HEADLINE>
By PETE YOST, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Moving a step closer to wrapping up his
investigation, Independent Counsel Robert Ray said Monday he is
filing a final report this week on the White House's improper
gathering of FBI background files.
</P>
<P>
   The report is the first of three involving President Clinton and
Hillary Rodham Clinton that will be completed in the coming months.
The reports are likely to be publicly released by a panel of three
federal appeals court judges as the November general elections draw
near.
</P>
<P>
   One coming out this spring will deal with the role of Mrs.
Clinton, a candidate for the U.S. Senate in New York, in the firing
of White House travel office staff. Another report on the Clintons'
Whitewater land dealings will follow sometime this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on the timing, the judges might not issue the
Whitewater report until after the election. The Clintons and others
named in the document would have 90 days to respond to any
criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have been through six years and $60 million'' worth of
investigations, presidential spokesman Joe Lockhart said at the
White House. ''It's certainly our hope that they report out in a
way that's done quickly ... that's consistent with the statute and
done without regard to politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard Wolfson, Mrs. Clinton's campaign spokesman, declined to
comment Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview last month, Mrs. Clinton said the Independent
Counsel's investigation ''has nothing to do with any of my campaign
decisions or how I'm trying to present myself.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can't do anything about what other people say or do and at
the end of the day there's no there there,'' Mrs. Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   One issue in the FBI files probe was whether Mrs. Clinton was
behind the hiring of White House security aide Craig Livingstone,
whose office collected FBI background files on hundreds of people,
including Republican appointees from prior administrations.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton said she had no role in Livingstone's hiring. An
FBI report quoted former White House counsel Bernard Nussbaum as
saying that Livingstone had been highly recommended by the first
lady. Nussbaum said he had been misquoted in the FBI report.
</P>
<P>
   The White House says the files were mistakenly gathered based on
outdated lists of White House passholders.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton was questioned in January 1998 about the FBI files
controversy by then-prosecutor Kenneth Starr's office. Ray took
over for Starr, who stepped aside last October.
</P>
<P>
   The report on the travel office will assess whether Mrs. Clinton
had a larger role than she or presidential aides have acknowledged
in the mass firings at the travel office in 1993, which took place
amid a White House-inspired FBI criminal investigation of the
operation.
</P>
<P>
   A White House memo that surfaced 2{ years after the dismissals
said Mrs. Clinton was the key figure in the dismissals, which the
first lady has denied being a part of.
</P>
<P>
   The Whitewater report will deal in part with Mrs. Clinton's
legal work for her business partners' failing Arkansas savings and
loan -- work that wasn't revealed until her law firm billing records
turned up inside the White House under still-unexplained
circumstances. Before the records appeared, Mrs. Clinton testified
she knew almost nothing about the deal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
