<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 17:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AM-CT--Murder in Greenwich, Conn Bjt,690  </HEADLINE>
By DENISE LAVOIE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Michael Skakel's arraignment in the
25-year-old murder of Greenwich teen-ager Martha Moxley is expected
to have all the drama of a celebrity trial.
</P>
<P>
   The Kennedy cousin, who will be arraigned Tuesday, is expected
to draw a media horde, as well as friends of his high-powered
family and a familiar figure from the O.J. Simpson trial. Former
Los Angeles police Detective Mark Fuhrman, who wrote a 1998 book
about the Moxley case, has been hired by ABC as a consultant to
provide commentary on the case for ''Good Morning America.''
</P>
<P>
   Skakel, the 39-year-old nephew of the late U.S. Sen. Robert F.
Kennedy, will be arraigned as a juvenile because he was 15 when
Moxley, also 15, was bludgeoned to death with a golf club on Oct.
30, 1975.
</P>
<P>
   Under confidentiality laws designed to protect juveniles, such
proceedings are generally closed to the press and public.
</P>
<P>
   But Judge Maureen Dennis, acting on a request from five
newspapers and The Associated Press, ruled last week that the media
would be allowed in the courtroom. The judge agreed with the
newspapers' argument that Skakel has already effectively waived his
juvenile confidentiality rights, both because he is an adult and
because his name and the charges against him are already well-known
across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Skakel's attorney, Michael Sherman, said he is uncertain whether
Skakel will enter a plea during the arraignment. The proceeding is
expected to last just a few minutes, as Skakel is formally
presented in court and the murder charge against him is read.
</P>
<P>
   Skakel denies any involvement in Moxley's death. The case went
unsolved for more than two decades until an investigative grand
jury was convened in June 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Although the grand jury proceedings were closed to the public,
prosecutors said in court documents that they were told by former
students at the Elan school in Poland Spring, Maine, that Skakel
made ''admissions as to the murder of Martha Moxley'' while he was
a student there from 1978 to 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Skakel was arrested in January after Judge George Thim -- acting
as a one-man grand jury -- ruled there was enough evidence to charge
him in Moxley's murder.
</P>
<P>
   Moxley's mother, Dorthy, said Skakel's arraignment is a critical
step in her long quest to bring her daughter's killer to justice.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is like a miracle, after all this time,'' said Mrs.
Moxley, who plans to be in the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   Martha's brother, John, who was 17 when his sister was murdered,
also plans to be there. But both he and his mother said they will
be there to support prosecutors, not out of any desire to confront
Skakel, who they have not seen since he was a 15-year-old boy.
</P>
<P>
   ''If I never had to see him, it would be fine with me,'' said
John Moxley. ''I don't need to look him in the eye. I'm going (to
the arraignment) for my own peace of mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Sherman said Skakel will have some of his own supporters,
including friends and family members, in the courtroom. He would
not say which members of the Skakel clan will attend.
</P>
<P>
   ''The key thing is to focus on what's important here, and that
is a fair trial and the presumption of innocence,'' Sherman said.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skakel is the son of Rushton Skakel Sr., who is the
brother of Robert F. Kennedy's widow, Ethel.
</P>
<P>
   Fuhrman, who named Michael Skakel as the killer in his 1998
book, ''Murder in Greenwich,'' has been hired by ABC as one of
several consultants who will provide commentary.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's one of many voices we'll have on the subject. Basically,
he was chosen for his insight and knowledge of the case,'' said
Sonya McNair, a publicist for ''Good Morning America.''
</P>
<P>
   The case has generated such widespread press attention that
Stamford court officials set up a pool of reporters to cover the
arraignment because there are not enough seats in the courtroom to
accommodate the media crush.
</P>
<P>
   The proceeding will be held in the civil courthouse in Stamford
rather than a smaller juvenile courtroom.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
