<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 17:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ex Officials Back Clinton on China  </HEADLINE>
By MARTIN CRUTSINGER, AP Economics Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration, bowing to
congressional criticism about secret trade deals, will release the
full text of its market-opening agreement with China on Tuesday,
administration officials said.
</P>
<P>
   These officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
Monday that the complete text of the deal would be sent to each
member of Congress and released to the news media.
</P>
<P>
   The decision represents an about-face for the administration,
which had been insisting that it could not make the deal public
because China was still in negotiations with Europe and other
countries over the terms under which it will enter the World Trade
Organization.
</P>
<P>
   In a US-China deal reached in Beijing in November, China agreed
to remove barriers that American exporters have long complained are
keeping billions of dollars of their products out of the Chinese
market.
</P>
<P>
   In return, the Clinton administration said it would support
China's entry into the WTO. But under WTO rules, Congress must
scrap its annual review of China's trade status and grant it
permanent normal trade relations in order for U.S. exporters to
receive the benefits of the cuts in tariffs and other trade
barriers. Permanent normal trade relations status is enjoyed by
almost all countries in the world.
</P>
<P>
   The full text of the November agreement has been available to
members of the House and Senate and staff members with appropriate
security clearances for reading in secure reading rooms. But
lawmakers had complained that the secrecy was difficult to justify.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Dennis Hastert urged the administration Monday to
make public all details of the agreement ''so that all the elements
of this agreement are ready for responsible consideration by
Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials have insisted that all of the
agreement's details were released in November when the deal was
announced even though the exact text of the document was withheld.
</P>
<P>
   But opponents in the labor and environmental movements have said
such a major change in U.S. policy should not be voted on without
both sides having a chance to examine the fine print.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, the administration released a letter signed by six
former secretaries of state urging Congress to grant China
permanent normal trade relations.
</P>
<P>
   Henry A. Kissinger, Alexander M. Haig, George P. Shultz, James
A. Baker III, Lawrence Eagleburger and Warren Christopher wrote
that the permanent trade status and membership in the World Trade
Organization would help move China toward a more open society.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents, including human rights advocates, argue that
abandoning an annual review would eliminate a potent weapon in
trying to influence China's policies.
</P>
<P>
   The China trade legislation is supported by the Republican
leadership and a large majority of Republicans in the House,
Hastert said in a speech to the Electronic Industries Alliance. If
House Democratic support is as weak as has been reported, ''I
cannot solve this problem for the president,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert urged Clinton to do more to try to rally Democratic
support to overcome opposition from labor unions and human-rights
groups.
</P>
<P>
   In Beijing, the Chinese foreign trade minister, Shi Guangsheng,
said if Congress refused to grant his government permanent
low-tariff trading rights, China would deny American companies
access to Chinese markets. That, he said, would cause the United
States ''regret, for 20 years, for a generation.''
</P>
<P>
   ----
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: White House working group on China:
http://www.chinapntr.gov
</P>
<P>
   AFL-CIO campaign to stop permanent trade status for China:
http://www.aflcio.org/publ/press2000/pr0222.htm
</P>
<P>
   Senate Finance Committee: http://www.senate.gov/(tilde)finance
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-13-00 1757 </TRAILER>
