<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tribune a Pioneer in Multimedia  </HEADLINE>
By DAVE CARPENTER, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- The Tribune Co. has long been aggressive in
seeking out new ways to reach information- and
entertainment-obsessed Americans, from its 1924 acquisition of WGN
Radio to its early involvement in ''new'' media, including a 1991
investment in America Online Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet's transformation of the industry and most
newspapers' move to the World Wide Web have only confirmed and
accelerated that multimedia strategy, Tribune executives said
Monday in discussing the $6.3 billion acquisition of Times Mirror
Co.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our company was one of the pioneers in radio and one of the
pioneers in television,'' Jack Fuller, president of Tribune
Publishing Co., said Monday. ''We've been seeing it that way for
most of the century.''
</P>
<P>
   But the officials also emphasized that the 153-year-old Tribune
remains a newspaper company at its core.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are bullish on the future of newspapers,'' said Scott C.
Smith, publisher and chief executive officer of the Chicago
Tribune, calling newspapers ''the last great medium in any city.''
</P>
<P>
   ''While newspaper audiences have declined modestly over the last
20 years, they've declined less than any TV station's audience
has,'' he said. ''They still have far more share than any cable or
Internet source has.''
</P>
<P>
   Media-watchers say those looking for insight into Tribune Co.'s
plans for its acquisitions, primarily in Los Angeles and New York,
should look at the history of its Chicago holdings.
</P>
<P>
   The company owns the largest-circulation Chicago newspaper, a
leading radio station in WGN, a top television station in WGN-TV
(which it founded in 1948), a 24-hour cable news channel and some
small publications. It reaches about 13 percent of the local market
via the Internet, according to Smith.
</P>
<P>
   All that adds up to a powerful package for not only consumers
but advertisers, according to analysts, who echo the company's
insistence that all the branching out doesn't mean newspapers are
on the decline.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not that newspapers are becoming weak, it's that there
are so many options,'' said Rudy Hokanson of CIBC World Markets
Corp. in New York. ''If you've got newspapers, broadcast and a
strong Internet presence, you have considerable influence.''
</P>
<P>
   ''(Tribune officials) have a clear vision of what a media
company is now,'' he added. ''They've been very smart operators.''
</P>
<P>
   Heading the Tribune Co. empire is John Madigan, 62, a
Chicago-area native with a background in business administration.
Madigan joined Tribune as chief financial officer in 1975, was the
Tribune's publisher from 1990-94 and became president in 1994. He
ascended to chief executive officer in 1995 and chairman in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   During his tenure, the company has significantly expanded its
reach, claiming even before the merger to reach 75 percent of U.S.
households.
</P>
<P>
   Madigan told investors, bankers and analysts last week that
Tribune's multimedia efforts are paying off financially, too. Its
10-month-old Tribune Interactive, created to manage Internet
activities, is on track to generate $30 million in revenue this
year, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He also announced a 23 percent investment in iBlast Networks, a
national wireless network to deliver speedier Web downloads of
digital media to consumers, the creation of a new sports Web site
for Chicago, and other moves.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're aggressively moving to exploit multimedia opportunities
in broadcasting and publishing to their fullest extent,'' he said
then. ''The value of mass media assets is increasing in today's
fragmented world.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
