<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 18:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Syria's New PM Names Cabinet  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAMASCUS, Syria (AP) -- Syria's new prime minister, Mohammed
Mustafa Miro, formed a new 37-member Cabinet on Monday, charged
with pursuing an overall Middle East peace settlement and boosting
the country's ailing economy.
</P>
<P>
   The reshuffle is seen as an effort by President Hafez Assad,
Syria's paramount leader, to press ahead with promised social and
economic reforms. His son and heir apparent, Bashar, said in
remarks published last week that the country was in need of change
in all spheres of life.
</P>
<P>
   Economic stagnation has ''regretfully become the most dangerous
phenomenon that has shrouded the Syrian economy throughout the past
few years,'' the government-run newspaper Tishrin warned Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Exports declined by 20 percent in 1999 compared to a year
earlier, creating a shortage of hard currency and leading to a drop
in imports and public consumption, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper's comment was the first official indication that
lack of economic progress was the reason behind the resignation
last Tuesday of the 8-year-old government of Mahmoud el-Zoubi.
</P>
<P>
   Syria has also entered into peace talks with Israel, although
negotiations stalled in January over the issue of the Golan
Heights, which Israel captured in the 1967 Mideast War.
</P>
<P>
   Several members of el-Zoubi's Cabinet retained their posts in
Miro's new government, including Defense Minister Maj. Gen. Mustafa
Tlas, Foreign Minister Farouk al-Sharaa and Interior Minister
Mohamed Harba. Mohamed Imadi also keeps his job as economy
minister.
</P>
<P>
   As in the previous Cabinet, the ruling Baath party had the
lion's share of the ministerial portfolios, taking 26 seats. The
remaining 11 went to the seven parties grouped in the so-called
National Progressive Front, which includes independents and
Communist, Socialist and Nasserite parties.
</P>
<P>
   The new Cabinet, to be sworn in Tuesday, includes two women
ministers and 14 political newcomers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
