<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Supports IMF Nomination  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- After rejecting Germany's first candidate,
President Clinton has thrown U.S. support behind banker Horst
Koehler's nomination to head the International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton informed German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder of his
decision in a telephone call on Monday, according to White House
press secretary Joe Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   The two leaders agreed that Koehler, president of the European
Bank for Reconstruction and Development in London, should come to
Washington to meet with IMF board members, particularly
representatives of poor countries.
</P>
<P>
   ''The president and Chancellor Schroeder also agreed that
Koehler should retain the talented management team at the IMF,''
Lockhart said. That would include Stanley Fischer, German-born
American who is acting IMF director.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration blocked Germany's first choice, Caio
Koch-Weser, because the Americans said the deputy finance minister
lacked the international standing needed to run the 182-nation IMF.
</P>
<P>
   Koehler, one of three remaining candidates, secured unanimous
European Union backing Monday, as Koch-Weser had done before
Clinton turned him down.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's agreement with Schroeder about retention of top IMF
staff was seen as a show of support for Fischer, who was the IMF's
deputy director before taking over as acting chief after Frenchman
Michel Camdessus retired in February.
</P>
</TEXT>
