<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Notre Dame Hires Arizona State AD  </HEADLINE>
By JR ROSS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTH BEND, Ind. (AP) -- Notre Dame hired Arizona State athletic
director Kevin White on Monday to help clean up its once pristine
image, tarnished by the school's first major NCAA violation last
year.
</P>
<P>
   ''Notre Dame has set the bar very high for a long time,'' White
said. ''I think we need to keep the bar set where it's at and
perhaps take it up a notch.''
</P>
<P>
   White will be the first Notre Dame athletic director to report
directly to the university president in a shakeup of the department
prompted by the school's first NCAA probation. That resulted from
the relationship between a booster and more than a dozen players.
</P>
<P>
   Former athletic director Mike Wadsworth resigned under pressure
last month following a tumultuous five years that included a
downturn in the football program, flirtations with joining the Big
Ten conference and ex-assistant football coach Joe Moore's age
discrimination lawsuit, which the university lost.
</P>
<P>
   School president the Rev. Edward A. Malloy then declared he
would assume control of the athletic department, a responsibility
that executive vice president E. William Beauchamp had for 13
years.
</P>
<P>
   ''An athletic director needs to be sponsored in that way -- I use
that word carefully -- and needs to have a direct relationship and a
tie-in to the president of the university to realize the most
potential. I just think it's critical,'' said White, sporting a
gold tie with navy stripes.
</P>
<P>
   White, expected to begin his stint at Notre Dame in mid-April,
has a reputation for cleaning up programs. While the athletic
director at Tulane, he helped resurrect the basketball program
after a point-shaving scandal led the university to disband the
team for four seasons.
</P>
<P>
   He dealt with another basketball point-shaving scandal while at
ASU, bringing in Rob Evans in 1998 to take over the program.
</P>
<P>
   White also reorganized ASU's fundraising structure, pulling
various independent booster groups into one organization, the Sun
Angel Foundation, which he brought under university control. The
move eased worries that the various bodies created the perception
that an NCAA infraction could easily occur.
</P>
<P>
   He also linked the amount of contributions groups and
individuals make to the university to the benefits they receive.
The move boosted ASU's annual giving from $1.8 million in fiscal
year 1997 to an anticipated $6 million in 2000. It also helped him
turn a $2.97 million deficit into a more than $1 million in surplus
during his first two years in Tempe.
</P>
<P>
   ''We had a chance to try to determine who were the most highly
regarded among the athletic directors at various places in the
country, and one name kept coming up from multiple sources,'' said
Malloy, who headed the university's search.
</P>
<P>
   The 49-year-old White, and a native of Amityville, N.Y., did his
undergraduate work at St. Joseph's College in Rensselaer, about 70
miles from Notre Dame. He's also served as athletic director at
Maine and Lorras College, a small Catholic school in Dubuque, Iowa.
He holds a master's in athletics administration from Central
Michigan and a doctorate in education from Southern Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm excited because he's excited about being here,'' said
first-year men's basketball coach Matt Doherty, one of several
Irish coaches to attend the announcement. ''You don't leave Tempe,
Ariz., for South Bend, Ind., unless you have a passion for this
place.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-13-00 1808 </TRAILER>
