<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Surprise, Worry Greet Media Merger  </HEADLINE>
By ROBERT JABLON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Surprise and concern rolled through newsrooms
Monday as word broke that the Tribune Co. will buy Times Mirror Co.
to create the nation's third-largest newspaper empire.
</P>
<P>
   From telephone operators to beat reporters in Baltimore, Los
Angeles, Chicago and cities in between, the announcement of the
$6.3 billion deal was met with the questions: How, what and when?
</P>
<P>
   Peter Hermann, police reporter for The Sun, a Times Mirror daily
in Baltimore, heard about it from a television reporter as they
covered the funeral for a 22-year-old policeman killed last week in
a car accident.
</P>
<P>
   ''He said, 'How does it feel to be working for a new company,'''
Hermann said. ''And I said, 'What?'''
</P>
<P>
   The Sun and the Los Angeles Times convened meetings with
staffers to answer questions about the takeover.
</P>
<P>
   At the Sun, Frederick Rasmussen, the newspaper's longtime
obituary writer, said the editorial staff greeted the news with
reserve.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think there's a sense of uneasiness -- I think that's just
natural,'' Rasmussen said. ''There wasn't any gnashing of teeth and
people weren't moaning or groaning or ruing the sale.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Times, Publisher Kathryn Downing told several hundred
workers that the Tribune Co. had committed to preserving the
newspaper's independence and did not envision large layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Some expressed curiosity about why the Chandler family, which
has owned the Los Angeles newspaper since 1882, would initiate the
deal.
</P>
<P>
   ''With luck, we've got some very good reporters out asking the
Chandlers that question, and I hope to read about it in the Los
Angeles Times,'' Downing replied to laughter.
</P>
<P>
   Others were more subdued.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think there are still many more unanswered than answered
questions, and as a result there's a mix of anxiety and
anticipation in the newsroom,'' said longtime columnist Patt
Morrison. ''After 112 years, this is a very big change to absorb in
one morning.''
</P>
<P>
   Rumors of the acquisition surfaced on Friday, but it was
generally believed that terms of the Chandler Trust forbade such a
sale.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Dwyre, the Times' sports editor for 19 years, said if the
paper had to be sold, he was glad it was to the Tribune Co., which
owns four newspapers, including the Chicago Tribune, 22 television
stations and baseball's Chicago Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   ''We could have done a hell of a lot worse,'' he said. ''They
didn't buy this paper to destroy it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Times has been the scene of recent turmoil under the
stewardship of Times Mirror chairman and chief executive Mark H.
Willes, who sought to maximize profits by relaxing the traditional
separation between news reporting and the business side of the
company.
</P>
<P>
   In December, the newspaper acknowledged it had split about $2
million in advertising revenue from a Sunday magazine devoted to
the Staples Center, a newly opened downtown sports arena.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the tension, Times staff may welcome the change
''because they know a solid newspaper company will be in charge of
the newspaper again,'' said Brett Levy, who works in information
technology.
</P>
<P>
   A wait-and-see attitude prevailed at the Chicago Tribune.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think anyone is really worried -- it's more like,
'What's going to happen next?,''' said George Gunset, a reporter
who has been with the paper for more than 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Said reporter James Janega: ''I'd rather have my company merge
than get a severance package.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-13-00 1813 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000313.0155 </DOCNO>
