<DOCNO> APW20000313.0156 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kentucky Forward Suspended  </HEADLINE>
By BRUCE SCHREINER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) -- Kentucky forward Desmond Allison was
arrested on drunken-driving and marijuana possession charges and is
not expected to play in the NCAA tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Tubby Smith suspended the 6-foot-5 sophomore on Sunday
night.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's like losing part of your family,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Fifth-seeded Kentucky (22-9) plays 12th-seeded St. Bonaventure
in the first round Thursday in the Midwest Regional in Cleveland.
Allison's absence leaves the Wildcats with only nine players.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's going to be a real challenge for us to go in and keep our
focus -- both mentally and physically -- against a very good St.
Bonaventure team,'' said Smith, who led Kentucky to a national
title and a regional final in his first two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Allison, alone in a black Ford Explorer, registered a
blood-alcohol level of 0.113 on a breath test, a police report
said. The state limit for drivers 21 and older is 0.10. For drivers
under 21, it is 0.02.
</P>
<P>
   A police officer who searched the car, which was registered to
someone other than Allison, found alcohol and less than an ounce of
marijuana, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The vehicle was registered in the name of Marvin Stone's father,
the school's sports information office said. Marvin Stone is a
freshman forward at Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   According to university policy, the 20-year-old Allison will be
suspended temporarily. If convicted, he will be suspended
indefinitely and forfeit his scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said he worried about Allison's suspension becoming a
distraction for his team, coming off an 86-72 loss to Arkansas in
the quarterfinals of the Southeastern Conference tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are going to use it as a motivating factor to persevere, to
show that we can rekindle that enthusiasm and use it as a real
catapult to help us play better and play together,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   St. Bonaventure coach Jim Baron dismissed any notion that his
Bonnies (21-9) might be catching the Wildcats at the right time.
</P>
<P>
   ''Kentucky's been there before and Tubby's a great coach, so we
can't overlook any adversity that they may be going through,''
Baron said. ''We have to worry about ourselves and that's the most
important thing at hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Allison started 29 of Kentucky's 31 games this season, averaging
7.8 points, 3.8 rebounds and 2.4 assists. He is the team's top foul
shooter, a 3-point threat and among the team's best passers and
defenders.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's just one of our best all-around athletes on the team, and
when you take away that type of athlete ... we really don't have
anyone on the perimeter that has that type of physical stature,''
Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Jules Camara, a 6-11 sophomore averaging 7.0 points and 4.6
rebounds, will move into the starting lineup. Camara started nine
games this season, and will team with 6-10 center Jamaal Magloire.
</P>
<P>
   Tayshaun Prince, the Wildcats' second-leading scorer at 12.9
points, will switch to small forward, Smith said. Point guard Saul
Smith will slide over to shooting guard at times when his backup,
J.P. Blevins, plays.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said other backup players, like freshman power forward
Marvin Stone and sophomore guard Todd Tackett, must contribute
more.
</P>
<P>
   ''This can give players a sense of urgency that they can
contribute now, that they can do more. ... They know that they've
got to reach down and bring their best game,'' Smith said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-13-00 1816 </TRAILER>
