<HEADLINE> Explosion Injures 32 in Argentina  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   USHUAIA, Argentina (AP) -- A powerful explosion ripped through an
industrial park in southern Argentina on Monday, injuring at least
35 people.
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters said the blast occurred in a factory where
explosives used in road construction were stored, sparking a fire
that quickly spread to several nearby factories and set off a
second explosion.
</P>
<P>
   Television images showed huge plumes of smoke billowing from the
factory plants as firefighters worked to recover people from inside
the buildings.
</P>
<P>
   They eventually brought the flames under control, but only after
the second blast blew out the windows of houses within in a
500-yard radius of the industrial complex, injuring several
firefighters.
</P>
<P>
   The powerful blasts reportedly lifted the roof off a nearby
school and forced the evacuation of some 30 students, authorities
said.
</P>
<P>
   At least five people working in and around the factories were
hospitalized with severe burns, said Mario Pombo, a spokesman with
the city government of Ushuaia, the world's southernmost city,
1,515 miles south of Buenos Aires. One person was admitted to
intensive care at a local hospital with burns covering almost 90
percent of his body, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters, reporters, and policemen were among those who
suffered minor injuries.
</P>
</TEXT>
