<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fiat, GM Form $2.4 Billion Deal  </HEADLINE>
By JUSTIN HYDE, AP Auto Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT (AP) -- General Motors Corp. and Italian industrial giant
Fiat SpA announced a $2.4 billion alliance Monday in the latest bid
by rival automakers to cut costs by sharing parts and people.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, Fiat will swap 20 percent of its Fiat Auto
subsidiary for about 5.1 percent of GM's common stock -- making the
Italian company GM's largest shareholder. Fiat and GM will form
joint ventures in engine building and purchasing that could
eventually involve thousands of workers on two continents.
</P>
<P>
   The deal was aimed at strengthening both companies in Europe,
where competition has become fierce, and Latin America, where many
automakers hope to grow. But GM and Fiat officials emphasized that
competition between the two would remain strong.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is cooperation between two companies that want to remain
independent,'' Fiat chairman Paolo Fresco said. In Europe, ''we're
going to compete quite aggressively.''
</P>
<P>
   The alliance continues a trend among automakers toward
partnerships or mergers that began with the merger of Chrysler
Corp. and Daimler-Benz AG in 1998, and continued with deals between
Ford Motor Co. and Volvo AB, Renault SA and Nissan Motor Co., and
GM and Subaru. In fact, GM and Fiat are competitors in bidding for
troubled South Korean automaker Daewoo Motor Co.
</P>
<P>
   Automakers believe such deals will cut the massive costs of
designing and building new vehicles by allowing companies to share
components and factories around the world. Such deals are seen as
especially important in Europe and Latin America, where smaller,
less profitable cars are far more popular than in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   GM and Fiat said they would form joint ventures in engine
building and purchasing in Europe and Latin America, and would also
look for savings in their financial operations. The companies said
the benefits of the alliance could amount to $1.2 billion in
savings in three years, growing to $2 billion a year within five
years.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the era when Fiat and General Motors were founded,
automaking was a national or regional affair,'' said GM chairman
Jack Smith. ''Today, automaking has become a global affair.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of the agreement, GM has the first right to bid on the
rest of Fiat Auto if Fiat decides to sell in the future, but Fresco
said Fiat had no intention to do so. The deal is subject to
approval by U.S. and European Union regulators.
</P>
<P>
   Fiat -- which with its automaking and other businesses accounts
for about 5 percent of Italy's gross domestic product -- is an
Italian institution, with so much clout that honorary chairman
Gianni Agnelli has been called the uncrowned king of Italy. The
conglomerate is Italy's largest private employer, and has 220,000
employees around the world, including 7,000 at subsidiaries in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   But the world's seventh-largest automaker has seen sales and
profits slip over recent years, and there have been rumors of
foreign mergers or buyouts. Fiat's share of the Italian market,
once 60 percent, has dwindled to 39 percent as competition eroded
its dominance. And a bet that South America would be a major source
of growth has not paid off yet due to widespread economic woes.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Fiat Auto posted an operating loss of $116 million
compared to $106 million in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Agnelli had recently acknowledged that the company was on the
lookout for international partners.
</P>
<P>
   ''We laid down two goals: an alliance as strong as possible, and
autonomy,'' said Agnelli, the 79-year-old leader of Fiat's founding
family, which was reported to have rebuffed overtures from
Germany's DaimlerChrysler AG that have might have meant
surrendering control.
</P>
<P>
   Fiat leaders did not directly answer questions on whether job
cuts would follow but suggested they could, stating that remaining
competitive ultimately was the best way to guarantee employment.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance has already received the blessing of Italy's major
union confederation, CGIL. Its leader, Sergio Cofferati, told the
Rome daily La Republica that the deal would be ''a turning-point
which is good for the Italian economy.''
</P>
<P>
   While a handful of Ferraris are imported to the United States
every year, Fiat has not sold any of its own brands in the United
States since 1993, when it stopped importing Alfa Romeo cars.
Fresco said the alliance might allow Fiat to reintroduce Alfa
Romeos through GM dealers.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of GM were unchanged at $77.81\ at 4:30 p.m. on the New
York Stock Exchange. U.S. shares of Fiat rose $1.18} to $36.06\,
also on the NYSE.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: General Motors at http://www.gm.com
</P>
<P>
   Fiat at http://www.fiatgroup.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-13-00 1832 </TRAILER>
