<DOCNO> APW20000313.0166 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 18:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Chief Visits Bosnia  </HEADLINE>
By AIDA CERKEZ-ROBINSON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARAJEVO, Bosnia-Herzegovina (AP) -- Bosnia will continue to
reduce its military, and NATO will not let up in its pursuit of war
crimes suspects, NATO's secretary-general said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Bosnia's multiethnic presidency reduced its defense budgets and
armed forces by 15 percent last year and confirmed in a meeting
Monday that it would do so again this year, Lord Robertson said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I heard what they said, and I will hold them to it,'' said
Robertson.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson also said NATO would stay committed to its Bosnian
peacekeeping mission, which includes help in returning refugees to
their homes, arresting war crimes suspects and reforming the media.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not just the armed forces that need to be reduced, but
the army of the unemployed. And that means attracting new jobs,''
Robertson said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We at NATO can help create the conditions for a prosperous and
stable country. But (only) you, the people of Bosnia-Herzegovina,
can bring it about,'' he said, urging voters to turn against
extremism in next month's municipal elections.
</P>
<P>
   ''These policies of ethnic division failed you then and cannot
help you now,'' he said. New politicians must arise who will
provide law and order in the country and tackle corruption.
</P>
<P>
   After meeting with U.S. Gen. Ronald Adams, the commander of the
NATO-led Stabilization Force, or SFOR, Robertson said NATO troops
would continue to arrest war crimes suspects in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   ''On a day-by-day basis, we continue to watch for those with a
guilty conscience and those who have been indicted,'' he said.
''There won't be a lasting peace until all of those who have been
indicted are brought to justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Robertson visited a reconstruction project in the Sarajevo
suburb of Stup, where French SFOR troops were rebuilding 216 houses
destroyed during the war, which ended in 1995 after more than three
years of fighting. The project and will enable about 1,000 people
to return to their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson was also scheduled to hold talks with the members of
Bosnia's multiethnic presidency and leaders of the democratic
opposition.
</P>
<P>
   This is Robertson's second visit to Bosnia as NATO chief. About
24,000 NATO-led peacekeepers are stationed in Bosnia, reduced from
50,000 troops in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson said he was looking forward to withdrawing more troops
when it was possible to leave ''a self-sustaining, multiethnic
democracy behind.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
