<HEADLINE> 'Spiderman' Climber on Supervision  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- The French daredevil known to his fans as
Spiderman pleaded guilty Monday to criminal trespassing charges for
scaling the 110-story Sears Tower in downtown Chicago last year.
</P>
<P>
   Alain Robert, 37, of Pezenas, France, was placed on court
supervision for one year for his spectacular but unauthorized Aug.
20 climb to the top of the 1,450-foot skyscraper.
</P>
<P>
   Downtown office workers watched astonished as he went hand over
hand up the side of the building, one of the world's tallest.
</P>
<P>
   The judge also ordered the daredevil to have no illegal contact
with the Sears Tower in the future.
</P>
<P>
   The slightly-built Robert has climbed more than 30 skyscrapers
as publicity for his shampoo-maker sponsor. He appeared in court in
his customary long and heavily peroxided hair, a dangling earring
and black leather trousers.
</P>
<P>
   Robert nor his attorney immediately returned telephone calls to
The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant State's Attorney Pattie Ehsaei said Sears Tower
management was happy with the outcome. ''I think this was the most
equitable disposition of the case,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
