<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No West Bank Withdrawal Date Set  </HEADLINE>
By SAMAR ASSAD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Palestinian and Israeli negotiators failed to
reach agreement Monday on the timing of an Israeli withdrawal from
6.1 percent of the West Bank and a release of Palestinian security
prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   Israel did, however, reportedly soften its position on a key
Palestinian demand to be given Jerusalem suburbs as part of the
withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiators met for over three hours in a Jerusalem hotel but
did not announce any dates for the implementation of three interim
peace issues. It was the second time negotiating teams met since
talks were resumed last week.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians expect Israel to carry out an overdue Israeli troop
withdrawal from 6.1 percent of the West Bank, release at least 150
Palestinian security prisoners and conclude an agreement on the
opening of a second land route for Palestinians between the Gaza
Strip and the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat said the Palestinians want
implementation ''within the next few days.''
</P>
<P>
   Erekat would not say if that meant before the four-day Muslim
holiday of Eid al-Adha, which starts Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   His Israeli counterpart, Oded Eran, said a withdrawal and
prisoner release before Thursday would be ''very difficult'' but
that he believed an understanding is possible in the next few days.
</P>
<P>
   Eran said Israel is still deciding on the withdrawal maps, which
have been discussed with the Palestinians but not shown to them.
</P>
<P>
   ''We intend to have a very rapid internal procedure to conclude
this issue,'' Eran said.
</P>
<P>
   Israel TV said Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak would present
the maps to his security Cabinet for approval Wednesday. The TV
said that the Palestinians would be given full control over two
Arab villages close to Jerusalem, Anata and Ubeidiya, and the
Beitunia village near the Palestinian city of Ramallah.
</P>
<P>
   Such a plan would partly meet a Palestinian demand to include
Jerusalem suburbs and other densely populated areas in the
withdrawal, though the Palestinians had asked for villages closer
to Jerusalem's walled Old City.
</P>
<P>
   They suspended talks last month after Israel refused to include
those villages in the 6.1 percent withdrawal and set a time line
for an additional pullout ahead of a final peace treaty.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and Barak broke the deadlock
last week in a series of three meetings in which Barak apparently
displayed flexibility over the location of the withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat adviser Nabil Abourdeneh said the leaders had agreed then
that the withdrawal and prisoner release would take place
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the sides agreed that the additional troop pullout
would be discussed in Washington next week, when the two sides
resume negotiations over a final peace treaty, slated for
September.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-13-00 1904 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
