<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 19:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Conservatives Shine in Spain  </HEADLINE>
By ADAM BROWN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADRID, Spain (AP) -- The ruling conservatives on Monday quietly
savored a landslide victory in general elections that gave Spain
its strongest right-leaning government and weakest opposition in a
generation.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's vote gave reformer Prime Minister Jose Maria Aznar, a
47-year-old former tax inspector, a free hand to implement his
plans for economic change for the first time and dealt a crushing
defeat to the left.
</P>
<P>
   The sweeping win by his Popular Party appeared to put an end to
a long-held notion about Spanish politics that endured through
Aznar's first 4-year term: that Spain was basically a center-left
country.
</P>
<P>
   The daily El Mundo, which generally supports the government,
proclaimed Aznar ''the undisputed leader'' of all European
center-right politicians.
</P>
<P>
   In a victory speech, Aznar tried to quell opposition fears that
his party would steamroll over them in Parliament and promised to
remain ''open to dialogue with all parties, social representatives
and all of Spanish society because we're all necessary for the
progress of Spain.''
</P>
<P>
   The left-leaning daily El Pais said Aznar had enjoyed ''a day of
glory'' and disproved naysayers who had pointed to his razor-thin
margin of victory in the last election in 1996 as evidence he would
not last.
</P>
<P>
   The vote tally surpassed even Aznar's most optimistic
expectations, giving him 183 seats in the 350-seat Congress of
Deputies, a gain of 27 from the last legislature. Up till now, he
ruled a minority government that relied on support from regional
nationalist parties to get bills passed.
</P>
<P>
   The Spanish left suffered a humiliating drop in support. The
main opposition Socialist Party fell from 141 seats to 125, and the
communist-dominated United Left went from 21 to 8.
</P>
<P>
   In the last legislature those two parties combined had more
seats in parliament than Aznar's party. Now they have fewer than
the Socialists alone did in the last Parliament. In the vote tally,
the right outnumbered the left by more than a million votes.
</P>
<P>
   The two leftist parties had struck an alliance for this election
but it backfired. Analysts said many United Left supporters
abstained rather than endorse the deal with the Socialists. Many
Spanish communists accuse the latter of being centrist sellouts.
</P>
<P>
   The Socialists ruled under Prime Minister Felipe Gonzalez from
1982 to 1996 when it was unseated by Aznar. Gonzalez's fall was
blamed in large part on corruption scandals tainting his
administrations. Gonzalez first took office seven years after the
death of the longtime dictator Gen. Francisco Franco in 1975.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-13-00 1907 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000313.0173 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 19:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Conn. Officer Convicted in Shooting  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITCHFIELD, Conn. (AP) -- A white police officer was convicted of
manslaughter Monday for shooting an unarmed black suspect in the
back at point-blank range.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Smith, 28, had been the first Connecticut police officer
to be charged with murder for an action committed in the line of
duty.
</P>
<P>
   The jury acquitted the New Milford officer of murder but found
him guilty of intentional manslaughter in the December 1998
shooting of Franklyn Reid. Smith could get up to 40 years in prison
when sentenced May 5.
</P>
<P>
   ''A trillion, trillion, trillion thanks to the jury, for your
courage to do the right thing,'' said Reid's mother, Pearlylyn
Reid.
</P>
<P>
   The officer said he shot Reid, 27, because he believed Reid was
reaching for a weapon.
</P>
<P>
   ''When he made that classic move, I thought, 'Oh (expletive),
I'm dead,'' Smith testified last week.
</P>
<P>
   Reid was unarmed. A short folding knife was discovered in the
pocket of a jacket found a few feet away from his body.
</P>
<P>
   Smith shot Reid once in the back. Prosecution witnesses
testified they saw Reid sitting or lying down moments before the
shooting; an expert testified for prosecutors that Smith's
bootprint was on Reid's shirt.
</P>
<P>
   Just before the shooting, Reid -- who was wanted for failure to
appear in court -- had led Smith on a brief foot chase. Reid had
also eluded another officer earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
   Smith shook his head when the verdict was read, but made no
other comment.
</P>
<P>
   Over the objections of Smith's lawyers, Judge Charles Gill
allowed the jury to consider the less serious charges of
intentional and negligent manslaughter, in addition to murder. The
jury began deliberating Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Reid was wanted on charges of violating probation, telephone
harassment and failure to appear in court. His criminal record
included convictions on assault and sexual assault charges.
</P>
<P>
   The charges against Smith initially brought protests from
hundreds of police officers. His conviction follows the acquittals
last month of four white New York City police officers in the
shooting death of West African immigrant Amadou Diallo.
</P>
<P>
   But the Reid case focused less on race than on the recent spate
of suspects killed by Connecticut police officers.
</P>
<P>
   Dwight and Pearlylyn Reid, who moved with their three sons from
Jamaica to New Milford in 1986, had rejected an offer of assistance
from the Rev. Al Sharpton, the New York activist involved in the
Diallo case.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they highlighted the police shootings in Connecticut.
Between December 1998 and November 1999, nine people were killed
and a 10th wounded in police shootings around the state.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-13-00 1908 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000313.0174 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 19:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NJ officials continue search for rapist  </HEADLINE>
By AMY WESTFELDT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- New Jersey officials searched on both ends
of the state Monday for a rapist who authorities say was improperly
released from prison, and a prosecutor said a psychologist failed
in a recent evaluation to describe the suspect as violent.
</P>
<P>
   The evaluation of Raymond Alves before his release concluded he
was at a low risk to repeat as a sexual offender, state Department
of Corrections spokesman Christopher Carden said.
</P>
<P>
   The Jan. 21 evaluation also stated that Alves had no prior
history of violent crimes, although he was a convicted rapist,
Bergen County Prosecutor William H. Schmidt said.
</P>
<P>
   The evaluation also failed to refer to an interview with a
prisoner in Florida who had said that Alves talked about killing
people, and the fact that he once tried to escape while Bergen
County prosecutors tried to take him into custody, Schmidt said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It makes one wonder whether anyone had bothered to look at the
file and find out what this man was about,'' Schmidt said.
</P>
<P>
   Alves, 58, was released from the Southern State Correctional
Center in Cumberland County on Thursday after serving a 23-year
prison sentence for raping two Clifton girls in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   He also was reportedly a suspect in several Bergen County
murders in the 1960s and 1970s, according to published reports. An
unidentified law enforcement source told The Associated Press that
officials did investigate Alves for murder.
</P>
<P>
   Corrections officials acknowledged last week that they had
notified Bergen County prosecutors of Alves' release too late for
prosecutors to be able to launch a formal objection.
</P>
<P>
   ''We realize it's a serious mistake and we are aggressively
trying to find out exactly what happened,'' said Carden.
</P>
<P>
   A letter dated Feb. 29 and postmarked March 8 was sent to the
prosecutor's office informing them that Alves was scheduled for
release. The letter, addressed to ''Prosecutor Fahy,'' arrived in
Hackensack on March 10.
</P>
<P>
   John J. Fahy has not been the Bergen County prosecutor since
1995.
</P>
<P>
   State law requires that prosecutors be given 30 days notice when
a prisoner is to be released. Schmidt said that if he had been
given the time, he would have asked the state Attorney General's
Office to hold a civil commitment hearing to declare Alves unfit
for release.
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt said that members of his staff have told him that
notification letters from the Department of Corrections often
arrive very close to the date of the prisoner's release, violating
the 30-day rule.
</P>
<P>
   ''This shouldn't have happened,'' Schmidt said. ''I'm afraid
there's going to be another victim.''
</P>
<P>
   State and Bergen County officials are seeking Alves on a Megan's
Law violation because he gave authorities a phony address in Falls
River, Mass., where he said he would be staying. The law requires
convicted sex offenders to tell New Jersey authorities where they
will live after they are released.
</P>
<P>
   Following leads from inmates and a social worker who interviewed
Alves, authorities were looking for him at shelters in Camden,
Bergen and Passaic counties, as well as Atlantic City and Las
Vegas, Schmidt said. Alves left prison with a $1,554 check and $100
in cash, and will likely need more money soon, Schmidt said.
</P>
<P>
   Carden said the Corrections Department is investigating all
aspects of its notification process. ''Any part of the process ...
will come under scrutiny,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-13-00 1912 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000313.0175 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 19:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spurs' Elliott Ready For Comeback  </HEADLINE>
By KELLEY SHANNON, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- While most of his team rested, Sean Elliott
took jump shots and ran drills until the sweat dripped off his
face.
</P>
<P>
   He's spent seven grueling months trying to get back into shape
after a kidney transplant, and he's not about to stop now.
</P>
<P>
   With family, friends and doctors watching Tuesday night, the
32-year-old Elliott will play in an NBA game for the first time
since his brother Noel donated a kidney to him on Aug. 16.
</P>
<P>
   ''Most of the pressure is going to come from within,'' Elliott
said Monday after an intensive workout with four teammates at the
Alamodome. ''I have a chance to make a statement to myself and also
to a lot of people that have gone through what I went through, just
people that have faced adversity.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm feeling pretty good about it. Probably nerves will be the
biggest thing I've got to deal with.''
</P>
<P>
   Elliott planned all along to make his unprecedented comeback in
a home game. But as he worked out alone at first, then with the
team the last six weeks, he didn't allow himself to think too much
about how the night would unfold.
</P>
<P>
   Will he want the ball right away? What will be his first play?
</P>
<P>
   ''That's stuff that you daydream about,'' he said. ''I'm going
to try to let the game come to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Elliott expects to play about 10 minutes a game until he
rebuilds his stamina.
</P>
<P>
   He could barely walk right after the transplant. When he was
able to move about, he would get winded just climbing a flight of
stairs. Now, he's nearly back to the condition he was before the
transplant.
</P>
<P>
   He'll find out exactly how close when he plays against the
Atlanta Hawks.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'll probably be exhausted the first 30 seconds I'm on the
floor because I'll have a lot of adrenaline -- and the nerves,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Just weeks after the Spurs won the NBA championship in June,
Elliott said he needed the transplant because of a disease that
prevents the kidneys from filtering waste from the blood. Without
the transplant, he would have been forced to undergo dialysis.
</P>
<P>
   Though doctors didn't rule out a return to the NBA, no
professional athlete in a major sport has come back to the same
level of competition after a kidney transplant.
</P>
<P>
   ''Of course, to Sean, basketball is more than a game. It's a
career and a passion and always has been for him,'' said his
transplant surgeon, Dr. Francis Wright of Methodist Specialty and
Transplant Hospital. ''Sean is clearly a unique case.''
</P>
<P>
   The risk of injury to Elliott's new kidney -- positioned on his
right side and partially protected by the pelvic bone -- is minimal.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't believe it is a scary situation,'' said Dr. Lewis
Teperman, director of transplantation for New York University and a
medical spokesman for the National Kidney Foundation. ''I don't
think anyone is going to intentionally hit him ... there, and to
normal injuries he'll respond fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Elliott's role on the court initially will be a small one, about
five or six minutes a half, Spurs coach Gregg Popovich said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Sean's doing something that's pretty heroic and pretty
amazing,'' Popovich said. ''We want to step lightly as we begin
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Elliott, in his 11th season, was selected by the Spurs in the
first round of the 1989 draft with the third overall pick. Last
year, he averaged 11.2 points, 4.3 rebounds and 2.3 assists during
the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   His ''Memorial Day Miracle'' shot -- an off-balance 3-pointer as
he nearly fell out of bounds -- helped seal a victory for the Spurs
in the final seconds of a game against Portland in the Western
Conference finals last season.
</P>
<P>
   Fans eager to see Elliott return bought tickets at a furious
pace Monday. By late afternoon, about 3,000 tickets had been sold
for the day, compared with sales of about 300 the day before a
typical game.
</P>
<P>
   The Alamodome usually holds 20,557 for a Spurs game, although
upper levels can be opened to accommodate more than 34,000. Ticket
sales reached at least 22,000 Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott's older brother Noel, who is traveling from Arizona for
the game, will be one of the fans cheering him on. Elliott said
he's constantly reminding Noel that both of them are making
history.
</P>
<P>
   The brothers were always close but the kidney transplant
strengthened their bond.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you can get closer, I guess we did,'' Elliott said. ''You
can probably say that. I've got one of his organs inside of me.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.kidney.org/
</P>
<P>
   http://www.spurs.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
