<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 19:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Details of Plane Collision Released  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRADENTON, Fla. (AP) -- Both small planes involved in a deadly
crash on a runway last week were cleared for takeoff just seconds
apart, federal investigators said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators are trying to determine whether one of the pilots
erred by pulling in front of the other plane, or if a Federal
Aviation Administration controller allowed the two aircraft to come
together on a runway at Sarasota Bradenton International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   National Transportation Safety Board investigators are still
examining all possible causes of the crash and will not make an
official finding for several months, NTSB spokesman Pat Cariseo
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The crash Thursday killed all four people on board both planes.
It ignited a huge fireball, but no one on the ground was injured.
The safety board released the new details after wrapping up
interviews with witnesses over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   A Cessna 152 under the command of student pilot Charlie Heffner,
80, and flight instructor Lori Bahrenburg, 26, had been given
clearance for takeoff shortly after 10:35 a.m., Cariseo said.
</P>
<P>
   Seven to 10 seconds later, clearance was given to a Cessna 172
that carried Sarasota Flying Club leader and a retired Air Force
colonel, Julius Taubman, 81, and David Mouckley, a 75-year-old
Toronto businessman.
</P>
<P>
   Cariseo said the Cessna 152 tried to take off to avoid the
collision, but its propeller hit the other aircraft. The impact
came about 13 seconds after the Cessna 172 had been given clearance
for takeoff.
</P>
<P>
   Cariseo said investigators were not able to detect any
mechanical problems in either plane.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
