<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Conservation Groups File Lawsuit  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOZEMAN, Mont. (AP) -- Twelve conservation groups filed a lawsuit
Monday seeking to force a federal decision on whether to protect
the lynx under the Endangered Species Act.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit claims the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service missed a
Jan. 8 deadline for making a decision on the status of the lynx.
That deadline was set after an earlier delay.
</P>
<P>
   ''We simply cannot afford to wait any longer to implement
conservation actions to protect this magnificent, rare cat and our
northern forests where it lives,'' said David Gaillard of the
Bozeman office of the Predator Conservation Alliance, one of the
groups that filed suit.
</P>
<P>
   Fish and Wildlife Service officials have recommended the wild
cat be listed as a threatened species.
</P>
<P>
   At the agency's office in Helena, biologist Lori Nordstrom
acknowledged the deadline was missed and said a decision will be
issued soon, possibly within a couple of weeks. She declined to
comment on the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The secretive forest cat is so rare it seldom has been seen in
most of the lower 48 United States for years. Opponents say there
never were many to begin with and that trying to develop a presence
now could restrict logging and deny access to public land by
hunters and skiers.
</P>
<P>
   Superior Wilderness Action Network, Defenders of Wildlife and
the Biodiversity Legal Foundation are among the groups that filed
the suit in U.S. District Court in Washington.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-13-00 1915 </TRAILER>
