<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Monday's Commodities Roundup  </HEADLINE>
By DAVE CARPENTER, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   Soybean prices bolted nearly 3 percent higher Monday on a
sobering forecast that U.S. farmers, already reeling from a long
slump in agricultural commodities, now face a serious drought
threat after the warmest winter on record.
</P>
<P>
   In other markets, natural gas prices jumped amid concerns about
supplies for summer, oil inched higher on similar notions and sugar
rose 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Soybean and grain futures, already on the move upward, surged
when the U.S. National Weather Service released its
first-everdrought forecast. Nebraska, Iowa, Illinois and Indiana --
among the most productive farm states -- all fall in the driest
area.
</P>
<P>
   Weather service director Jack Kelly said it would take a
''large, large amount of precipitation'' to end the drought, and
officials said drought conditions appear likely to continue and
worsen at least through April.
</P>
<P>
   Also supporting prices were weekend rains that didn't meet
expectations in Midwest crop areas, as well as continuing rains in
central Brazil that are holding back harvest progress.
</P>
<P>
   Soybeans hit a three-week high, while corn rose to a two-week
high as investors fretted about the approach of spring planting
season, about three weeks away.
</P>
<P>
   Soybeans for May delivery rose 13\ cents to $5.23 a bushel; May
corn rose 4 cents to $2.30} a bushel; May wheat rose 3{ cents to
$2.63{ a bushel; May oats rose 1} cent to $1.18\ a bushel.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's just a tad early to see the markets get this excited,''
said Allen Dever, grains analyst for Doane Agricultural Services in
St. Louis. ''But if it (dryness) persists through the growing
season, then people would want to know why the prices didn't go up
sooner.''
</P>
<P>
   Energy analysts said the natural gas market remains tight as the
result of concerns about supplies as the high-use summer season
draws near. April natural gas settled up 8.6 cents at $2.86 per
1,000 cubic feet on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Crude oil also edged up in choppy trading as an uneasy market
awaits the March 27 OPEC meeting to find out how much additional
oil will be injected into a needy market, and when.
</P>
<P>
   April crude rose 26 cents to $32.02 a barrel. In other energy
commodities, April heating oil rose .91 cent to 75.45 cents a
gallon and April unleaded gasoline fell . 31 cent to 99.11 cents a
gallon.
</P>
<P>
   In London, April Brent crude fell 5 cents to $28.89 a barrel on
the International Petroleum Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Sugar rose to a one-month high on a heavy dose of short-covering
-- the buying of futures contracts to balance previous sales -- by
large funds and speculators. A surge in demand in Asia helped spur
the technical rally, traders said.
</P>
<P>
   May sugar rose .20 cent to $5.42 a pound on New York's Coffee,
Sugar &AMP; Cocoa Exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-13-00 1936 </TRAILER>
