<HEADLINE> Big Movers in the Stock Market  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks that moved substantially or traded
heavily Monday on the New York Stock Exchange and Nasdaq Stock
Market.
</P>
<P>
NYSE
</P>
<P>
Times Mirror Co., up 37 11/16 at 85|
Tribune Co., down 6] at 30 13/16
</P>
<P>
   Tribune will acquire Times Mirror in a $6.46 billion deal that
would create a multimedia empire encompassing the Los Angeles
Times, the Chicago Tribune and 22 television stations. The combined
business would be the nation's third-largest newspaper company,
trailing Gannett Co. Inc. and Knight Ridder.
</P>
<P>
Aetna Inc., down 5\ at 50}
</P>
<P>
   Aetna, the nation's largest health insurer, rejected a $10
billion takeover offer from WellPoint Health Networks Inc. and ING
Group. Instead, Aetna plans to split its health care and financial
services businesses into two publicly traded companies.
</P>
<P>
Infineon AG, opened at 66, trading at 70
</P>
<P>
   The company, a spinoff of German electronics giant Siemens AG,
began trading Monday on the Frankfurt stock exchange and the NYSE.
Infineon, a semiconductor maker, has bounced back strongly since
1998, when profits suffered due to low demand.
</P>
<P>
NASDAQ
</P>
<P>
Dell Computer Corp., up 3{ at 54}
</P>
<P>
   Bear Stearns &AMP; Co., Banc of America Securities and Robertson
Stephens all raised their ratings on Dell stock. Bear Stearns
analyst Andrew Neff said Dell, a maker of personal computers, is
increasingly able to capture the growth of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
Aspect Development Inc., up 11 13/16 at 96 13/16
I2 Technologies Inc., down 16 13/16 at 191 3/16
</P>
<P>
   Software developer i2 is buying Aspect Development Inc. for
about $9.3 billion in stock in a deal that would be one of the
largest in the software industry. Both companies specialize in
making business-to-business software.
</P>
<P>
StarMedia Networks Inc., down 16 15/16 at 33 1/16
</P>
<P>
   Salomon Smith Barney downgraded the company's stock to
''neutral, high risk'' from ''buy, high risk.'' Salomon said
StarMedia, an Internet company targeting Latin America and other
Spanish- and Portuguese-speaking markets, is facing increased
competition and higher costs.
</P>
<P>
Burmah Castrol PLC, up 5{ at 32
</P>
<P>
   The company said it has held talks with BP Amoco PLC, which
could lead to it receiving a bid. Oil analysts said BP Amoco
appeared to be most interested in Burmah Castrol for its lubricants
business.
</P>
</TEXT>
