<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Michigan Students End Sit-In  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANN ARBOR, Mich. (AP) -- Protesters at the University of Michigan
on Monday ended their 37-day sit-in at the office of a secretive
campus society accused of mocking and misusing American Indian
customs and artifacts.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 6, a group of minority students occupied the
wigwam-themed office of the Michigamua society and demanded that
the group be expelled from the university.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters said the 98-year-old society had not honored a
1989 promise to drop the use of ''Native American culture and
pseudo-culture'' from its rituals.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters said in a statement that they ''decided that in
order to truly be effective in attacking these systemic problems of
institutional racism, we must be out of the psychologically damning
environment of the Michigamua 'wigwam.'''
</P>
<P>
   The protesters left after they removed genuine and pseudo-Indian
artifacts from the Michigamua office, university spokesman Joel
Seguine said. He said the items were taken to the university's
Natural History Museum for safekeeping.
</P>
<P>
   The students also expressed disappointment with the university's
response to their complaints.
</P>
<P>
   University President Lee Bollinger said the university was
examining its policies on office space assignment and repeated its
opposition to racial or ethnic stereotyping, as well as to campus
sit-ins.
</P>
<P>
   Michigamua (pronounced mi-chi-GAW-muh) was founded in 1901, its
name taken from the Ojibway words for ''great water.'' Each year it
invites a select group of campus leaders -- all male until this year
-- to join.
</P>
<P>
   It counts former President Ford and late U.S. Supreme Court
Justice Frank Murphy among its alumni.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning, each new inductee got a ''tribal'' name upon
joining. Other rituals included loincloth wearing, body painting
and holding ceremonies around a totem pole. In response to growing
criticism, the group promised in 1989 to abandon such practices.
</P>
<P>
   Current inductees of Michigamua, which counts six women and
eight minority students among its 24 members, claim they reject the
old practices.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
