<HEADLINE> Monday's Canada News Briefs  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressNote: All dollars are Canadian unless otherwise noted
<TEXT>
<P>
   ------
Commons Voting on Referendum Bill Expected To Last 30 Straight
Hours
</P>
<P>
   OTTAWA (AP) -- Here we go again.
</P>
<P>
   A parliamentary tactic that won widespread attention in December
for its novelty, if not its effectiveness, restored gridlock to the
House of Commons on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   MPs began the process of voting on 411 amendments to the Liberal
government's clarity bill, which sets up some rules on how Ottawa
would respond to a Quebec sovereignty referendum.
</P>
<P>
   The roll-call voting is expected to last about 30 straight hours
as every MP rises in turn -- 411 times -- to signify their vote. The
process is likely to end sometime early Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   The Bloc Quebecois, the only party uniformly opposed to Bill
C-20, has proposed 403 amendments (another 700 or so were
disallowed by the Commons Speaker). Eight more amendments came from
other opposition parties.
</P>
<P>
   The Bloc's tactic is similar to one used by Reformers last
December to stall the Nisga'a land claims legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ---
Loblaw Facing Demolition of its Newest Store
</P>
<P>
   MONTREAL (AP) -- Loblaws was scrambling Monday to find a way to
avoid a shocking court order that would force Canada's largest food
retailer to demolish a big grocery store slated to open next week.
</P>
<P>
   The judgment, supporting the complaint of a competitor that the
$15-million to $20-million building contravenes city zoning laws,
is just the latest difficulty for Toronto-based Loblaw since it
began courting the Quebec market.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're examining all our legal options,'' Laurent Pepin,
spokesman for Loblaw and its Quebec subsidiary Provigo, said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Loblaw's chances to save the store in the Montreal-area
community of Brossard appear limited. Even if the company appeals,
the 7,200 square-meter building still has to be flattened within 30
days, unless a judgment to save it comes first.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge was brought by Gerard Villeneuve, owner of a Metro
Inc. franchise supermarket in a nearby mall, supported by some
other merchants.
</P>
<P>
   ---
Jane Stewart Says She ''Resented Personally'' Accusations Against
Her
</P>
<P>
   OTTAWA (AP) -- Human Resources Minister Jane Stewart lashed out
at one of her most dogged critics Monday, accusing Reformer Diane
Ablonczy of repeatedly calling her a liar.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart again faced nonstop questions about the grants scandal
unfolding in her department as the Commons resumed sitting after a
one-week break.
</P>
<P>
   Under continued probing by Ablonczy, the Reform human resources
critic, the minister said:
</P>
<P>
   ''Mr. Speaker, I want to say that I have resented personally the
accusations that this member has made against me, calling me a liar
outside this House -- because she is wrong,'' Stewart shouted.
</P>
<P>
   That ended question period.
</P>
<P>
   After, Stewart would not stop to answer questions outside the
House.
</P>
<P>
   Ablonczy did not back down.
</P>
<P>
   ''Clearly, there's no trust or credibility left in this
minister,'' Ablonczy said in a television interview.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart's resignation, ''would be a good first step,'' in
solving the problem, she added.
</P>
<P>
   ---
Ontario Appeal Court Reserves Decision in 'Bondage Bungalow' Case
</P>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- An appeal court reserved its decision Monday on
whether the purpose of wild fantasies at a dominatrix's pleasure
pad was sexual arousal or sexual activity.
</P>
<P>
   Terri-Jean Bedford admits she manacled, tortured and humiliated
her clients -- mainly wealthy patrons with wild fantasies -- in
exchange for money at her Toronto home.
</P>
<P>
   But she insists she didn't offer them sex.
</P>
<P>
   Bedford's lawyer Alan Young told a three-judge panel at the
Ontario Appeal Court that activities at her ''bondage bungalow''
were no more like prostitution than the service offered by a girl
at a country fair's kissing booth.
</P>
<P>
   Convicted in 1998, Bedford was fined $3,000 for operating a
common bawdy house, which was divided into theme rooms that
included a nursery, a dungeon and a classroom.	   ---
British Columbia To Sell Fast Ferries
</P>
<P>
   VICTORIA, British Columbia (AP) -- The British Columbia
government will try to get the fast-ferry monkey off its back by
selling the scandal-plagued vessels and absorbing the huge debt of
the British Columbia Ferry Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Joy MacPhail, the minister in charge of the Crown corporation,
said Monday the government will take on $1.1 billion in debt in an
effort to ensure the corporation remains afloat.
</P>
<P>
   The three catamaran fast ferries -- one of which isn't even
finished yet -- have a book value of $40 million each, although they
may sell for a higher or lower price than that.
</P>
<P>
   It cost $463 million to build all three.
</P>
<P>
   The project has added almost a half-billion dollars in debt to
the ferry corporation's books.
</P>
<P>
   She said it was time to put an end to a failed experiment.
</P>
</TEXT>
