<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 21:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Sierra Leone Rebels Hinder Troops  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone (AP) -- Despite promises to allow
unhindered access to international peacekeepers, Sierra Leone's
former rebels on Monday turned back a contingent of U.N. troops who
were moving into rebel-held territory.
</P>
<P>
   At the United Nations, a British official who just returned from
Sierra Leone blamed the former rebels' leader Foday Sankoh for
failure to implement a peace deal ending the country's bloody
8-year civil war, saying he wants to maintain a ''military
option.''
</P>
<P>
   In the West African nation Monday, soldiers from Sankoh's
Revolutionary United Front refused to allow 107 Indian peacekeepers
and six military observers past a roadblock between the
southeastern towns of Daru and Koidu, the hub of Sierra Leone's
rich diamond trade.
</P>
<P>
   The RUF soldiers said they did not have clearance to let an
armed escort move forward, U.N. officials said. The peacekeepers
later returned to their base.
</P>
<P>
   The RUF, which was brought into a power-sharing government last
year after signing the peace deal, controls much of Sierra Leone's
eastern region.
</P>
<P>
   Sankoh has repeatedly promised to give the United Nation's 6,000
peacekeepers freedom of movement in Sierra Leone, but his soldiers
have continued to hinder them.
</P>
<P>
   Cease-fire violations remain commonplace despite the July peace
accord, and U.N. officials have reported rebels looting villages,
burning houses, raping women and mutilating civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Few rebels have handed in their weapons, as required by the
accord. Last month, the United Nations warned the country's rebels
to turn in their guns or face a ''forceful response'' from the
6,000-strong U.N. peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is absolutely unacceptable to the U.N. that any of the
parties who have signed an agreement should be in some way
retaining their armed forces or their weaponry and not handing it
in,'' Britain's U.N. Ambassador Jeremy Greenstock told reporters
after a Security Council meeting on Sierra Leone. ''The council's
authority, in support of the Lome peace agreement, is being
thwarted here.''
</P>
<P>
   Sankoh, who became a minister in Sierra Leone's government under
the agreement, is ''confused'' and ''worried about his own
position,'' said Greenstock, who met Sankoh during his trip to the
country. ''I think there's an element there in his thinking that he
must retain a military option still.''
</P>
<P>
   RUF rebels killed tens of thousands and cut off the arms, legs,
ears and lips of many more in a bid to gain power through fear
during Sierra Leone's eight-year civil war.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-13-00 2108 </TRAILER>
