<DOCNO> APW20000313.0205 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 21:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guatemala Will Ask U.N. To Stay  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   GUATEMALA CITY (AP) -- Guatemala's president wants the U.N.
mission monitoring 1996 peace accords to stay here past its
scheduled departure at year's end, his office said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   President Alfonso Portillo has not specified how much longer
he'd like MINUGUA, as the mission is known, to stay, spokesman Jose
Maria said.
</P>
<P>
   MINUGUA monitors compliance with the peace deal between
government forces and leftist guerillas that ended the 36-year
civil war. It has a broad range of responsibilities, which include
monitoring electoral reforms and overseeing projects for improving
drinking water in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
   Bertrand de la Grange, spokesman for the UN's Guatemala effort,
said an extension would have to be approved by the General
Assembly, but that ''it's obvious the peace process in this country
has a long way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   MINUGUA's 1999 edition of its annual human rights report
documented 4,800 human rights violations here, a striking increase
from 1998's total of 1,200 abuses. The report blamed last year's
''serious deterioration'' in human rights on the continued weakness
of Guatemala's legal system.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
