<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 21:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Children's Author, Illustrator Dies  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Maine (AP) -- Children's author and illustrator Barbara
Cooney, whose works received a National Book Award and two
Caldecott Medals, has died. She was 83.
</P>
<P>
   Cooney's career, mostly as an illustrator, spanned 60 years and
110 books. The last, ''Basket Moon,'' was published in September. A
resident of the coastal town of Damariscotta, she died Friday at
Maine Medical Center after a long illness.
</P>
<P>
   ''She was a star of children's publishing throughout the United
States, and I doubt that there is a school library or public
library in which she is not represented,'' said Tim Moses,
spokesman for her publisher, Viking Children's Books. ''We're going
to miss her very much.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooney's first book, ''Uncle Snowball,'' was published in 1940.
She won the Caldecott Medal, the highest U.S. honor for a
children's book illustrator, in 1959 for ''Chanticleer and the
Fox.'' The book was Cooney's adaptation of a story from Geoffrey
Chaucer's ''Canterbury Tales.''
</P>
<P>
   Her illustrations for Donald Hall's ''Ox-Cart Man'' garnered
another Caldecott in 1980. ''Miss Rumphius,'' published in 1982,
was one of The New York Times' 10 best illustrated books of the
year and received the next year's National Book Award for
children's picture books.
</P>
<P>
   ''Her artwork was terribly reflective of her personality, which
was apparently on the surface very simple, and yet she was an
immensely complex and talented lady,'' Moses said.
</P>
<P>
   Cooney was born in New York City in 1917. She grew up on Long
Island and moved to Maine 17 years ago. She knew the state from
childhood visits to her grandmother, who was a teacher in a
one-room schoolhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Many of her books focused on the culture, history and society of
Maine. Her love for her new home and for books prompted her to
donate $850,000 in 1997 to help build a library in Damariscotta.
</P>
<P>
   A fan of the author, Gov. Angus King dubbed Cooney an official
state treasure in 1996 and named a ''Barbara Cooney Day'' that
year.
</P>
<P>
   ''Barbara's death is a tremendous loss to the literary community
and to the people of Maine,'' King said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Cooney is survived by her husband, four children, three
grandchildren and one great-grandchild.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Information on Barbary Cooney
http://falcon.jmu.edu/~ramseyil/bcooney.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-13-00 2125 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000313.0209 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 21:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judge Dismisses Sweat Lodge Request  </HEADLINE>
By MICHELLE LOCKE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- A federal judge on Monday rejected a
convicted serial killer's request that he be allowed to participate
in an Indian sweat lodge ceremony before his execution this week.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Darrell Rich had gone to federal court to try to
force prison officials to allow Rich, who is part Cherokee, to use
a sweat lodge on prison grounds as a religious last rite.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a simple proposition. It really is just a matter of
whether or not you can let this man go to church before he is
executed,'' lawyer James Thomson told U.S. District Judge Vaughn
Walker.
</P>
<P>
   But state officials said the sweat lodge is too high a security
risk. Allowing Rich to be unrestrained in a ceremony that includes
a rake, a shovel and hot rocks is ''just a formula for disaster,''
said Dannette Valdez, a deputy attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   Sweat lodges are used in some American Indian religious
ceremonies to purify the spirit. Participants sit within an
enclosed structure and pray while water is poured over fire-heated
rocks.
</P>
<P>
   Walker agreed that prison officials have legitimate security
concerns and said they have given Rich the same treatment as
inmates of other faiths.
</P>
<P>
   Rich's lawyers are appealing the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Rich was convicted of killing three women and a girl and
attacking five other women. He is scheduled to die early Wednesday.
Gov. Gray Davis on Friday turned down a request for clemency.
</P>
<P>
   In court papers, Rich said the ceremony was ''critical for
making amends and preparing to meet my Maker, my ancestors and
those persons I have harmed during my time on the earth.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-13-00 2125 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000313.0210 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 21:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chavez Rejects Press Freedom Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- President Hugo Chavez on Monday
rejected a report by the InterAmerican Press Association
criticizing his government's performance in respecting press
freedoms.
</P>
<P>
   In its annual meeting in Cancun, Mexico, over the weekend, the
IAPA expressed concern about a provision in Venezuela's new
constitution, pushed through by Chavez, requiring the news media to
publish ''truthful information.''
</P>
<P>
   While acknowledging that Venezuela respects ''in a generic way''
basic press freedoms, the report criticized Chavez's ''constant
threats and insults against the print media and their editors and
directors.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Freedom to criticize is respected absolutely,'' Chavez told
reporters in Caracas, adding: ''I'm not going to lose any sleep
over this.''
</P>
<P>
   Chavez reiterated earlier statements saying certain elements in
the media have ''manipulated and blackmailed in the name of freedom
of expression.''
</P>
<P>
   Chavez, a former army paratrooper who staged a failed coup
attempt 8 years ago, became president in February 1999 promising to
rule in favor of the poor. His leftist coalition has transformed
Venezuelan politics, virtually eliminating the traditional parties
that ruled Venezuela during four decades of democracy.
</P>
<P>
   An IAPA mission in November traveled to Venezuela to express
concern about the new constitution's ''truthful information''
clause, saying it could be used to squelch press freedom in the
South American nation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
