<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 21:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Official: Drug Arrest Well Planned  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- The arrest of a major Mexican drug suspect
last weekend was well-planned, not the result of a chance weapons
check, a human rights official involved in the case said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Mexican attorney general's office said that Jesus Labra was
arrested after he was spotted with a .38-caliber pistol during a
check for illegal weapons among spectators at a youth football game
in the border city of Tijuana. Labra is suspected of being a leader
of the Tijuana-based Arrellano Felix drug organization.
</P>
<P>
   But Victor Clark Alfaro, president of Tijuana's Binational
Center of Human Rights, said the arrest was the result of a
well-planned operation. Clark Alfaro was in the police station
where Labra had been detained to assure Labra's safety.
</P>
<P>
   ''The operation was planned in Mexico City with federal agents
there working in coordination with military officials here,'' he
said in a telephone interview from Tijuana.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear how the case against Labra would be affected if
the arrest had been well-planned instead of a chance weapons check.
Labra's attorney, Gustavo Galvez Reyes, has accused authorities of
arresting his client without a warrant, but Labra did face a court
order to testify on possible drug charges.
</P>
<P>
   Labra, about 50 years old, was a prominent businessman in
Tijuana a decade ago before rumors linking him to the Arellano
Felix brothers arose and he dropped out of public view.
</P>
<P>
   The Mexico City daily Reforma said Labra was married to an aunt
of the brothers and had been a key figure in the gang since it
began to take over narcotics trafficking in the area at the start
of the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Numerous local press accounts said Labra was arrested Saturday
when heavily armed men in civilian clothes charged directly at
Labra on school grounds where a football game involving Labra's son
was being played.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general's office said in a statement Sunday that
when soldiers inspecting for weapons tried to question Labra, he
tried to escape and was subdued by soldiers, it said.
</P>
<P>
   Galvez Reyes, Labra's attorney, claimed that agents from the
U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration participated in the arrest.
Terry Parham, chief spokesman for the DEA, said in a telephone
interview from Washington that the agency had no role in the
investigation or arrest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
