<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FCC Seeks Airwaves Trading System  </HEADLINE>
By KALPANA SRINIVASAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- With the proliferation of cellular telephones,
pagers and other wireless devices, federal regulators that oversee
the nation's airwaves are devising ways to utilize it more
efficiently. They are looking at plans that treat airwaves as
commodities to be bought and sold on the open market -- a shift from
the traditional licensing process.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Communications Commission has laid out various steps
they are taking to better utilize existing portions of the
airwaves, and is looking to create a secondary market so that
companies can have access to slices of the airwaves being held by a
licensee but not in use.
</P>
<P>
   One way to achieve this is to encourage license holders that
aren't using all of their frequencies to post that availability on
a Web site for other interested companies.
</P>
<P>
   FCC officials say they are ultimately looking to set in place a
system that fuels innovative uses and let the marketplace determine
the value of the frequencies.
</P>
<P>
   Moving toward this secondary market for frequencies, the FCC
created last week a new class of commercial licensees called
''guard band managers'' in anticipation of an upcoming auction.
These managers will receive their licenses through the normal
bidding process, but could turn around and lease slices of the
airwaves to commercial service providers or third parties.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is an innovative and efficient approach to licensing,''
FCC Chairman William Kennard said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the current system, the government licenses each user and
regulates what frequencies and signal power it can use. The rights
have never been bought and sold in a secondary market.
</P>
<P>
   But the burgeoning use of wireless devices -- expected to grow in
the years ahead -- has regulators looking for creative ways to
harness existing spectrum.
</P>
<P>
   ''For your industry and for the commission, the biggest
challenge is the dwindling supply of quality spectrum,'' Kennard
told the wireless industry at a convention last month.
</P>
<P>
   In developing this new secondary market, the FCC would allow
licensees who own the rights to a slice of the airwaves to profit
from any surplus, such as parts not in use 24 hours a day. The
commission is expected to hold forums on the issue this spring.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the commission also will begin looking into a new
technology called software defined radio, that also helps to make
more efficient use of unused portions of the airwaves. Using a
system akin to a computer chip, these radios can find frequencies
that are not being utilized, and then make the necessary
adjustments so those frequencies can be used by the device.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if several broadcasters are covering the same
sporting match, they could use software defined radios to seek out
frequencies that perhaps taxi drivers in the area are not using,
FCC officials said.
</P>
<P>
   It could be several more years before consumers benefit from the
technology -- but ultimately it will make it easier for them to
access the airwaves when they want to without running into
congestion.
</P>
<P>
   The FCC also is expected to auction frequencies this spring that
are particularly good for delivering wireless Internet service to
home and handheld computers. These frequencies currently belong to
analog TV broadcasters using channels 60 to 69. Those broadcasters
will eventually shift to digital and have to give up those analog
channels, but that could take years.
</P>
<P>
   Kennard is urging broadcasters currently occupying those analog
channels to voluntarily negotiate deals with the auction winners so
that the airwaves can start being put to use to provide wireless
data and other services as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Federal Communications Commission site:
http://www.fcc.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
