<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Monday, March 13, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
U.S.-China Trade Deal To Be Detailed
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Bowing to congressional criticism about secret trade
deals, Clinton administration officials said they will release tomorrow the full
text of its market-opening agreement with China. In a US-China deal reached in
Beijing in November, China agreed to remove barriers that American exporters
have long complained are keeping billions of dollars of their products out of
the Chinese market. In return, the Clinton administration said it would support
China's entry into the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
No West Bank Withdrawal Date Set
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Palestinian and Israeli negotiators failed to reach
agreement Monday on the timing of an Israeli withdrawal from part of the West
Bank, but Israel reportedly softened its position on a key Palestinian demand to
include Jerusalem suburbs as part of the withdrawal. Palestinians expect Israel
to carry out an overdue troop withdrawal from 6.1 percent of the West Bank,
release at least 150 Palestinian prisoners and conclude an agreement on the
opening of a second land route for Palestinians between the Gaza Strip and the
West Bank. Israel TV said Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak would present the
withdrawal maps to his security Cabinet for approval Wednesday.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Spain Conservatives Win in Landslide
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MADRID, Spain (AP) -- The ruling conservatives won a landslide victory in
general elections that gave Spain its strongest right-leaning government and
weakest opposition in a generation. The sweeping win by the Popular Party of
reformer Prime Minister Jose Maria Aznar appeared to put an end to a long-held
notion that endured through Aznar's first 4-year term: that Spain was basically
a center-left country. Sunday's vote dealt a crushing defeat to the left. The
vote gave Aznar 183 seats in the 350-seat Congress of Deputies, a gain of 27
from the last legislature.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gore and Bush Campaign in South
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- Florida and the other five primaries of tomorrow's Southern
''Super Tuesday'' have been rendered all but meaningless since Bill Bradley and
John McCain dropped their campaigns, but Democrat Al Gore and Republican George
W. Bush -- the two remaining major candidates -- dueled over which of them has
the makings of a president. In Florida, Gore pressed Bush to drop TV ads
''selling candidates the way dog food and soap suds are sold.'' Bush, who made
stops in Mississippi and Louisiana, embraced congressional Republicans after
months of keeping his distance, urging them: ''Be patient, help is on the way.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Study: Estrogen Won't Block Heart Disease
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) -- Challenging a medical doctrine that has stood for two
decades, a study found no evidence that estrogen supplements protect older women
from heart disease. The findings are likely to confuse doctors and patients
alike about the already complicated decision of whether to take estrogen for
many years after menopause. That belief has been a centerpiece of women's health
care since the 1980s and has helped make the estrogen pill Premarin the most
widely prescribed medicine in the United States.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Aetna Stock Sinks 9 Pct.
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Investors dumped shares of beleaguered Aetna Inc. today, a
day after the nation's largest health insurer rejected a $10 billion takeover
bid and unveiled plans to split its health care and financial services
businesses into two publicly traded companies. Aetna, hurt by rising medical
costs, several class-action lawsuits and cold relations with doctors and
hospitals, said it plans to divide the company by the end of the year. The
Hartford, Conn.-based Aetna's stock slipped 9 percent, dropping $5.25 to $50.75
on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Rise
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks rose slightly Tuesday amid continued fears of
possible central bank intervention. The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average
gained 28.39 points to 19,218.32 in early trading. In New York, the Nasdaq on
Monday fell 141.38 to close at 4,907.24, its fourth-worst point drop ever. The
Dow Jones industrial average rose 18.31 to 9,947.13, reversing an early loss of
190.49.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Injured Martin Tops AP All-Americans
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Cincinnati center Kenyon Martin, who will miss the NCAA
tournament because of a broken leg, got the most votes today for the AP
All-America basketball team. Iowa State forward Marcus Fizer was second. Duke,
Michigan State, Stanford and Arizona held the top four spots in the final AP
men's basketball poll as well as in the NCAA tournament.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by BRADLEY FOSS
</SUBHEAD>
