<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Deadly Pedophile Sentenced To Death  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) -- A convicted pedophile and killer
was sentenced to death Monday for the murder of two young sisters
he strangled after he raped one of them.
</P>
<P>
   The Howard Steven Ault case led to a new Florida law expanding
public access to information on convicted sexual predators.
</P>
<P>
   Circuit Judge Marc Gold accepted jurors' September
recommendation that Ault be sentenced to death for the 1996
slayings.
</P>
<P>
   Ault was convicted Aug. 11 of first-degree murder in the deaths
of DeAnn Mu'min, 11, and her 7-year-old sister, Alicia Jones. Ault
raped the older girl.
</P>
<P>
   Ault, 33, also was convicted on two counts of capital sexual
battery, kidnapping and aggravated child abuse.
</P>
<P>
   He was on supervised community release for a 1988 sex crime when
he befriended the girls' mother and picked the children up from
school one day, promising them candy.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of Ault's case, legislators passed a bill in 1997
tightening loopholes on public listings of registered sexual
predators and adding several new measures, including providing
photos of convicted sexual offenders on request.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
