<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Toyota Sets Up S. Korea Subsidary  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Toyota Motor Corp. has set up a sales subsidiary in
South Korea and become the first Japanese automaker to begin
full-scale operations in the country, the company said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   It marks the first time Japanese-made cars will be sold in South
Korea other than on a trial basis, said Toyota spokesman Koki
Konishi.
</P>
<P>
   Toyota made the move after the South Korean government lifted an
import ban on automobiles from Japan in July, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The new Toyota Motor Korea Co., set up in Seoul recently, is
capitalized at $7.4 million and wholly owned by Toyota Motor.
</P>
<P>
   Toyota Motor Korea plans to kick off sales activities in January
of next year, with a sales target of 800 Lexus models in its first
12 months. It will initially employ 18 local workers, Konishi said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Toyota began selling its U.S.-made Avalon and Camry
models in South Korea on a trial basis but sales were meager,
Konishi said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
