<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 22:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Young, Old, Borges Win Book Awards  </HEADLINE>
By HILLEL ITALIE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Honoring the young and the old, the living and
the dead, the National Book Critics Circle gave awards Monday night
to a 30-something novelist, an octogenarian poet and the late
Argentine writer Jorge Luis Borges.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Lethem won the fiction prize for ''Motherless
Brooklyn,'' the story of an orphan with Tourette's syndrome who
grows up to be a detective. Lethem has written several previous
books, including the crime novels ''Amnesia Moon'' and ''Gun, With
Occasional Music.''
</P>
<P>
   ''After the ceremony I'm being taken out to dinner by my
publisher and I'll probably spend the whole meal pinching myself,''
said Lethem, who turns 36 this year and whose book already has been
optioned for a movie, with Edward Norton expected to play the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Among the fiction finalists were the acclaimed South African
writer J.M. Coetzee, whose novel ''Disgrace'' already had won
Britain's Booker Prize, and David Gates, a two-time nominee and an
admirer of Lethem's book.
</P>
<P>
   ''I loved the language, and I loved the concept. Who would have
had thought of such a story?'' Gates said of Lethem's book.
</P>
<P>
   The poetry prize went to 84-year-old Ruth Stone, for her
collection ''Ordinary Words.''
</P>
<P>
   Borges, who died in 1986, won in the criticism category for
''Selected Non-Fictions,'' a compilation of essays, lectures and
film reviews published last year to mark the centennial of his
birth.
</P>
<P>
   The general nonfiction award went to Jonathan Weiner for ''Time,
Love, Memory: A Great Biologist and His Quest for the Origins of
Behavior.'' Harry Wiencek received the biography-autobiography
prize for ''The Hairstons: An American Family in Black and White.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Book Critics Circle also gave out three honorary
awards, including a lifetime achievement prize to retired New
Yorker film critic Pauline Kael. In a statement read by humorist
Roy Blount, Kael offered a hopeful -- and sardonic -- future for her
beloved art form.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the last few years a number of prominent journalists have
suggested movies are finished,'' Kael said. ''They argue that
people have stopped going because the highly touted ones are often
disappointing or worse.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're wrong, I think. They are assuming people are rational
about going to movies. It isn't just publicity that turns us into
suckers. We turn ourselves into suckers.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Book Critics Circle, founded in 1974, is a
not-for-profit organization of book editors and critics with 750
members nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.publishersweekly.com/nbcc/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
