<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weapons Dug Up in Doctor's Yard  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVINE, Calif. (AP) -- Police found about 20 automatic and
semi-automatic assault weapons and some 50 rounds of incendiary
ammunition inside canisters removed from the yard of a doctor who
killed himself days after his business partner was shot.
</P>
<P>
   The weapons and ammunition were inventoried on Monday from the
remaining five plastic canisters found buried beneath a concrete
slab in Dr. Larry Ford's backyard, said Lt. Sam Allevato. When
police examined the sixth canister on Friday, they found 2 { pounds
of C-4 military-style plastic explosives.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, investigators found hazardous materials in jars in
Ford's home, and weapons and ammunition in 21 plastic containers
beneath a false floor. The contents were taken to FBI headquarters
in Virginia for further investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Ford shot himself March 2, three days after his partner, James
Patrick Riley, was wounded outside his office by a masked gunman.
</P>
<P>
   Riley and Ford worked together at Biofem Pharmaceutical Inc., a
biomedical company formed to market female suppositories to prevent
sexually transmitted diseases.
</P>
<P>
   Ford was questioned in connection with the shooting but was not
suspected because he was in Biofem's office at the time,
investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   Since Ford's death, his attorneys have said the infectious
disease specialist did research on biological matters for the
federal government. The South African embassy in Washington is
investigating reports he provided biological weapons advice to the
South African Defense Force.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
