<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 22:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stars 4, Rangers 3  </HEADLINE>
By IRA PODELL, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Jamie Langenbrunner had two goals and Mike
Modano extended his point streak to a career-high 10 games Monday
night as the Dallas Stars rallied for a 4-3 victory over the New
York Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Langenbrunner's second goal with 8:17 left, set up by Modano,
broke a 3-3 tie. The defending Stanley Cup champions, who trailed
3-1, got goals from Scott Thornton and Jon Sim in the second
period.
</P>
<P>
   Langenbrunner, playing his 300th career game, has 14 goals this
season for the Stars, who won for the 31st straight time on the
road when they score at least three goals.
</P>
<P>
   Manny Fernandez, playing his fourth consecutive game in place of
Ed Belfour, made 30 saves for his second win in as many days.
Fernandez, who hadn't made consecutive starts all season, is 2-2
since Belfour left the team.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour, arrested last week on assault charges, is expected to
rejoin the Stars on Tuesday and be available to play Wednesday
night at New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez kept it tied when he stopped Radek Dvorak's penalty
shot with 29.5 seconds left in the second period.
</P>
<P>
   Dvorak had a goal and an assist for the Rangers, 1-4 in five
games. New York, in 10th place, wasted a chance to jump up to
seventh in the Eastern Conference playoff race.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, who have 11 games remaining, have missed the
playoffs in each of the last two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The penalty shot was awarded, with New York shorthanded, when
Dvorak was pulled down by former Rangers defenseman Sergei Zubov.
On the attempt, Dvorak deked to his backhand, but was denied when
Fernandez deflected the shot with the shaft of his goal stick.
</P>
<P>
   Thornton made it 3-2 at 7:03 of the second when he took a pass
from Joe Nieuwendyk in the high slot and scored his fifth goal.
</P>
<P>
   Sim's fifth goal with 3:50 left brought Dallas all the way back.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas grabbed a 1-0 lead just 1:47 into the game, with the
teams skating 4-on-4, when Langenbrunner scored on the Stars' third
shot.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers came back 14 seconds later when Dvorak beat
Fernandez with a rising slap shot from just inside the blue line.
Dvorak's 18th was also scored when both teams had a man in the
penalty box.
</P>
<P>
   New York made it 2-1, with the teams once again skating 4-on-4.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Leetch drew three defenders to him in the left circle and
fed Mathieu Schneider, who ripped a shot for his eighth goal.
</P>
<P>
   Petr Nedved's breakaway goal 2:49 into the second made it 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars also were without forwards Jere Lehtinen (ankle),
Blake Sloan (leg), Guy Carbonneau (wrist), Brian Skrudland (chest)
and defenseman Shawn Chambers (knee). A woozy Darryl Sydor was
helped off the ice after he slid face first into the end boards.
</P>
<P>
   New York forward John MacLean missed his fourth straight game
with an eye injury.
</P>
</TEXT>
