<HEADLINE> Illinois Priest Ordered To Trial  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   RACINE, Wis. (AP) -- A priest accused of setting up a sexual
encounter via the Internet with an undercover agent posing as a
14-year-old boy was ordered Monday to stand trial on drug charges.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. John M. Furdek, 47, of Villa Park, Ill., was arrested
Feb. 17.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said he had traveled to Racine to meet the ''boy''
at a fast-food restaurant, intending to sell him anabolic steroids
-- a drug associated with muscle-building -- and to have sex.
</P>
<P>
   At a preliminary hearing, defense attorney Patrick Cafferty
asked the judge to rule only on the drug charges. He said he plans
to file a motion for dismissal on the sex-related charges against
Furdek, pastor of St. Alexander's Catholic Church in Villa Park,
Ill.
</P>
<P>
   Furdek was charged with possession of anabolic steroids with the
intent to deliver, possession of marijuana, attempted second-degree
sexual assault of a child, solicitation of a child, attempted child
enticement-sexual contact and possession of drug paraphernalia.
</P>
</TEXT>
