<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 22:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sanwa Bank Said To Join Bank Merger  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Sanwa Bank is in the final stage of negotiations to
combine its operations with those of Asahi Bank and Tokai Bank, in
a deal expected to create Japan's second-largest bank, media
reports said.
</P>
<P>
   The companies will set up a joint finance holding company in
April, 2001 and merge in the fiscal year that ends March 31, 2002,
the Nihon Keizai business daily reported Tuesday. The banks have
combined assets of $971.6 billion (103 trillion yen), the report
said.
</P>
<P>
   The three banks were to hold a board meeting on the integration
Tuesday ahead of a formal announcement later in the afternoon,
national broadcaster NHK said.
</P>
<P>
   The trio currently has about 1,000 domestic branches with some
34,500 employees, the Nihon Keizai said. Over the next three years,
they plan to eliminate about 7,000 jobs, NHK said.
</P>
<P>
   The bank would be third in size worldwide, behind the Mizuho
Financial Group -- to be formed out of the merger of Dai-Ichi Kangyo
Bank, Fuji Bank, and the Industrial Bank of Japan -- and the planned
merger of Germany's Deutsche Bank AG and Dresdner Bank AG.
</P>
<P>
   Tokai and Asahi tentatively agreed last year to combine their
operations under a joint holding company. The deal expected Tuesday
would add Sanwa to the mix.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our bank and Asahi Bank are considering various possibilities
for other financial institutions joining (the proposed) financial
holding company,'' Tokai Bank said. ''But nothing has been decided
yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanwa Bank spokesman Yoichi Fujita also said nothing has been
decided, declining further comment. Asahi Bank released a similar
statement.
</P>
<P>
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange suspended Monday's trading in shares of
all three banks.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese banks are combining their operations to improve their
balance sheets, which are saddled with billions of dollars in
irrecoverable loans from a speculative lending boom in the late
1980s and early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   By combining their operations, Sanwa, Tokai and Asahi would be
able to increase their sources of revenue and fight off increasing
competition as Japan deregulates its financial sector, said Koyo
Ozeki, a senior analyst at Merrill Lynch Securities in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's definitely a plus for the financial system,'' Ozeki said.
''On an independent basis, even one of the best banks such as Sanwa
doesn't necessarily have the ability to survive or win against the
competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Sakura and Sumitomo banks have also said they would merge by
2002 in what would be the world's fourth-largest behind the
Sanwa-Asahi-Tokai combination.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
