<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Monday, March 13, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Congress Urged on Utility Industry
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Energy Secretary Bill Richardson today said rapid change
in the electricity industry is causing reliability problems that could increase
the likelihood of power outages this summer. Richardson said Congress must pass
legislation to restructure the electric utility industry as it becomes
competitive or risk ''more long, hot summers of outages in America's cities.''
An Energy Department report says the transition to competition has caused some
utilities to focus on competing for markets, cutting costs and maximizing
prices, instead of assuring that power is kept flowing.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
U.S.-China Trade Deal To Be Detailed
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Bowing to congressional criticism about secret trade
deals, Clinton administration officials said they will release tomorrow the full
text of its market-opening agreement with China. In a US-China deal reached in
Beijing in November, China agreed to remove barriers that American exporters
have long complained are keeping billions of dollars of their products out of
the Chinese market. In return, the Clinton administration said it would support
China's entry into the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Annan Warns on Iraqi Oil Industry
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Secretary-General Kofi Annan warned in a report today
that Iraq's oil industry will continue to deteriorate, jeopardizing U.N. relief
operations, unless more spare parts are allowed into the country immediately.
The 63-page report details how low oil prices, bureaucratic delays and blocked
contracts have undermined efforts to improve life for 22 million Iraqis living
under U.N. trade sanctions.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
No West Bank Withdrawal Date Set
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Palestinian and Israeli negotiators failed to reach
agreement Monday on the timing of an Israeli withdrawal from 6.1 percent of the
West Bank. However, Israel reportedly softened its position on a key Palestinian
demand to include Jerusalem suburbs as part of the withdrawal. Israel TV said
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak would present the withdrawal maps to his
security Cabinet for approval Wednesday.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Russians: Chechen Leader Captured
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   URUS-MARTAN, Russia (AP) -- Russia said Monday it had finally captured senior
Chechen warlord Salman Raduyev, an elusive fighter who once raided Russia and
seized hundreds of hostages and claims to have set bombs at Russian rail
stations. Raduyev was the first high-level rebel leader seized by Russia in the
six-month-old Chechen war. The Russians say they are questioning him at a Moscow
prison. He was charged Monday with terrorism, which carries a possible sentence
of 50 years, the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Borges Wins National Book Critics Award
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The National Book Critics Circle gave awards tonight to a
30-something novelist, an octogenarian poet and the late Argentine writer Jorge
Luis Borges. Jonathan Lethem, 35, won the fiction prize for ''Motherless
Brooklyn,'' the story of an orphan with Tourette's syndrome who grows up to be a
detective. The poetry prize went to 84-year-old Ruth Stone, for her collection
''Ordinary Words.'' Borges, who died in 1986, won in the criticism category for
''Selected Non-Fictions,'' a compilation of essays, lectures and film reviews
published last year.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Software Makers Plan $9.3B Merger
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   DALLAS (AP) -- Two rivals in the business-to-business software industry said
today they will merge in what they billed as the sector's biggest combination
ever, a $9.3 billion stock-for-stock deal. Dallas-based i2 Technologies Inc.
said it will buy Aspect Development Inc., based in Mountain View, Calif., to
boost its business of linking manufacturers and their suppliers on the Internet.
After news of the purchase, shares of i2 plunged, finishing down more than 8
percent, at $191.18} at 4 p.m. Monday on the Nasdaq Stock Market. Aspect shares
rose $11.81\, or nearly 14 percent, to $96.81\, also on the Nasdaq.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Rise
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks rose slightly Tuesday amid continued fears of
possible central bank intervention. The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average
gained 28.39 points to 19,218.32 in early trading. In New York, the Nasdaq on
Monday fell 141.38 to close at 4,907.24, its fourth-worst point drop ever. The
Dow Jones industrial average rose 18.31 to 9,947.13, reversing an early loss of
190.49.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Devils Beat Penguins 3-2
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH (AP) -- The New Jersey Devils, in a scoring slump for more than a
month, twice opened two-goals leads before holding off Pittsburgh 3-2 tonight on
Bobby Holik's goal off a Penguins player's skate. The Devils, trying to hold off
Toronto and Philadelphia to keep their nearly season-long lead in the Eastern
Conference, had scored more than two goals only twice in 12 games before taking
a 3-1 lead in the second period. Holik scored what proved the game-winner at
17:36 of the second.
</P>
