<HEADLINE> Two Brothers Appear in Bombing Plot  </HEADLINE>
By C.G. WALLACE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Two brothers who admitted to participating
in the 1997 bombing of a fur farm went before a judge Monday, one
to have his sentence reduced and the other to be sentenced for the
first time.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Joshua Ellerman, 21, had his seven-year sentence reduced
by 13 months. He already has served 20 months. He confessed to
breaking into The Fur Breeders Cooperative in Sandy, planting five
bombs and lighting two fires that caused $1 million in damage.
</P>
<P>
   His brother, Clinton Colby Ellerman, 23, was sentenced to five
years by U.S. District Judge Jay Thomas Greene for building the
bombs used in the crime.
</P>
<P>
   The two brothers confessed, which led to indictments against
four others. One suspect committed suicide and the other three men
were acquitted.
</P>
<P>
   The brothers' confessions were the only evidence linking the men
to the bombing and to an alleged prior bombing plot.
</P>
<P>
   The two men could have been sentenced to up to 35 years.
</P>
<P>
   Both men had been affiliated with Straight Edge, a
sometimes-violent group that opposes drugs, alcohol, tobacco and
casual sex and in some cases are pro-animal rights.
</P>
<P>
   The Fur Breeders Cooperative is one of the country's largest and
provides materials and mink to hundreds of farmers in the West.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
