<HEADLINE> Judge Joins San Diego Mayor's Race  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO (AP) -- A Superior Court judge narrowly beat out a
wealthy banker to win the second spot in the November run-off for
the San Diego mayor's seat, a tally of late-arriving ballots showed
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The race between Judge Dick Murphy and Peter Q. Davis had been
too close to call following the March 7 election. Of the 12 mayoral
candidates, only County Supervisor Ron Roberts had won enough
support -- 26 percent -- to clearly advance to the run-off. All three
are Republican.
</P>
<P>
   The second round is needed because no one won at least 50
percent of the vote last week.
</P>
<P>
   Davis initially had appeared to lead the count, but voting
officials had to tabulate some 90,000 absentee ballots and
''provisional'' ballots that needed to be verified as eligible.
</P>
<P>
   The San Diego County voter registrar announced Monday that
Murphy beat Davis 41,874 votes to 41,705 votes -- a difference of
just 169 ballots. Each polled about 15.7 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy said the race had been ''an emotional roller coaster, but
we ended up just fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis, a political newcomer who spent $1.25 million of his own
money on the campaign, offered his congratulations to Murphy.
</P>
<P>
   ''He ran a great race and he was a gentleman the whole way,''
Davis said. ''That's the way it goes in politics.''
</P>
</TEXT>
