<HEADLINE> Pistons 124, Celtics 115  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUBURN HILLS, Mich. (AP) -- Jerry Stackhouse scored 36 points as
the Detroit Pistons beat the Celtics 124-115 Monday night to end
Boston's four-game winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   Lindsey Hunter added 25 points for Detroit, which improved to
3-1 under interim coach George Irvine, and Grant Hill had 14.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Pierce led Boston with a career-best 38, while Antoine
Walker added 30.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit started out strongly, hitting eight of its first nine
shots, including four 3-pointers. That gave the Pistons a 20-6 lead
after just four minutes, and they led 32-23 at the end of the first
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The second period was more of the same, as the Pistons hit their
first seven shots to take a 50-30 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The margin was 72-47 at intermission, the highest-scoring half
for Detroit since it poured in 73 against the Celtics on April 16,
1991.
</P>
<P>
   Stackhouse had 25 in the half on 7-of-12 shooting from the field
and a perfect 8-of-8 from the line.
</P>
<P>
   Boston rallied in the third, and Walker's 3-pointer pulled it
within 11 before a Stackhouse jumper made it 94-81 at the end of
the period. Walker finished with 12 points in the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Hill started the fourth with a three-point play, moving the
margin back to 16 points.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit shot 23 free throws in the fourth quarter, just two
short of the team record. Boston had 21 attempts in the period,
which took nearly 45 minutes to play.
NOTES: Boston played without Danny Fortson, who missed the game to
attend a funeral. ... The Celtics are now 1-17 in the second game
of back-to-backs. ... Detroit's 40 points was its best second
quarter of the season, and just three off their team record. ...
Detroit shot better from the field (68 percent) than Boston did
from the free-throw line (64 percent) in the first half. ... Boston
had held each of its last two opponents under 80 points. Detroit
reached 80 three minutes into the third quarter. ... Three players
-- Stackhouse, Hill and Williams -- took Detroit's first 31 free
throws.
</P>
</TEXT>
