<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 23:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Group Reports Journalist Deaths  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIENNA, Austria (AP) -- Last year proved to be one of the
deadliest yet for reporters around the world, with 87 journalists
and media staff killed while working, a media group said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In its annual report on global press freedom, the Vienna-based
International Press Institute deplored 1999 as one of the worst
years on record for violations of press freedom and urged
governments to respect international conventions on freedom of
expression.
</P>
<P>
   ''Developments in the conflicts in Serbia, Sierra Leone and East
Timor were particularly distressing ... journalists were considered
legitimate targets and killed ... because people did not like what
they were saying,'' Johann P. Fritz, director of IPI, said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia topped the list for the deadliest place to work, with
25 journalists and media employees killed last year.
</P>
<P>
   Columbia topped the year as the most violent assignment in Latin
America, claiming the lives of seven journalists, according to the
report. Reporters also were killed in Argentina, the Dominican
Republic, Guatemala and Peru. Governments in the region also used
legal and economic pressure on journalists, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to armed conflicts, many reporters and editors were
victims of unexplained slayings, as well as assaults, imprisonment,
harassment and censorship, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Journalists reporting on the Chechen conflict in Russia also
faced censorship, harassment, kidnapping and assaults.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-13-00 2328 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000313.0242 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 23:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Finland Marks Post Winter War Peace  </HEADLINE>
By MATTI HUUHTANEN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HELSINKI, Finland (AP) -- Finns on Monday marked the 60th
anniversary of a truce that followed 105 days of fierce fighting
against Stalin's Red Army in the Winter War, possibly one of the
coldest in history.
</P>
<P>
   Finland lost, but the small country's resistance against the
Soviets helped secure its independence in post-war Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Some 23,000 Finnish soldiers were killed, and 45,000 wounded, in
a population of 3.7 million. But Finland's white-clad troops on
skis, which became famous as the ''ghost army,'' proved a stronger
force than expected.
</P>
<P>
   The Soviet Union put its losses at 217,500 dead or wounded, but
Finland estimated enemy casualties at up to 400,000.
</P>
<P>
   Many Soviets died of cold, with temperatures dipping as low as
50 degrees below zero.
</P>
<P>
   The question of who began the war had been contentious until the
breakup of the Soviet Union when Russian historians admitted Stalin
was to blame.
</P>
<P>
   In secret talks with the Finns, Stalin demanded Soviet
fortifications on Finnish islands in the Gulf of Finland to protect
Leningrad, now known as St. Petersburg.
</P>
<P>
   Finland rejected this as a violation of its sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   When negotiations broke down, the Finns still did not believe
that Stalin would attack, though Marshal Carl Gustaf Mannerheim had
mobilized over 180,000 men near the border for ''refresher
training.''
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 26, 1939, Soviet Foreign Minister V.M. Molotov accused
Finnish troops of firing at the Russians across the joint border
near the village of Mainila, in south-eastern Finland. The Finns
have consistently denied the charge.
</P>
<P>
   The peace treaty forced Finland to cede 11 percent of its land,
mostly large areas of eastern Karelia, and more than 400,000
Karelians were resettled in Finland.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen months later, Finland was embroiled in another war with
the Soviet superpower which lasted over three years, this time with
the help of Germany.
</P>
</TEXT>
