<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 23:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Swingley Closing In On Iditarod Win  </HEADLINE>
By MARY PEMBERTON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITE MOUNTAIN, Alaska (AP) -- Defending champion Doug Swingley
was closing in on his third victory in the Iditarod Trail Sled Dog
Race late Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Let's get this thing over with. I want a shower,'' Swingley
said as he led his team of 11 dogs at a fast clip across the sea
ice of Norton Sound.
</P>
<P>
   As long as the shower beckons, Swingley figures he might as well
try to beat the record he set in 1995, when he finished the race in
9 days, 2 hours, 42 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm giving it a little bit of a try,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Swingley decided at the Koyuk checkpoint to make a push to beat
his record. If he can make it to Nome before 10 a.m. Tuesday, he'll
set an impressive mark by pushing the trip below in less than nine
days.
</P>
<P>
   Swingley reached the White Mountain checkpoint at 5:33 p.m.
Monday. His nearest competitor, Paul Gebhardt was about 4{ hours
behind. Gebhardt left the Elim checkpoint at 4:48 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Swingley had a mandatory eight-hour layover at White Mountain
before he could hit the trail again for the final 77-mile leg of
the race. He has been setting a record pace for much of the race
and could pass under the burled arch on Nome's Front Street
sometime Tuesday morning, which would top his 1995 record.
</P>
<P>
   Farther back down the trail, mushers were bunched in a pack,
jockeying for position. By Monday afternoon, eight mushers had
passed through the Koyuk checkpoint, 171 miles from Nome.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff King left Koyuk at 10:12 a.m. He was followed by Charlie
Boulding at 12:15 p.m., Ramy Brooks at 2:14, Rick Swenson at 2:37,
Martin Buser of at 2:38 and Rick Mackey at 2:49.
</P>
<P>
   As Buser, a three-time champion, and Swenson, the only five-time
champion, rested their teams in Koyuk, they talked about what might
have been.
</P>
<P>
   Buser said he was at a disadvantage this year because there
wasn't enough snow early in the season to do much long-distance
training. Swingley has said he trains his dogs by running them 150
miles at a stretch.
</P>
<P>
   Buser said conditions were such that he put in a lot of 25-mile
runs. Swingley's strong showing has proved the value of distance
training, Buser said.
</P>
<P>
   Swenson said an accident just outside the Rohn checkpoint that
injured one of his dogs set him back by a few hours. Swenson said
his team was spooked by two people walking along the trail and one
of the dogs ran into a tree.
</P>
<P>
   If not for that, said Swenson, ''I would have given Doug a run
for his money.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Iditarod Trail Committee: http://www.iditarod.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
